fields.name: Calculus
fields.description:
Objectives
At the end of this course students will be able to ..

... calculate limits using appropriately chosen methods, such as l'Hpitals rule or by identifying dominant terms.
... calculate derivatives, find local extreme values and use these to graph functions.
... calculate integrals using appropriately chosen methods, such as the substitution method, integration by parts or partial fraction expansion.
... solve simple differential equations with or without initial data.
... compute Taylor polynomials and manipulate Taylor series.
... determine if a series converges using an appropriately chosen convergence test.
... write down the arguments involved in solving a calculus problem in a logically correct manner.

Contribution to the general learning outcomes; select from Academic Standards and Procedures (OER), section 2.3.: 2.3.1a, 2.3.2a, 2.3.2b, 2.3.2d, 2.3.2h 

Contents
This course deals with calculus of functions of one variable. In particular we cover

manipulating algebraically with exponential, logarithmic and (inverse) trigonometric functions
determining limits by identifying dominant terms
computing limits using l'Hpital's rule
calculating derivatives of any composition of elementary functions
computing tangent lines to implicitly defined curves in the plane
finding and classifying the (local) minima and maxima of functions
graphing simple functions (e.g. rational functions, exponentials, logarithms and compositions thereof)
calculating areas under the graphs of elementary functions
computing antiderivatives using integration by parts
computing antiderivatives using an appropriately chosen substitution
integrating simple rational functions (using "partial fractions")
determining if an improper integral converges (and compute the area)
solving first order differential equations of separable type and of linear inhomogeneous type
solving homogenous linear second order differential equations with constant coefficients
performing arithmetic with complex numbers
determining if a series converges by comparing to a geometric series or p-series.
determining if a series converges using an appropriately chosen convergence test
determining the interval of convergence of a power series
performing simple algebraic manipulations with power series
Students will also practice exercises in-class to improve their skills.

Recommended prior knowledge
Strongly recommended: Mathematics at exit level Wiskunde B or comparable. 

Registration
This course is only open to AUC students.

Study materials
Calculus, a complete course by R.A. Adams and C. Essex, 10th ed., Pearson, ISBN 9780135732588

 

 

Assessment
Week 6: Exam 1: 27% (LO 1,2,4,7)

Week 12: Exam 2: 27% (LO 1,2,3,4,7)

Week 16: Exam 3: 27% (LO 2,3,5,6,7)

MyMathLab assignments 1-12: 19% (all LOs)

Note that the assessment details may be adjusted; please consult the Course Manual in Canvas for the final overview.

Remarks
Students who have passed Calculus for Economics cannot take Calculus as part of their degree requirements.

fields.name: International Relations: Theory and Practice
fields.description: The purpose of this course is to introduce students to the main theories and issues in the field of international relations. Four major IR theories will be discussed in detail: Realism, Liberalism, Marxism and Constructivism. In addition, students will get familiar with a wide range of IR concepts such as power, hegemony, anarchy, conflict, cooperation, regionalism, terrorism, weapons of mass destruction and globalization, among many others. The course material is divided into four main parts: IR theory, international cooperation, international security, and international political economy.

fields.name: Lifestyle and Disease
fields.description:
Chronic diseases such as cancer, cardiovascular diseases, musculoskeletal disorders, diabetes mellitus and obesity contribute largely to the global burden of disease. Important risk factors of these diseases are within the domain of lifestyle. Scientific evidence shows a clear association between lifestyle factors (e.g., dietary behaviour and physical activity) and chronic diseases. The strong association with lifestyle implicates that the majority of these diseases are preventable or that changing lifestyle plays an important role in the management of these diseases.
A planned approach of disease prevention and health promotion is desirable to develop effective interventions and public health solutions. This approach entails a thorough process from analysing the public health problem, to identifying the lifestyle factors that cause the problem, assessing the relevant behavioural determinants and selecting suitable intervention strategies that are effective and cost-effective.
This course combines methodological knowledge and skills of randomized controlled trials, systematic reviews, meta- analyses and economic evaluation with knowledge on how to systematically plan, develop and evaluate health behaviour change (lifestyle) programmes.
During this course, students will choose their own topic related to lifestyle and chronic disease, conduct a systematic review to evaluate what is already known about this topic, systematically develop an intervention that fills a gap in the literature, and write a research grant proposal for a study evaluating the effectiveness and cost-effectiveness of that intervention. Students will make a video knowledge clip that shows how the intervention was developed according to the first steps of the Precede-Proceed model. The course continuously provides input that can be used to write the specific parts of the research grant proposal. The research grant proposal will be presented in a scientific presentation.

fields.name: Case Studies in Energy, Climate and Sustainability
fields.description:
In this course we will investigate a range of topics that are relevant in the context of the energy transition, climate change, and sustainability. The topics (or case studies) are chosen to be relevant to political discussions, current events, and societal debate and span the sciences (climate change, renewable energy, etc) as well as the social sciences (cost-benefit analyses, post-truth, societal change). 

The theoretical foundations will be studied to the extent needed to understand the particular cases, but the focus is mostly on the application of knowledge and insight in different contexts and situations. Some lectures are based on the contents and information transfer, while other classes are more discussion-based or used to work on certain problems.

fields.name: Social Cognition
fields.description: Social cognition is an interdisciplinary field that examines how people perceive, interpret, and make sense of social information in their environment. This course explores the fundamental theories, concepts, and supporting research related to social cognition, including perception, attention, memory, and judgment processes that influence social interactions. Students will examine how individuals process and interpret social cues, form impressions of others, make decisions about social situations, and navigate the complexities of social interactions. The course will also explore how social cognition is influenced by factors such as culture, emotion, and social context. Implications of social cognition for real-world phenomena such as intergroup conflict, prejudice, and decision-making will be discussed.

fields.name: Corporate Social Responsibility
fields.description:
Have you ever wondered what companies such as Patagonia mean by claiming they have a Corporate Social Responsibility (CSR)? Or why oil companies, such as Exxon or Shell, are engaged by activist investors on whether their business model aligns with the climate targets of the Paris agreement? What do investors mean when they say that pursuing ESG (Environmental, Social, Governance) goals is a matter of value, not values?

In this course, we will analyse whether corporations can and should expand their goal from only maximizing shareholder wealth to also considering the impact of their  activities on different stakeholders. Framing the analysis as a legal and economic problem, we will discuss: a) the impact of corporations on social welfare; b) whether the interests of shareholders and other stakeholders can be reconciled; c) the concrete meaning of CSR in corporate governance and the role of corporate law therein.

fields.name: International Sustainable Development
fields.description:
This course addresses the global agenda for Sustainable Development (SD) and its implication for different countries and local communities in the Global South. Complex and fast socioenvironmental changes call for urgent societal transformations to sustainability; however, the way sustainable development has been conceptualized and implemented in different parts of the world requires a more critical examination. Students will be exposed to academic, policy and professional debates related to the development and sustainability nexus. Through interdisciplinary lens, the course will contrast the North-centric perspective to Sustainable Development with counter-narratives emerging from Indigenous and peasant communities, feminist and youth movements, and other subaltern groups.

The course content will be grounded in real-life cases in which multi-dimensional, cross-cultural and cross-scalar aspects of SD will be addressed. Particular attention will be given to the tensions and contrasts between the Global North and Global South in the sustainable development narratives, policies and practices, such as inequalities, colonial legacies, ontologies, ethical considerations and dependence relations. With focus on the Global South context (and Latin America as case study), students will explore how recent global perspectives grounded on sustainable development narratives such as SDGs, Green Economy and Building Back Better influence national and local practices, and how alternative views emerging from subaltern groups such as Rights of Nature, the Commons, and Degrowth influence practices at broader scales.

fields.name: Decolonisation in Historical Perspective
fields.description:
This course offers an approach to decolonization from a historical and philosophical perspective. The interaction between the historical process of decolonization , ideologies and theoretical concepts will be at the core of the course. Using an interdisciplinary lens, decolonization will be discussed from a local, regional, national and international level. By using foundational texts that were written in the different stages of decolonization, including Aim Csaire, WEB Du Bois, Frantz Fanon, Rabindranath Tagore, and others, the courses aim is to engage students with contemporary perspectives in order to deepen their understanding of the different periods.

Understanding decolonization as an ongoing process, the course will also discuss the impact and continuous influence of colonialism in our present day world. Here the work Stuart Hall, Paul Gilroy, Samir Amin, Gayatri Chakraborty Spivak, Charles Mills, Linda Martn-Alcoff and others will be used to understand afterlives of colonialism.

fields.name: Criminal Justice Systems
fields.description:
The course introduces students to criminal justice from a legal and a sociological perspective. The course comprises both a solid introduction to the legal underpinnings of criminal justice systems, and a more empirical introduction to their actual functioning and how different societies deal with criminal behavior. The course is relevant to students focusing on the law track, the sociology track and the IR track. In the first part of the course we will discuss the various criminal justice systems (common law and civil law/ national and international) and what their general aims are as well as basic concepts and will focus more particularly on the Dutch criminal justice system as an example. We will then look into several criminological and victimological issues and discuss comparative issues and try to understand why countries have different criminal justice systems. In the second part of the course we will focus on substantive criminal law. We will look into the jurisdiction principles as well as the general principles of criminal law such as the principle of legality and the ne bis in idem principle. We will briefly look into the concept of individual criminal responsibility (mens rea and actus reus) but only in order to understand the basic concept as we will study this concept in-depth in the fourth part. We will also study the way the criminal justice system is set up as well as its various organs. In the third part we will focus on criminal procedural law. What investigative powers do state functionaries have and how and to what extent is the application of these powers restricted by human rights law? We will discuss the concept of the right to a fair trial and the particular difficulties that arise from international criminal cooperation.

In the fourth and last part we will focus on individual criminal responsibility and will study the concepts of mens rea and actus reus as well as the various defenses from a comparative perspective and will look how international criminal courts and tribunals deal with this concept.

fields.name: International (dis)order: Past and Present
fields.description:
This survey course will provide students with a comprehensive understanding of the historical origins, political impact, and future challenges of major European and international institutions, with a particular focus on the EU and the UN within the broader framework of the geohistorical and the changing geopolitical relations in the international system.

We will begin by exploring challenges, ideas and discourses that have their routes as far back as the beginning of the 19th century but became ever particularly relevant in the interwar period to eventually discuss the post-1945 era of international institutions. This will provide the basis for the understanding of the current dynamics surrounding the potential world order transition and its implications for global governance.

We will then specifically consider the UN and the EU. We will discuss their origins and aims, we will examine some key policy areas in which their governance has expanded significantly, before interrogating specific challenges they are currently facing in an attempt to understand their complexity and multifaceted nature. A mix of current affairs, complex theoretical perspectives and geo-historical facts will help us ground our understanding.

The final part of the course looks at the future. Combining insights from the previous sections, we will ask: how do we expect relationships within state actors at the UN to develop? What will happen to global governance efforts? Is the world order about to be restructured? Does globalization mean that we live in a post-national, post-democratic order?

fields.name: Human Stress Research
fields.description:
Without stress, there is no life: stress activates energy and an abundance of biological processes required to thrive. However; with too much stress life becomes miserable! Stress is the Spice of life  sometimes too hot to handle.
A stressor is a real or perceived threat that knocks you out of your balance, and the stress-response is what your body does to reestablish the balance. For each and every individual, how you respond to a certain stressor, how you feel afterwards and what you will remember of this event is the result of your own reference: your genetic background in interaction with your previous experiences, your physical condition, social settings etc. This is the context of the stress experience which ultimately determines if your stress responses are adaptive (beneficial) or maladaptive (pathological). Individual differences are large: an exciting happening for one is a threat for others. Flourish or perish.
In this course, we gain insight in the intriguing phenomenon of stress from a neurobiological point of view, to help us understand the impact of stress on physical and mental health throughout life and how we may ameliorate potential adverse consequences. Various experts in the field of stress research (including clinicians, brain imaging experts, and preclinical neuroscientists) will contribute to this course, together providing a broad overview of the current status of the field.

fields.name: Political Communication and Data Analytics
fields.description:
This course was previoulsy taught under the name Framing in Politics.

Did the media contribute to reduced consumer confidence during the euro crisis? Does coverage of immigrants increase anti-immigration sentiment? Media coverage of politics and economics doen not simply mirror reality, but is the result of choices of and institutional constraints on journalists and their sources. These choices have a strong impact on the way consumers, politicians, and companies perceive the world and how they act: The way that an issue or development is framed in politics or economics (co-)determines consumer behaviour, policy choices, and investor decisions. In this course students will learn how to use automatic text analysis tools and
statistical analysis techniques to analyse the determinants and effects of public discourse. Specifically, we will look at the discourse on immigration and on the economic crisis, and investigate the effect of real world developments on the public discourse, and the subsequent effect of this discourse on public opinion and policy. After this course, students will be acquainted with the recent literature on political communication, framing,
and specicially the framing of immigration and economics. Moreover, students will have experience with state-of-theart analysis tools for both text analysis and statistical time series analysis in R.

fields.name: Comparative Public Policy
fields.description:
Section 1: Theoretical Foundations and Policy Building Blocks

1. Introduction to Policy Analysis:

 Theoretical and empirical approaches to the study of policy.

 Typologies of public policies and welfare regimes. Values and normative theory.

 

2. Policy Analysis Framework: Analytical Instruments and Processes:

 Understanding policy cycles, types (e.g., regulatory, distributive, redistributive), and welfare state typologies.

 Exploring collective provision and responsible sectors for service provision.

 Problem definition, policy issues, and framing.

 Agenda-setting, policy windows, and actors.

 

3. Policy Development and Implementation:

 Policy formulation, categories, and implementation.

 Governance and the rise of the regulatory state.

 Policy evaluation and outcomes.

 

4. Ethics in Policy Analysis

 Consideration of ethical principles in policy analysis.

 

Section 2: Exploration of Policy Areas

1. In-Depth Policy Exploration: Traditional and Emerging Areas:

Health-care policies.

 Long-term care policies.

 Work-family reconciliation.

 Europeanisation of policies.

 Lifestyle policies.

 

2. Comparative Analysis and Learning Across Nations:

 Analysing traditional and emerging policy areas in developed countries.

 Learning from policy success and failure across nations.

 Emphasis on fundamental policy concepts like context, rights, responsibilities, and social class redistribution.

fields.name: Diplomacy Lab
fields.description: Conflict resolution is often divided between peacemaking, peacekeeping, and peacebuilding. The category of peacemaking includes processes aiming to stop outright violence, thus allowing peacekeeping and peacebuilding to occur. This class explores the theory and practice of peacemaking, and the process at its core, negotiation. We will explore both traditional hard bargaining negotiation and the process of principled negotiation, and the difficulties associated with each. These theories will be illuminated by examples from case studies from around the world, and from both micro and macro levels. These case studies will also allow us to investigate how culture and conflict dynamics affect negotiation, and how groups can splinter and divide during negotiation, complicating the process. In an ever more complicated world, peacemaking has become an ever more complicated process, this class introduces students to the basic principles and prepares them to better understand how conflicts come to an end.

fields.name: Migration, Integration and Diversity
fields.description:
By the end of this course, students should be able to:

Appreciate the complexity of the processes of migration from different perspectives
Develop and present persuasive oral and written arguments related to migration and displacement
Critically analyse, from an inter-disciplinary perspective, the challenges of diversity through migration histories and trajectories
Engage in contemporary debates on integration responses from an inter-disciplinary perspective, drawing on insights from historical experiences and current cases
Think critically about policies related to refugees and forced migration and the resolution of displacement crises

fields.name: International Crimes
fields.description: This course deals with two key areas. On the one hand, the development of international judicial institutions tasked with prosecuting those responsible for the gravest crimes: War Crimes, Crimes against Humanity, and Genocide. The course provides students with an understanding of the historical developments that led to the current institutional landscape for prosecuting these crimes. On the other hand, the course reflects on the impact of globalisation on the evolution of transnational crimes, as well as its impact on law-enforcement efforts to govern / manage transnational crime such as terrorism, piracy, human trafficking, or drug smuggling. The first cluster of the course will explore the key questions surrounding International Crimes and position them in the birth of institutions concerned with these crimes during the aftermath of WW2. The 2nd cluster of the course focusses on the ICTY, discussing the context within which the court was established, its proceedings and outcomes. The next section covers the ICTR following a similar format. We then proceed to discuss the broader field of transitional justice and the prominent position of the ICC herein. We will analyse the underlying assumptions regarding the impact of the ICC and a number of other transitional justice instruments on post war societies (especially on processes of reconciliation) and critically reflect on how they play out in reality. The next two clusters of the course reflects on various forms of transnational / global criminal activity - human trafficking, piracy, arms trafficking, and the global drug trade - as well as on terrorism. The final section of the course reflects on the effects of globalisation and technological change upon law enforcement, analysing in particular international law enforcement agencies, and finishing with some thoughts on surveillance and governing through crime.

fields.name: Global Environmental Governance
fields.description: This course critically examines the past, present and future of global environmental governance (GEG) and international environmental law. Environmental degradation, in its diverse shapes, forms and severities, is one of the most critical and urgent challenges faced by modern society. It is fair to say that most environmental problems are, by definition, global issues. Given the closed, interconnected ecosystem formed by planet Earth, and given the far-reaching state of globalization of contemporary society, most local conditions ultimately affect the global. But this dynamic also applies vice versa: environmental problems tend to manifest themselves in local impacts and conflicts. The increasingly global nature of most environmental problems would seem to demand global responses, yet the local dimensions may require different approaches and actors. This course will critically reflect on the evolution of such (global) responses in international law, international relations, politics, and global governance, as well as the more recent emergence of local, transnational, non-state and sub-state governance initiatives. We will build an understanding of how environmental issues migrate back and forth across different governance levels and scales, and how policy responses can be articulated at global as well as at local levels, and how these various efforts can interact, conflict, or create synergies.

fields.name: Mind Reading: Multivariate Pattern Analysis
fields.description:
Cognitive Sciences and Computer Sciences (specifically Artificial Intelligence) are symbiotic fields of research. Many popular models of Machine Learning are based on our knowledge within (cognitive) neuroscience, like neural networks and decision trees. Conversely, Machine Learning is an important tool used to analyze neuroimaging data, and help us test established cognitive theories about perception, emotion, and consciousness.

Multivariate (more commonly voxel) pattern analysis (MVPA) is one such tool that is used to test cognitive theories. In popular psychology, MVPA has been mentioned as the first tool that can been used by academic to predict human experience while only considering neural activity, otherwise known as mind reading.

In this course, student will take a critical look at methods that are used within cognitive neuroscience, and aim to reproduce a research finding using the aforementioned MVPA methodologies.

fields.name: The Empathic Brain
fields.description:
While we watch a movie, we share the experiences of the actors we observe: our heart for instance starts beating faster while we see an actor slip from the roof of a tall building. Why? Specific brain areas are involved when we perform certain actions or have certain emotions or sensations. Interestingly, some of these areas are also recruited when we simply observe someone else performing similar actions, having similar sensations or having similar emotions.

This course will give students different perspectives on empathy and bring students in touch with empathy research in different paradigms and methodologies. Student will learn about different dimensions of empathy, why we are more empathetic to our ingroup, how we regulate emotions empathetically, and how we coregulate visceral experience with our loved ones.

Students will also learn to specialize, both in terms of topics (4 topics mentioned above) as well as in neuroimaging techniques (EEG, eyetracker, & psychometrics). They will learn how their respective specializations can bring unique additive value, as well as how their focusses combine to form well-supported psychological theory.

fields.name: The History of Ideas
fields.description:
The History of Ideas in the World

The course will unpack how different world philosophies have thought about the self and its relation to the world. We will particularly focus on the ontological, existential and moral impact of these ideas on personal and group identities as well as on other-than-human worlds. Rather than offering an exhaustive survey of different world philosophies, the course will attend to:

the specific ways in which knowledge about the self and world is generated from within these philosophies and
the claims sustained about its scope.
The course provides a hand-on approach to methodologies that inform historiographies. The skills acquired will enable students to understand how the past, the present and the future are interlinked in complex ways and enable to take an informed stand on contemporary public debates.

fields.name: Data Futures Lab
fields.description:
Infrastructure sets the invisible rules for society (Keller Easterling)

Data Futures Lab is an intensive interdisciplinary lab course enabling students to produce research and analysis informing policy-making in the area of digital technology development and data governance at the municipal level. 

This course is a collaboration of AUC with the IN-SIGHT.it research project (UvA) and Amsterdam-based centre for critical technology innovation, Waag. This will ensure active student involvement in current research activities as well as civic initiatives in the city itself.

The course will explore the social, political and ethical dimensions of a datafying society looking at digital technology development and deployment within urban spaces, in particular Amsterdam. A central question throughout will be how to design, standardize, implement, and maintain digital urban infrastructures in the public interest.

The course will first start with the introduction of key theoretical concepts and approaches from the disciplines of computer science, urban geography, science and technology studies, law, political sciences and international relations. This will help students make sense and interrogate interactions between emerging technologies and society, locally and globally, that together mark the digital transition. 

Having gained a theoretical foundation, the course will thus focus on how values are entangled with technology in different ways and what that means for society. The examples throughout the course will stem from, and be applicable to the urban environment, introducing a global analytical lens to contextualize the topic before introducing a specific focus on the current developments in the city of Amsterdam.

On the basis of the foundational theoretical knowledge base, students will critically engage in ongoing research activities and with a range of civic actors that are working in Amsterdams own data and technology ecosystem.

Concretely, the students will be analyzing and evaluating different aspects of the digital policies of the municipality of Amsterdam. At the end of the course, the findings will be presented to the alderman and invited councillors.

fields.name: Medical Anthropology
fields.description:
This course introduces medical anthropology to unpack how health, body, healing, and medicine shape individuality, societies and politics of everyday lives. The course asks how bodies, health, and illness are situated in a globalized world that is becoming increasingly complex and interconnected?  Where does medical anthropology begin and end with regard to the medicalization of social life?

The course especially highlights the interdisciplinary and transdisciplinary configuration of medical anthropology. Therefore, it showcases the contributions of epidemiology, biomedicine, history, psychology and sociology to the formation of this subdiscipline. This course is not a comprehensive overview of medical anthropology therefore, it focuses on certain themes that are pressing in medical anthropology. The course is critical and remains assertively partisan to the medicalization of bodies, Eurocentric construction of shame, restrain, and dominated bodies. Therefore, decolonizing bodies and anthropologies remain the central inspiration of this course and each lecture.

The course content, readings, and assessments follow these themes: trauma, mental health, disabilities, and sexualities.

fields.name: Brain and Cognition
fields.description:
The goal of this course is to deepen understanding of the neurobiology of the mind and the aetiology of mental disorders. Students will be encouraged to critically analyze the impact of neurobiology, mental well-being and (psychiatric) brain conditions/disorders on society.

To most of us, the mind constitutes as the very essence of our identity. However, where to draw the line between normal and abnormal, well and ill, an eccentric personality and a schizotypal one, an active, creative fast-thinking personality and ADHD?

This course will explore the neurobiology of the mind. First, students will be provided with a concise overview of the structure and function of the human brain and will be introduced to the basics of neural communication (electrical signaling and synaptic transmission). Second, the focus will be on key concepts in cognitive neuroscience such as perception and emotions. Next, the healthy mind will be the focus. What is the current state of neurobiological research into behavioral interventions to increase brain health and mental well-being?

Furthermore, a selection of relevant topics will be covered in depth: the neurobiology of sexual orientation, gender identity and the neurobiology of antisocial behaviour, and creativity and mental conditions.

The final part of this course is about the aetiology of mental conditions, such as ADHD, depression, and schizophrenia, with special attention for the nature-nurture discussion. Students will be challenged to critically reflect on the boundaries between normality and abnormality and the implications for society.

fields.name: Sustainable City
fields.description:
Nowadays, urban areas account for half the worlds population. Over the next two decades, they will house nearly all of the worlds net population growth: 1.4 million people are being added to urban areas each week. By 2050, over 70% of the total world population is expected to live in cities.

All these different people with different interests exert strong pressure on how to optimally use the limited amount of land available. In finding this optimal use important trade-offs are to be made between the various aspects of the three pillars of sustainability: environmental, social, and economic.

On the one hand, cities are engines of national and global growth. Urban areas generate around 80% of the global Gross Domestic Product (GDP). They also offer less car dependency due to higher accessibility of amenities and opportunities for public transportation. On the other hand, cities are also associated with around 70% of global energy consumption and energy-related greenhouse gas emissions, more crime, noise and air pollution and fewer opportunities for social mobility for children from low-income households compared to rural areas.

These issues give rise to a series of interesting and relevant questions, which we will address throughout the course:

First, we need to understand the economics and geography of cities. Why do people and firms want to concentrate in highly dense, expensive and vulnerable parts of the world? What explains the location of cities?

Second, we need to understand the extent to which urbanization is a sustainable form of organization of economic activities. How does urbanization influence different aspects of sustainability? More specifically, those that are related to productivity, building, transport, social mobility and green space in urban areas.

Third, we need to understand the kinds of urban policy frameworks required to make cities productive, resilient, inclusive, cleaner, quieter and safer.

fields.name: Econometrics
fields.description:
Good policy making requires understanding the impact of policies. How can we evaluate the effects of labor market policies? How can we measure the effectiveness of foreign aid programs? How can we identify which types of education are best for reaching learning goals? This course aims to answer such questions by offering an introduction to causal data analysis. Well cover a range of modern econometric techniques that are widely used in applied micro-economic research.

The first half contains basic econometrics, including linear regression models, hypothesis testing and coefficient interpretation. Considerable attention will be spent on omitted variable bias and selection bias, and how these concepts relate to the difference between correlation and causality. The second half moves through popular techniques that establish causality: Randomized Controlled Trials, Instrumental Variables, Regression Discontinuity and Panel Data models. Diverse applications in labor economics, health economics and development economics are discussed as illustrations. The focus of the course is applied rather than theoretical and students will make data assignments, in which theyll learn how to implement these techniques in R.

fields.name: Introduction to Geographic Information Systems
fields.description:
This course provides a theoretical and practical basis for utilizing Geographic Information Systems (GIS) and Remote Sensing for the analysis of environmental problems. The course is primarily directed to the natural sciences, but the techniques can also be applied to the social sciences (such as urban planning).
Introduction lectures will emphasize on general principles and theory in geospatial analysis techniques, applications in remote sensing and GIS project design  oriented to the exercise of that day.
The lab work includes specific techniques and tools such as georeferencing, digitizing, topology and data formats, geodatabases and map visualization and presentation.
Spatial analysis focuses on the analysis of digital elevation models, use of map algebra and supervised image classification techniques for the monitoring of land use / land cover change and biomass estimation based on remote sensing information.
Students are expected to complete a project on an approved geospatial topic that is relevant to modern society, such as the effects of climate change on land degradation occurrence of natural hazards and/or land use change.

fields.name: Environmental Law and Policy
fields.description:
There are very few issues that affect our daily lives, our future and that of the planet as profoundly and as visibly as environmental degradation. This course will explore the emergence and evolution of law and policy approaches designed to address contemporary environmental challenges in a multi-level context, with a particular focus to the level of the European Union (EU) and its Member States. We will examine how the unique and complex nature and framing of environmental problems affects the way governments and non-governmental actors, respectively and collaboratively, respond to the environmental challenges posed by our modern industrialized, globalized, and anthropocentric world.

Drawing on various fields of study including law, policy, politics, IR, environmental studies, economics, sociology, philosophy, and ethics, this course will provide students with interdisciplinary, multi-perspective knowledge and critical insight into how modern societies respond to environmental threats.

fields.name: Constitutional and Administrative Law
fields.description:
This course will introduce students to the basic principles of constitutional and administrative law that do not seem so obvious today. With the American constitutional system as the anchor and core of the course, we will study both theory and practice of constitutional law from a comparative perspective, also looking at the jurisdictions of The Netherlands, Germany, France and the United Kingdom. Throughout the course we will also touch on the increasing constitutional dimensions of the European Union (EU) and constitutional role of the European Convention of Human Rights (ECHR), and their influence on the (European) jurisdictions that are the focus in this course.

In the course we will explore basic concepts such as the rule of law, sovereignty, separation of powers, checks and balances, and compare different constitutional models and systems of government. We will study the role of the three branches of government in accordance with the trias politica. How do their powers eb and flow in relation to each other, without violating their constitutional boundaries.

We will the discuss how constitutions are shaped by the societies they govern, and vice versa, as well as the role and importance of judicial review in that context. Moreover, students will learn to read and interpret judicial decisions on a variety decisions, with a variety of methods, and debate the merits and drawbacks of these methods. How could it be that constitutional rights once granted, such as abortion rights, can be interpreted out of a constitution?

Students will be more hands-on and lead the discussions when studying constitutional rights and civil liberties and their protection across the jurisdiction that are the focus in this course. These rights include the freedom of speech and expression; of religion, thought and conscience; privacy and medical rights, like abortion and euthanasia. While the focus is on Western-style liberal democracies and constitutionalism, we will try to incorporate non-Western, non-liberal and non-secular perspectives throughout.

fields.name: Democracy in Crisis
fields.description:
What is the state of democracy today? What are the fundamentals of Western liberal
democracy and are there democratic alternatives to it? Is there a genuine democracy or is
this term devoid of meaning? Should we aspire for democracy? What is the dark side of
democracy? This course provides a theoretical, philosophical and hands-on framework for
exploring these big questions.

fields.name: The Politics of Modernity
fields.description:
We live in a modernor even post-modernworld. Yet the exact nature, beginnings, drawbacks, and benefits of modernity continue to be contested.

 

All sides accept, however, that modernity is characterized by (1) the rise of technology, built on a mathematical or quantitative, materialist understanding of (natural) science and (2) secularization and individualism, that is to say: equal rights to protect individual freedom and individual moral autonomy, producing a contractual understanding of political legitimacy.

 

Modernity is hence generally contrasted with (1) both teleological and supernatural explanations in (natural) science and (2) teleological, theological, or hierarchical understandings of man and society.

 

Discussion in class will revolve around two sets of intertwined questions. First: What is modernity? Is there a specific politics of modernity? If so, how does it differ from the pre-modern? And: What is the relation between modern politics, modern philosophy, and science? Are modern politics the product of modern philosophy and modern science?

 

Behind these two sets of questions we find a third one: Is there a natural order? If so, does the natural order extend beyond science to morality and politics? To what extent can we know this order?

 

Historically, these questions are intertwined with the rise of liberalism. Indeed, the dominant view is probably that the politics of modernity is liberalism (and the criticisms it has provoked). Nonetheless, liberalism is an essentially contested concept (it has no generally accepted single definition). Liberalism means something different in North America than elsewhere. Liberals exist on the left (progressive liberals, distinct from the illiberal left) and on the right (conservative liberals, distinct from the illiberal right). People also distinguish between classical liberals, neoliberals, old school liberals, and Cold War liberals. These different definitions may overlap.

 

For these reasons, to explore the politics of modernity, the course is organized around Stephen Holmess book The Anatomy of Antiliberalism. In this book he defends his own understanding of liberalism against six influential thinkers, critical of modernity, which he (hence) considers illiberal. The organization of the course in this way is not meant to endorse Holmess views. Instead, his book is meant as a point of departure for exploring the politics of modernity.

To avoid strawmen, we will read the six influential thinkers, critical of modernity, in their own words, before we turn to Holmess replies. In addition, we will confront Holmess defense of liberalism with a defense of modern republicanism. Defenders of modern republicanism see it as a tradition that is modern, but not liberal. In other words, in their view the politics of modernity is not necessarily either liberal or critical of modernity: for them the politics of modernity could also be republicanneither liberal, nor critical of modernity.

fields.name: Nations, Nationalism and Modernity
fields.description: This course is an introduction to the multidisciplinary field of Nationalism Studies. We will examine some of the most influential definitions of and theories about nationhood and nationalism: primordialism, modernism, and constructivism. Using multiple historical and contemporary case studies, students will explore the intersections between ethnicity and nationalism, nationhood and statehood, citizenship and identity, empire and nation-state, as well as colonialism and nation-building. Myths, historical narratives, ethnic stereotypes, (print, digital etc.) media, and strong emotions are going to play an important role in our discussions. In several of our sessions, we will examine (anti)nationalist rhetoric and thinking, along with the vexed issue of collective responsibility and guilt. In the context of the increasingly globalized world, we aim at a better understanding of the old and new challenges to nationhood and nationalism.

fields.name: Inequality and Poverty
fields.description:
Chile, Spain, Lebanon, Hong Kong  the year of 2019 has seen a dramatic increase in large-scale protests around the world. The multiplicity of these mobilizations has stimulated the question: is there a common thread among them? Although each has been brought forth by and within a specific local, historical and socio-political context, on a global scale, protesters discontents suggest a broader, shared theme: inequality. At the same time, the variety of issues addressed by these protests, ranging from economic struggles, over gender issues to climate crisis and more-than-human concerns, further highlights the need to expand our understanding of inequality beyond the common, narrow notion of resource distribution disparities. It emphasizes that we need to think of inequality in plural terms of inequalities that concern both humans and more-than-humans and interrogate how this shift further affects our ideas and definitions of poverty.

                  Hence, this course invites students to critically re-think the neighboring concepts of inequality and poverty by examining their constitutive elements, dynamics and interrelations both theoretically and methodologically in-depth. Here, the goal will not be the elaboration of a universally applicable definition of inequality and poverty, but rather the elicitation of an inventory that enables students to engage with the concepts in an informed, critical and inclusive manner. In order to do so, the course brings together readings from sociology, anthropology, political sciences and further offers perspectives from history, economy and philosophy. Moreover, in the last third of the course, students will conduct a mini-fieldwork based on a case study they will have developed throughout the first phase of the course.

fields.name: Contemporary Sociological Thought
fields.description: Over half a century ago, American sociologist C. Wright Mills coined the phrase "the sociological imagination" to describe the distinctive perspective of sociology. What is this "imagination" and how is it "sociological"? In what ways does it impact academic research, public debate, public policy, and even our personal lives?  This course explores these questions through a review of contemporary sociological theory and research.  As we learn about the seminal contributions of Pierre Bourdieu, Howard Becker, Dipesh Chakrabarty, Randall Collins, Michel Foucault, Nancy Fraser, David Graeber, Arlie Hochschild, Bruno Latour, Karl Polanyi, and other important theorists and researchers, we examine deeply topics such as power and inequality, race and class, work and surveillance, capitalism and emotions, as well as suffering and love. A considerable amount of attention is also given to topics like the epistemology and methodology of sociological research, Eurocentrism and its alternatives, and the politics of social ethnography. The key problems of sociological knowledge are examined in light of our increasingly interconnected, but also highly divided and fragile world.

fields.name: Cognition Lab
fields.description:
The course will begin with an overview of Cognition and developmental trajectories to explore the bases of cognitive development.

Consequently, it will link cognitive development to the major learning theories, from classical to more progressive and contemporary theories. Examples include Cognitive Behavioural Theories, Social Constructivist Theories as well as technology-enhanced learning strategies. Students will briefly engage with seminal theorists such as Skinner, Pavlov, Thorndike, Piaget, Vygotsky and Bandura.

These foundational learning theories will support later lectures in the course that focus on creativity, imagination, making predictions and intuitive reasoning and play as crucial elements for active learning, not only during childhood but also for life-long learning. Other topics will include creative cognition development during childhood, play and eyewitness testimonies.

fields.name: Developmental Psychology
fields.description:
During the first part of the course students will acquire knowledge about the main developmental psychological theories on development in infancy, early childhood, middle childhood and adolescence. The themes covered in this course range from physical, cognitive, social and
emotional development, while considering the most important contexts throughout development. Theories will be linked to research practices by discussing commonly methods used in the scientific study developmental psychology.

The second part of the course will consist of a collaborative research project. In groups students will investigate an empirical question in the domain of social or cognitive development in adolescence. They will apply their theoretical and methodological knowledge by formulating and operationalizing a research question, collecting relevant data, conducting basic statistical analysis, and finally writing up their findings in the form of a scientific article. For students with little methodological and statistical background, additional materials will be provided.

fields.name: Cognitive Psychology
fields.description: This course is about the scientific study of cognition  the mental processes that are involved in perception, attention, memory, language, problem solving, reasoning, and decision making. Apart from outlining what we currently know about these topics and how they have led to particular theories about what is going on in our mind, emphasis will also be placed on how we have obtained this understanding. As part of this, the course provides opportunity to get hands-on experience with some classic and contemporary cognitive psychology experiments. Another important aspect of the course is to demonstrate and discuss the relationship between cognitive theory and everyday experience. For example, we will debate on implications for design, and courtroom decisions.

fields.name: Health, Resilience, and Human Flourishing
fields.description:
When we think of how human beings flourish, we inevitably have to deal with the shadow-side: the question of resilience in times of adversity. Adversity is a part of the human condition. Today as before, human beings are faced with challenging circumstances, whether it is political turbulence, economic hardships, social injustice, environmental concerns, or warfare. On a personal level, human beings may experience adversity in the form of trauma, loss, or extreme stress. In the face of growing challenges, the intergenerational debate about fragility versus resilience is becoming increasingly heated. While young people are accused of subscribing to a culture of safetyism, expressed in the demand for safe spaces, trigger warnings and so forth, they respond by arguing that the ability to communicate ones own needs and limitations and the concern for mental health are in fact signs of resilience. The growing importance of the topic of resilience in the public debate highlights the need for further conceptualization and scientific research, and the topic is one that is close to the students own lives. 

This 100-level intensive course on Health, Resilience and Human Flourishing has an interdisciplinary focus, bridging social sciences (qualitative and quantitative approaches to situational variables that impact resilience and human flourishing), science (medical, biological, and neurological approaches to resilience and human flourishing), and humanities (bibliotherapy, philosophical therapeia). On the one hand, the course will explore factors that contribute to health-related resilience at the biological, psychological, interpersonal, and social levels. On the other hand, the course will invite students to contextualize the discussion around resilience and make interdisciplinary connections around this theme.

fields.name: Challenges of Food and Nutrition Security
fields.description: Food and nutrition security is a critical input for the functioning and wellbeing in any society. At the same time, food and nutrition security remains far from guaranteed with 800 million people being undernourished and another billion people suffering from a lack of vitamins and minerals. In this winter course you will first develop a broad and deep understanding of the concept of FNS, both historically and contemporaneously. Next, the course will analyse challenges to ensure food and nutrition security for all now and in the future as well as challenges posed for societies and individuals by food and nutrition insecurity. Special attention is paid to the impact of shocks such as the Covid-19 pandemic and the war in Ukraine for local and global FNS

fields.name: Classical and Modern Anthropological Thought
fields.description:
This course is an introduction to the discipline of Classical and Modern Anthropology, the study of human diversity. The course will provide a brief overview of the four sub-disciplines of Anthropology, namely (1) Social and Cultural Anthropology, (2) Archaeological Anthropology, (3) Biological/Physical Anthropology, and (4) Linguistic Anthropology, before diving into the (member-wise) largest sub-discipline of social and cultural anthropology. Social and cultural anthropology, which studies the socio-cultural variation of human societies and groups (e.g., when it comes to constructions of marriage, family and kinship, gender, and ethnicity), will thus be the central focus of the course.

In this course, we will explore how anthropologists define the concept of culture and the student will be familiarized with key concepts (e.g., hegemony, ethnicity, rites of passage) that anthropologists use. We will cover essential debates and theories (e.g., cultural relativism and functionalism, respectively) that have shaped anthropology and those that still do play a role in anthropology today (e.g., the crisis of representation). We will read (excerpts of) classical anthropological texts that lay the foundation for contemporary anthropology (e.g., Malinowski) and we will read more recent work that illustrates which questions anthropologists ask about modern-day issues and how they try to gain in-depth knowledge. In this regard, we will also pay attention to applied anthropology (e.g., urban anthropology) and how anthropology can be of use for education, business, and governments.

The course will also introduce a range of methodological approaches that are characteristic of social and cultural anthropology like the ethnographic method and (its component parts like) participant observation. The student will learn how classical and modern-day anthropologists have gained and gain insights and knowledge about cultures by means of interviews, conversations, life histories, creating genealogies and entertaining contact to so-called key informants.

In the course, we will also read a much acclaimed ethnography called In Search of Respect: Selling Crack in El Barrio written by well-known anthropologist P. Bourgois. This ethnography on drug dealers in East Harlem (New York) in the 1990s serves as an example of how methods are employed, thick description is generated, theories applied, and ethnographies are written in (urban) anthropology.

fields.name: Introduction to Environmental Sciences
fields.description: The aim of this course is to provide students with the fundamental ideas and concepts in the field of environmental sciences, especially those related to food systems, and with analytical tools needed for a reflection on the nature of environmental problems and its possible solutions.

fields.name: Mathematical Methods for Economics
fields.description: This course teaches basic mathematical skills and techniques that are required to understand follow-up courses in economics. The focus is on acquiring mathematical skills, and occasionally on their applications in economics. Topics include equation solving, differentiation, integration, solving simple optimization problems, Lagrange multipliers. This course is principally intended for Social Science majors who are planning to study economics courses such as Fundamentals of Micro-and Macro Economics (200-level) and the advanced economics courses (300-level).

fields.name: Economic Thought in a Historical Perspective
fields.description: This course presents an introduction to economic thought seen from a historical perspective. The rationale for taking this perspective is that economic theories did not develop in a vacuum. Indeed, economics was once named the science of political economy, to indicate the close connection between political interests and economic inquiry. The key to this course is the insight that economists of the past and present responded to the social and economic circumstances of their times. Moreover their answers were not unequivocal; similar problems called forth different solutions giving rise to competing paradigms and schools of thought. Studying the development of economics in its historical context is the best way to learn appreciate the richness of economics as a scientific tradition. To this purpose, we shall discuss economic thinking from the early beginning to modern times. This course aims to demonstrate how methods and tools emerged in their proper historical context and how they relate to economic policy. This requires an elementary introduction to some of the tools of economics, which will be done in a largely non-technical manner. Applied economic questions relate to major issues in society, such as the issue whether economic science has a solid case in supporting either a free market society or active government involvement in economic problems. We also introduce the work of major thinkers in economics such as Adam Smith, Karl Marx, John Maynard Keynes and Milton Friedman, minds not always in agreement about the proper way to conduct economic research and policy, to say the least. The philosophy of this course is that tackling similar questions from different angles furthers understanding of what economics is all about.

fields.name: Law, Society and Justice
fields.description:
This course offers an introduction to law at the intersection of legal studies, sociology and ethics. For starters, law is seen as a human artifact that is used to establish and maintain social order. By setting and applying legal rules, political communities seek, for example, to organize their government, to punish and prevent crime, to coordinate life, to structure relations, and - on the international level - to cultivate peace, to foster trade, to protect the environment and to strengthen development aid.

This use of law - also called legal ordering - is addressed in three perspectives.

Part 1 offers an introduction to so-called positive law. A body of basic legal knowledge is presented, addressing questions such as: What is the basic structure of a modern legal system? What types of law and legal cultures do exist? How are lawyers supposed to find law? What is the special nature of international law, and why is it generally considered to be a weak ordering instrument? Furthermore, students are trained in a number of basic legal skills: consulting the sources of law, reading a judicial decision, interpreting legal rules and arguing to defend a legal claim.

Part 2 offers an introduction to socio-legal studies. The essence of legal ordering is studied by first tracing its historical development. How did communities first start to use legal rules and concepts? Following Max Webers sociology, it is argued that the concept rationalization is crucial to understand the emergence of modern legal systems. On its path to more contemporary socio-legal research, this part furthermore visits the work of famous thinkers such as mile Durkheim, Karl Marx and Pierre Bourdieu, as well as a number of case studies. Among others, it raises the following questions: Is legal ordering a function of solidarity-types? How does legal ordering lead to social change? Does law contribute to social equality, or rather to social inequality? What factors influence legal decisions taken by e.g. judges? Is legal ordering to be seen as an ideology?        

Part 3 is devoted to the so-called Court of Reason, in which students debate cases that raise ethical dilemmas by playing various roles (judge, counselor and moral advisor). We read Michael Sandels much appraised book entitled Justice: What is the Right Thing to Do? It gives an accessible introduction to a number of influential moral perspectives, as offered by e.g. utilitarianism, deontology and virtue ethics. Students are invited to incorporate what they learn about moral theory in their own reasoning in the Court of Reason.

fields.name: Classical and Modern Political Thought
fields.description:
Classical and Modern Political Thought introduces students to a selection of the core texts in the history of political thought. We call them core textsbecause they have fundamentally shaped the world we live in today. This does not mean that the texts are a sequence of improvements or that they should be read as authorities. Instead, the texts are read in order to help us understand our world, and develop our own thinking about important political questions regarding power, justice, peace, order, and so forth.

According to the classical tradition, the well ordering of society crucially depends on both its citizens and leaders developing a virtuous character. Thinking about politics thus starts with thinking about human nature, human excellence, and the good life. Examples of thinkers in this tradition are Plato and Aristotle.

Writers from the monotheistic religions in many respects agree with the classical thinkers. But there are also important differences, creating challenges for those who have sought to reconcile the pagan classical authors and religious texts. From the Christian tradition examples of such thinkers are Augustine, Thomas Aquinas, and Christine de Pizan; from the Islamic tradition, Alfarabi; from the Jewish tradition, Moses Maimonides.

During the sixteenth and seventeenth centuries, the focus shifts from the moral development of citizens towards the development of institutions that circumscribe the actions of individuals. Thinkers such as Niccolo Machiavelli and Thomas Hobbes argue that realistic politics or a strong state are necessary to prevent civil war. In response, others in the tradition of what would later become known as liberalism, such as John Locke and James Madison, share much of Hobbes view of human nature, but also argue that as much as the state is necessary to protect the citizens from each other, so a constitution is necessary to protect the people from the state.

In the nineteenth century, a discussion of the strengths and weaknesses of liberal-democracy takes center stage, with authors such as Alexis de Tocqueville and John Stuart Mill. We conclude the course with challenges to and defenses of liberal-democracy posed by writers such as Karl Marx, Emma Goldman, Friedrich Nietzsche, Hannah Arendt, and John Rawls.

fields.name: Methods for Social Sciences Research
fields.description: This foundational course focuses on critical methodological literacy and introduces students to a variety of practices of Social Science research. We examine some of the most important epistemological issues of social scientific research by giving an overview of critical questions debated in the early and recent history of social sciences. Moreover, we introduce students to the research cycle and a variety of quantitative and qualitative methods  including digital - to the social sciences. Students will learn the potential and limits of each method through required readings and a variety of practical exercises, learn when which method is suitable and how they can complement one another.

fields.name: Introduction to Climate and Sustainability
fields.description:
The first part of the course is focused on how and why the climate is currently changing and what this means for society at large. The second part is focused on the transition to a more sustainable society.

Part 1: Climate Change ; Topics of study include a brief history of climate science, featuring some of the great physicists of the 19th century who laid the foundations for our understanding. The carbon cycle and the Earths energy balance will be discussed as key aspects of the climate system. We will investigate the observations, causes, impacts and future projections of climate change. An underlying theme is to consider how we know what we know, and to instil a critical thinking approach to statements about climate change.

Part 2: Sustainability ;The current energy system will be briefly discussed, as well as the transition to a low carbon energy system (shared with C&E). We will explore sustainable development from various angles. Examples of questions to be addressed are the following: What economic, ethical, social and political considerations are at stake in this transition? How would continuing climate change be expected to impact different aspects of life? What options do we have to deal with the challenges of climate change? What are the interactions between climate change and development, climate change and conflict, etc? How does societal change occur and how can we influence its trajectory? How can we characterize the different stakeholders and positions in the political and societal debate? How does climate change relate to other sustainability issues (the so-called planetary boundaries)? Welcome in the Anthropocene: an era characterized by profound and long-lasting human influence.

fields.name: Mathematical Logic
fields.description: In this course we study branches of logic -techniques and theorems- that are most relevant to mathematics. There are two sides to the relation of logic to mathematics. On the one hand, logic is concerned with so-called foundational questions about mathematics. Such questions lead to the development of formal systems that formalise parts of mathematics, e.g. axiomatisations of arithmetic, analysis, geometry etc. A central theme here is the expressive power of a logical system, and, in particular, whether the system is expressive enough to contain the mathematical theory at hand, so that properties of the logic immediately transfer to properties of the mathematical theory. On the other hand, logic is concerned with the proof of meta-mathematical results, such as consistency and decidability of particular formal systems, definability of certain notions of interest etc. These results include limitative theorems which establish the absolute limits of the deductive power of formal systems; a good example here is the famous Halting problem which roughly states that there is no method by means of which it can be decided for arbitrary computer programs whether they will eventually terminate on arbitrary input or run forever. Although such a limitative theorem belongs to theoretical computer science, its implications inform any application of computation as we know it. The techniques and theorems that we will study come from the four main areas of mathematical logic, which are: set theory, proof theory, model theory and recursion theory.

fields.name: Legal and Social Philosophy
fields.description: This course focuses on what Jrgen Habermas of the Frankfurt School calls the interaction between system and lifeworld: the way society and its governance structures mutually influence and shape each other. Focusing firstly on the system-part of this interaction, we explore a number of traditional theories about the nature and function of legal ordering. These theories raise the question to what extent it is possible, or useful, to conceive of law as an autonomous normative system. Does it not conflict with the fact that law tends to incorporate and reflect new ideas about, for instance, the environment, privacy and medical ethics? To get a better grip on this social influence, we explore the work of adventurous thinkers such as Ronald Dworkin, Pierre Bourdieu and Niklas Luhmann. They will help us explore the interaction between system and lifeworld more in depth. The final part of the course focuses on what Habermas and others call the public sphere: the social space in which problems of general interest are discussed, and in which collective solutions (as expressed in e.g. legal rules) are found in a communicative manner. Is it realistic to presuppose that citizens are after consensus when they discuss matters in this social space? If not, does it at least make sense to see that type of communication as ideal; as something to strive for? Amongst others, here we will address the work of neo-marxist political theorist Chantal Mouffe, who argues that said ideal disregards the inherent conflictual nature of social life. The final part of the course thus prompts us to philosophize about the role of public deliberation in the establishment of social order.

fields.name: Race, Class and Gender Intersectionality
fields.description: The course will explore the ways in which the categories of race, gender and sexuality, and social class are historically co-constituted and intersect, operating exclusion and violence onto particular populations. Students will be familiarised with intersectionality within the intellectual tradition of Black Feminism in dialogue with Critical Race Studies, Queer and Affect Theories, and Decolonial Thought. We will also learn how other categories are present in the hierarchical organisation of the social world and space, beside and together with race, class, gender and sexuality, also ability, health, and citizenship. Students will be acquainted with the travels and associations of the concept of intersectionality with analyses and social struggles from diverse geographical areas (beside North America and Europe, Latin America, the Caribbean, Africa and the Middle East) and disciplines (Law, Popular Culture, Geography, Health). The course aims to foster participative learning and critical reflection.

fields.name: Debates and Dialogues in Philosophy
fields.description: This will be a challenging 300 level course, discussing styles of doing philosophy (analytic vs continental; cross-cultural vs mono-cultural). The course will center around central topics, such as (Spring 2024 edition) Truth, Knowledge, Freedom, Friendship. These topics will be looked at from different angles and schools. The course will be team-taught to trigger in-depth and research based debates and dialogues within the class room.

fields.name: Cultural Studies of Affect and Emotion
fields.description:
Contemporary Postcolonial Literature  will offer students an introduction to theoretical concepts, texts, and practices in the field of postcolonial theory and literature by examining the interrelations between literary production, representation and the legacies of empire and decolonisation.

The focus will be on literary responses to colonialism and imperialism and to post- and neo-colonial contexts characteristic of more recent times. In the process  combining the close reading and analysis of literary case studies with the study of theoretical texts,  the course also offers an in-depth survey of postcolonial criticism and theory that builds on what students have learned about this field in Introduction to Literary and Cultural Theory and Fictions of Empire. Case studies include works by: Kwame Anthony Appiah, Mahesweta Devi, Chimamanda Ngozi Adichie, Derek Walcott, Marlon James, Ocean Vuong, Rabindranath Tagore, Junot Diaz, Arundhati Roy, and/or works of the postcolonial Low Countries (Neterlands and Flanders-Belgium).

By the end of the course, students will have obtained comprehensive knowledge of the inner diversity of postcolonial criticism and theory as well as the ability to engage critically and in an informed way in the discussion of subjects and themes such as: dynamics of othering and stereotyping; the nexus between power and representation in (post)colonial and multicultural settings; masculinity/femininity, gender/sexuality, subaltern knowledge; minority writing; migrant literature and postcolonial feminism amongst others. The course includes literary case studies written in different languages, to the extent that they are available in English translation, as well as texts originally written in English.

fields.description:
Contemporary Postcolonial Literature  will offer students an introduction to theoretical concepts, texts, and practices in the field of postcolonial theory and literature by examining the interrelations between literary production, representation and the legacies of empire and decolonisation.

The focus will be on literary responses to colonialism and imperialism and to post- and neo-colonial contexts characteristic of more recent times. In the process  combining the close reading and analysis of literary case studies with the study of theoretical texts,  the course also offers an in-depth survey of postcolonial criticism and theory that builds on what students have learned about this field in Introduction to Literary and Cultural Theory and Fictions of Empire. Case studies include works by: Kwame Anthony Appiah, Mahesweta Devi, Chimamanda Ngozi Adichie, Derek Walcott, Marlon James, Ocean Vuong, Rabindranath Tagore, Junot Diaz, Arundhati Roy, and/or works of the postcolonial Low Countries (Neterlands and Flanders-Belgium).
