The course includes literary case studies written in different languages, to the extent that they are available in English translation, as well as texts originally written in English.

fields.name: Urban Anthropology Lab
fields.description:
The majority of today's world population live permanently, or part of their lives, in cities. Cities continue to grow in number and in size: urbanization has reached unprecedented levels. Many scholars view cities as central building blocks of 'post-industrial' society; others link cities to discussions on 'modernity'. Yet again others view the growth of cities as emblematic of the expanding gap between North and South, East and West.
But what does ongoing urbanization mean for the lives of ordinary persons living in cities, and of those aspiring to do so? What are the problems and dilemmas characteristic of social life in the city? This course addresses these questions by presenting a critical review of anthropological and sociological thinking on cities, urban life and urbanization. The course focuses on experiential and organizational aspects of social life in the city, but it also explores how this is embedded in broader societal frames, including the countryside (urban-rural linkages), transnational migration networks, and globalising trade. By taking a comparative perspective (including examples from Western and socalled 'developing' countries), the course surveys the social and cultural diversity in perspectives and practices of city dwellers/urban actors, and discusses different research approaches and traditions to study these meaningfully.

The course is organized around two major parts. In the first part, key concepts and debates from the literature (both theoretical debates and case studies) will be discussed in a combination of lectures and student presentations. In this part, students will also view documentary movies highlighting a particular aspect of city life. Furthermore, an excursion will be organised to the renowned New Town Institute in Almere (NTI). Here students will get acquainted with the Institute's ongoing research projects, and make use of the information facilities of the Institute. In the second part of the course, students will apply the key concepts in their own research projects (group work). They will prepare a design for this project, and carry out anthropological fieldwork for data collection.

Linking this to Capstone projects is encouraged, but not mandatory. Feedback is given during frequent research seminars. The findings of the fieldwork are reported in a research paper, which must include a critical discussion of the literature. The course is thematic, exploring a number of important themes about city life that have come to prevail in academic/anthropological discussions.

fields.name: The Art Market and Culture Industry
fields.description:
Although the definition of art remains open, we can safely state that art works, their makers and public have always been part of social, political, cultural, religious and economic networks. In this respect, the 19th-century concept of Art for arts sake tells us perhaps more about the much-desired emancipation of artists in the Western world from the whims of patrons, guilds and art academies, than about art itself.



Drawing from a wide range of historical and present-day examples, this course will investigate relations between art, artists and the market. How has the profession of the artist and artistic education changed over the centuries? How can we define the relationship between artists and patrons, then and now? What are the institutional role of art academies, art dealers, museums and the government? Case studies range from late medieval commissions of altarpieces to the rise of



the art dealer in seventeenth-century Dutch cities, from the Salon in nineteenth-century Paris to the present-day phenomenon of art fairs. We will also look at museums, from their origins in princely collections to the challenges that current museums are facing, with receding government funding, changing geo-political realities, and restitution claims from both private persons, communities and states. In the final leg of the course, we look at various models of cultural policy and the rationales behind them. Students will learn to look at these processes with an interdisciplinary approach, making use of various methodologies. They will work with key concepts such as social distinction, art worlds, the culture industry, the commodification of art and cultural imperialism to understand the (changing) social significance given to art and the culture industry, and the relationship between art and the economy.

fields.name: Film and the Body
fields.description: The medium of film is entangled with questions around the body, be they in relation to the film-as-body, the body of the spectator, or the depiction of bodies on film. We will wrestle with these longstanding questions through various different approaches. We consider how the film apparatus itself has been theorised as a body: a hearing and seeing mechanism of sensibility. We also trace a phenomenological turn in film studies attending to how the spectators body senses, interacts with, and is affected by film, and what this might tell us about the centrality of the body in spectatorship. Next, we consider the import of the depiction of bodies on screen, from fundamental questions around the attractions of the moving body to interventions in critical animal studies, critical race theory, feminist and gender theory, crip studies, and posthumanism around cinematic depictions of particularised bodies. Questions of the bodys ontology, embodiment, biopolitics, and figuration recur across the course, effecting a wide-ranging interrogation of philosophical and film theoretical debates around the body. With the help of screenings and scholarship that challenge simplistic and normative accounts of film and the body, we will develop a complex and rigorous knowledge of debates around this compelling relation, allowing for your own thoughtful interventions in these ongoing dialogues.

fields.name: Modern Philosophical Texts
fields.description:
This course, offered in the January period, will focus on the work of the French philosopher, anthropologist and sociologist Bruno Latour (1947-2022), especially but not exclusively on his book Facing Gaia: Eight Lectures on the New Climatic Regime, based on his 2013 Gifford Lectures on Natural Religion. In this book, Latour shows how the emergence of modern sciences in the seventeenth century radically changed our understanding of nature. He argues that now that we have entered the Anthropocene, an ecological mutation of unprecedented scale, we need a new way of looking at nature. This book explores how we can come face to face with the Earth as Gaia, as originally proposed by James Lovelock.

In the course we will study Latours Facing Gaia in the context of his philosophical development. Starting out in science and technology studies, Latour later developed his actor-network theory as a way to go beyond philosophical divisions such as subject-object, transcendence-immanence, and human-nonhuman. In 2013 he published An Inquiry into Modes of Existence, in which he presented an experimental metaphysics that puts ontological questions back on the table, as part of the recent ontological turn in anthropology. In Facing Gaia, as well as in his recent After Lockdown (2021), Latour has applied both his actor-network theory and his experimental metaphysics to ecological questions.

The course will also relate to how Latours Facing Gaia is situated with contemporary approaches to the climate crisis, and how his plea for a new Gaian religiosity can be used to make sense of the popularity of various new forms of ecodelic religiosity, especially ayahuasca religiosity.

fields.name: Religion, Secularism and Violence
fields.description:
While 20th century extreme violence (e.g. Word wars I and II, proxy wars during the Cold War, the Cambodian genocide under the Khmer Rouge) was often justified by atheistic or non-religious political, ideological motives (e.g. Nazism, Stalinism, etc.), the beginning of the 21th century brought violence to the world stage explicitly justified on religious grounds. This religious violence was contested by those who dismissed the use of religion as illegal, and used by others to plea for a peaceful world without religion. This course is taught at a moment at which in major European countries (the Netherlands, France and Germany) election campaigns are fought in which the fear for religious violence is a major factor.

This resurgence of religious violence has also triggered new extensive interdisciplinary research on the link between religion and violence in the past and the present. The course will explore this new emerging field of academic enquiry. We will start with an analysis of how violence is part of five world religions (Christianity, Islam, Judaism, Hinduism, and Buddhism) in founding stories, in sacred texts, in rituals, in practices, and in symbols, and how they have dealt during their history with the violence aspects of their religious traditions. In the second part, the entanglement of religion and politics will be illustrated by recent cases in their social, political and cultural contexts (eg. ISIS), and motives (apocalypse, Armageddon, sacrifice and martyrdom, etc.). In the third part other

themes will be explored, such as conflicts about sacred spaces, evil and purification, and blasphemy, next to aspects such as religious violence against women and the use of religion in colonial violence. In the last part we will give attention to new theories that shed new

light on the relation between religion and violence from evolutionary, philosophical and theological perspectives.

fields.name: Media / Environment
fields.description:
Media and the Environment are seemingly at the heart of every pressing issue that surrounds us. As we face, according to Bruno Latour, a profound mutation in our relation to the world (8), we need new arts of noticing, that is more inclusive to different kinds of human and more-than-human world making projects (Tsing). This course will approach this task by exploring the various entanglements of media and environment. 

Firstly, by adopting the definition of media offered by John Durham Peters as containers of possibility that anchor our existence and make what we are doing possible (2), we will explore media not only as technologies of communication, but as environments of being. From the earliest tools humans have developed to the latest discussions on Large Language Models, our writing tools [have been] working on our thoughts (Nietzsche). We will explore the ways in which media not only send messages about human doings and our relation to more-than-human worlds, but are instrumental in the formation of those systems (Peters).

Secondly, we will in turn approach various formulations of human and more-than-human environments as media of life. Whether we approach environments through the ancient Greek taxonomy of elements; earth, water, air, and fire or through the modern periodic table, we can go beyond mere descriptions of objects that are seemingly external to the human lifeworld, and recognize them as the medium through which we imagine and build those lifeworlds. 

Our journey will take us through the oceans and the atmosphere. We will trace the fire that burns at the heart of what we call civilization. We will follow the rare-earth metals, the fiber-optic cables, and the satellites that enable our contemporary communications infrastructures. 

By offering new ways to explore seemingly familiar things, this course is an invitation to think critically about our human and more-than-human environments and our imagined futures on Earth.

fields.name: Poetics of Protest
fields.description: From the Civil Rights era to Black Lives Matter, poetry has been integral to modern cultures of protest  both as a medium of expression and as a means of change in its own right. This course considers the poetics of protest by considering a broad array of poetry and other literary texts in historical perspective and in its specific social and cultural contexts, stretching from the 1960s and 1970s till today. Special attention will be paid to the ways in which poetry and literature have engaged with political and democratic themes (e.g. social justice, racial equity, civil disobedience); to the political and institutional settings and the performance contexts of protest poetry and its audiences; and to the fashioning of public personas in/through poetry and literary writing, such as that of the Poet Laureate, the poet-activist, and the writer as public intellectual. The course will alternate close readings and analysis of poetry, literature, and spoken word performances with the study of critical and historical texts to explore how poetry, politics, and public life have informed each other and how they have been dynamically interrelated over time.

fields.name: Creative Writing
fields.description: This course is a diverse exploration of creative writing as a discipline and an art form. Students will immerse themselves in both the theory and practice of writing creatively.

fields.name: Philosophical Logic
fields.description: The aim of the 200-level philosophical logic course is to provide the students with a deeper understanding of what logic is about. The course is a continuation of the introductory course `Logic, Information flow and Argumentation'. As such, it maintains an interdisciplinary character and it draws connections with a variety of fields such as: philosophy of language, cognitive science, psychology of reasoning, mathematics, linguistics and natural language semantics, computer science, artificial intelligence, philosophy and history of logic. We will expand on the logics covered in the introductory course, namely, classical propositional and predicate logic, as well as dynamic epistemic logic. We will also motivate and introduce new systems, prominent in one or more of the fields mentioned above; for example, the students will be familiarised with intuitionistic logic, set theory, many-valued logics, tense logic, non-monotonic logic and game theory. In each case the students will learn to work within the respective logical systems and use their expressive powers, while asking critical questions about these systems and investigating their applications to various fields. We will explore the difference between the model theoretic and the proof theoretic approaches to logic, as well as study some interesting axiomatisations. In a few cases, a number of meta-logical results will be proven, such as the completeness theorem for classical propositional logic. Special attention will be devoted to philosophical questions surrounding the technical results.

fields.name: National Cinemas
fields.description: If a nation, like an individual, derives its identity in large part through the stories it tells about itself, then cinema is the medium par excellence to narrate those stories to mass audiences on a global scale. In this course, we will study the concept of national/regional cinema as the projection of national/regional character, and as such will be primarily concerned with the question To what extent are the films studied engaged in constructing (or challenging) notions of nationhood/regionhood? Within this broader framework, we will focus on the cinema from Latin(o) America as well as the cinema aboutLatin(o) America, in order to examine its influence in shaping ideas about what it means to be Latin American, and by extension, Non-Western. As such, a significant component of the course will be to analyze the intersections of concepts of nation with those of race, gender and class. Fictional features as well as documentary and based on true events films will be examined with regard to the principles and problematics of cinematic realism while representing the Self and Other. The focus of analysis will be those films considered landmarks of the regions cinema which helped to frame a sense of identity both at home and abroad. By concentrating on a selection of films from industries such as Mexico, Cuba, and North America (Latino indies) which earned domestic and international critical notoriety and/or large box office profits, we will analyze a body of films which helped to define a sense of Latinness on a broad scale. Although this course is not designed to present an anthology of national cinemas, it is intended that the critical concepts and issues raised will be applicable across a wide range of different contexts.

fields.name: Philosophy of Science
fields.description:
This course presents an introduction to key debates in the philosophy of science. The course is divided into three parts:

PART I

- Scientific method: Is there a distinctive scientific method? Or are there fundamental methodological differences between various scientific disciplines.

PART II

- Realism: Do scientific theories describe an underlying reality or are they merely convenient instruments for prediction?

- Scientific explanation: Do explanations in the natural sciences, social sciences, and humanities differ essentially?

- Reductionism: Are the various sciences autonomous or is there a (hierarchical) relation between them?

PART III

- Science and society: What is the social structure of science? Can and should science be value-free? Is a specifically feminist science possible and desirable?

Throughout the course we will draw on examples from the natural sciences, the social sciences and the humanities. Students will be encouraged to apply general philosophical ideas and analyses to their own specific fields of interest, especially to concrete cases from the six themes in the AUC curriculum.

fields.name: History Lab
fields.description:
In History Lab students become conversant with a range of methods characteristic  and defining  of history as a discipline that is eminently concerned with the study of the past. Working with primary sources is vital to the historians research: from archival documents, visual sources, objects and ego-documents to quantitative data, historians may work with a diverse range of variegated sources in their efforts to document, understand and (re)interpret the past, and to transmit information about it to other historians as well as to a wider audience. Given that the range of historical sources is wide and diverse, the selection of skills or skill-sets which the historian needs to obtain is concomitantly broad. In the first half of the course, History Lab familiarises students with some of the methods needed; through a combination of lectures and hands-on exercises and assignments. It gives a sense of their variety and range. In the second half of the course, students will put their newly acquired knowledge and skills into practice in a designated lab project focused on a topical case study selected by the lecturer and giving them inside experience of a current research project in the field. In line with the lab concept, the precise subject and focus of the project may differ from year to year, contingent on staffing and the choice of partner institution(s). 
For the January 2022 iteration of the course we will be working together with the Dutch National Maritime Museum. This Museum emphasizes the strong connection between the maritime world and society as a whole, and more specifically the impact of this on the lives of many individuals. Students will be introduced to the core areas the museum defined to work towards this vision. As a preparation on one of their exhibitions students will advise the museum staff on how the existing collection of the museum can be used to present a multi-perspective view on the (in many cases contested) maritime history with relevance for society. To do so students will research the collection, select a couple of objects, interpret these objects from multiple perspectives, analyse its possible impact on the audience, write a short vindication of their chosen object(s) and present this during the last session (attended by some of the museum staff members).

fields.name: Literary Ecologies
fields.description:
This course offers new ways of thinking about the relationship between literature and science through conceptualizing that relationship in terms of a literary ecology.  Adapted from biological sciences, an ecology is a way of thinking about the dynamics of interconnection, interdependence, attunement, and exchange between organisms and their environment, where the environment, importantly, is understood as active, evolving, and responsive, rather than fixed.  In this course, we will experimentally adapt this framework in thinking about similar dynamics not only within literary and scientific texts, but also in the relationships between them, their impact on each other, and the evolving social, cultural, and political environments which they shape and to which they respond.   

Through drawing on literary and scientific texts from a range of historical periods, we will explore the relationships between scientific discovery (in e.g. psychology, neuroscience, evolution, embryology, energy and climate, astronomy, mathematics) and cultural production and representation. We will consider the ways in which imaginative literature in particular, but also art, cinema, and the media, addresses, responds to, and creates popular science, while also considering works of science and scientific debates which make use of literary strategies. Exploring these literary ecologies will encourage us to re-examine the relationships between scientific discovery and literary communities in order to gain insight into the role of creativity in scientific discourse and the part literature has to play in reflecting critically on scientific developments in a range of historical and cultural contexts.  In doing so, we may also open up new ways of understanding how past and emerging textual environments have been shaped by and continue to shape debates about nature, evolution, climate, technology, and cognition.

fields.name: Documentary
fields.description:
Students will consider the history of documentary filmmaking and the assumed role of the documentary as social vehicle responsible for representing truth and reality, and sometimes dogma and/or propaganda. Notions of defining documentary film will be interrogated, however elusive the term, the mode, etc. The documentaries in this class will be viewed and analyzed as products of their particular social, historical and political contexts. The films will range from the 'canon' as well as experimental documentary approaches to works that remain under the radar to the burgeoning form of interactive-web docs. Questions surrounding objectivity, subjectivity, hybrid modalities, and the use of archival footage, and forms of address and voice will be unpacked throughout this course.



In the second half of the term attention will also be given to more personal and first-person documentary forms, including sub-genres such found-footage and essay films. Furthermore, the increasing documentary turn in contemporary art practices will be explored and to that end, modes of reception as well as their aesthetic qualities will be considered. This course, scheduled in the first semester, will coincide and engage in meaningful ways with IDFA (International Documentary Film Festival Amsterdam) by attending satellite events such as the DocLab exhibition and other special screenings and related guest lectures.

fields.name: Journalism
fields.description: Journalism is changing. As both students and consumers of journalism, you are entering a twenty-first century news landscape that looks nothing like the one your parents (or even your younger selves) grew up with, and will likely look even more different by the time you graduate. Journalism is in many ways in crisis. Politicians regularly use their public platforms to denigrate reporters, denounce media outlets as purveyors of fake news, and flout efforts by the press to hold them accountable. Generalized disillusionment and skepticism with elites in the news media breed resentment and reactionary anger around the world. In many countries journalists are struggling with both economic and political woes. Many newsroomsparticularly traditional newspapers--face a growing backlash from the public, as well as a near-total financial collapse of their advertisement-driven business model. News organizations generally have fewer resources to do enterprise and investigative projects, and the expansion of digital publishing has brought an onslaught of competition, layoffs, and cost-cutting. For all the changes, the practice of journalism remains largely founded on the principles of one long-standing institution: the newspaper. Newspaper journalism continues to influence the skills and sensibilities of professional journalists, who face the daunting task of learning the tools of the trade and adapting the traditional principles of newspaper journalism for a fast-changing media landscape. With the newspaper as its foundation, this class is designed to develop the basic skills of newswriting, and to give you a more panoramic sense of how the news media operates today, the role of the free press in a democratic society, the vicissitudes of journalism in an age of rising skepticism, and the ethical dilemmas that beset many journalists as they try to navigate an increasingly digital, global, frenetic news cycle. We will also turn a critical eye on our starting point of the newspaper and its received wisdoms. Through readings, in-class activities and discussions, and group and individual assignments, students will report and write on a range of local and regional topics in a range of journalistic styles, including short news reports and reviews, long-form features, and multimedia productions such as podcasts. Students will have the opportunity to collaborate with AUCs independent student newspaper, The Herring. The semester will culminate with an intensively reported enterprise project that exemplifies how journalism can serve as a paradigm for exploring the issues of the day. As this is a collaborative, writing- and reading-intensive class students will be expected to actively participate and commit time in and out of class to reading, research, reporting, writing, and editing.

fields.name: Urban Utopias
fields.description:
Assuming that a well-designed environment results in the social, political and economic advance of society at large, humans have always looked for design to improve their surroundings. The founding of new cities and the restructuring of existing ones are shaped by a desire for a better society. Architects and urbanists have thus shaped utopias for good life.

Through recourse to architectural history and theory, this course investigates a range of concepts and ideologies of planning and shaping urban environments. We will assess the conditions under which a variety of design visions were conceived. After a brief introduction in the history and theory of ideal cities and communities, we will focus on a number of key design concepts and theorists that shaped twentieth century urban developments, and their influence today and traces in the past. Urban Utopias will be investigated in terms of their shape and everyday life unfolding in them.

fields.name: Modernism and Postmodernism
fields.description: When in The Notebooks of Malte Laurids Brigge, Rainer Maria Rilke wrote, There is a place within me of which I knew nothing, he anticipates the early twentieth-century modernist fixation on interiority, consciousness and the contours and situatedness of the self.  In the first part of this course, we will explore this interior turn through looking closely at literary devices such as free indirect discourse, the stream of consciousness technique, temporal dislocation, fragmentation, and allusion as well as the social, political, and cultural contexts in which this experimental writing takes shape.  Authors in this part of the course include: Marcel Proust, Virginia Woolf, Djuna Barnes, T.S. Eliot, Mina Loy, and James Joyce as well as Harlem Renaissance authors such as Langston Hughes and Zora Neale Hurston.  We will also look at a selection of Little Magazines and manifestos in the print culture of the period (e.g. Futurism, Vorticism, Feminism, Imagism) before moving on to explore the paradigm shift from depth to surface that signals the advent of Postmodernism in the work of Jorge Luis Borges and Samuel Beckett, before moving on to look at early postmodern fiction (Thomas Pynchon), historiographic metafiction (Jeanette Winterson) and fiction of the postmodern condition (Don DeLillo). Through exploring postmodern literary devices such as metafiction, irony, parody, pastiche, intertextuality, textual instability, playfulness, and self-reflexivity, we will explore both the evacuation of meaning and the multiplicity of meaning emerging from these texts, in turn drawing on them to both situate and test theories of postmodernity formulated by Lyotard, Baudrillard, McHale, Hutcheon, and Waugh.  By the end of this course, students will learn the skills required to read these complex texts, identify formal and stylistic features, engage and test ideas of canon, authorship, and constructions of the reader, as well as situate this writing within the broader twentieth century.

fields.name: Film Analysis
fields.description: This course uses important case studies from film history from between approximately 1950-2000 to engage students with fundamental debates surrounding the pre-/co-requisite Introduction to Film Studies final three major topics: cinematic genres, authorship, and spectatorship. This course expands upon Introduction to Film Studies by prompting students to write historical and theoretical analyses of films, rather than prioritizing a given films formal construction. Moreover, the overarching rubrics of the musical genre, historical models of authorship, and spectatorial theory from approximately 1970-2000 will encourage sustained discussions of recurring themes like feminist and queer filmmaking, genre vs. art cinema, high- and low-culture, cultural hegemony and resistance, etc.

fields.name: World Religions
fields.description: In this course practices of differentiation, and the desire to expel, contain or kill otherness through scientific and governmental techniques are explored. Paying a tribute to philosophical writings on the concept of Self (Human) and Other (non-Human), the course offers various explorations of the disciplinary and discursive constructions of sexual, racial, moral/religious, social, medical and mental difference. The course departs from readings of Michel Foucault and offers a series of critical engagements with the themes of (sexual) deviance and biopolitics. Readings selected from various sociological and cultural studies traditions then introduce fresh perspectives on the classic theme of the norm and the exception/deviation.

fields.name: Sociology of the Other
fields.description: In this course practices of differentiation, and the desire to expel, contain or kill otherness through scientific and governmental techniques are explored. Paying a tribute to philosophical writings on the concept of Self (Human) and Other (non-Human), the course offers various explorations of the disciplinary and discursive constructions of sexual, racial, moral/religious, social, medical and mental difference. The course departs from readings of Michel Foucault and offers a series of critical engagements with the themes of (sexual) deviance and biopolitics. Readings selected from various sociological and cultural studies traditions then introduce fresh perspectives on the classic theme of the norm and the exception/deviation.

fields.name: Ethics
fields.description:
How should we live? What is the right thing to do? Do we (really) have a moral responsibility to others? Are there good reasons to act morally? Does morality have any foundation? Is happiness all that matters? To what extent should moral decisions be impartial? To what extent (and how) is morality shaped by our cultural, religious, political context?

This course in ethics will not only explore these questions in a systematic manner, but also engage with some of the most pressing moral problems in society today. 
As a student of this course, you will have the opportunity to develop familiarity with important ethical theories such as deontology, utilitarianism, virtue ethics, ethics of care, and ethical relativism. You will be introduced to central traditional philosophers such as Plato, Aristotle, Confucius Immanuel Kant, John Stuart Mill and Friedrich Nietzsche, as well as to more contemporary thinkers such as Peter Singer, Mary Midgley, Charles Mills, Iris Marion Young, and Paulien Kleingeld.

fields.name: Perspectives on Games
fields.description:
Over the course of a few decades, video games have grown from technical novelties to pieces of mainstream entertainment with financial stakes rivaling blockbuster films. Their audience, once comprised of specific age and social groups, now cover the entirety of the demographic spectrum. On the public eye, some have held video games responsible for the most reprehensible acts of violence and crime while others hailed them as demonstrators of the very mechanics through which we can organize our lives and goals in the most fulfilling manner. To an ever-increasing extent, play on digital devices is how we entertain ourselves and socialize with others. In this course, we will look at video games through all of these perspectives and more, and aim to cultivate a multifaceted and interdisciplinary understanding of this youngest and most impactful of media.



Starting with the very idea of games and play, we will start by looking at the role of games and playful acts in personal development and social interaction. We will discuss approaches to defining what comprises a game and ways to categorize playful behavior. Building on this understanding, we will then evaluate key concepts in approaching video games and how they came into prominence and how do they relate to each other. Some of the keywords we will discuss are agency, narrative and immersion. Alongside these fundamental concepts, we will look at games as fictional spaces and rule systems, and discuss the phenomenon of cheating alongside other social and individual behavior associated with gameplay.



After establishing these conceptual frameworks, we will turn our attention to broader issues that emanate from the interaction of games with wider culture. We will investigate how games intersect with notions of gender, violence, addiction and online community formation. We will discuss the emergence and subsequent dispersal of a distinct games culture and consider the potential of games in larger contexts through serious games.

fields.name: Portraiture and the Body
fields.description:
This course is about how portraits of the human body have been produced and perceived across times and cultures. Indeed, the human body may well account as the first art object: from early on, individuals have altered their bodies with tattoos and body paint and other modifications (like wearing corsets, heels or wigs, and todays craze for fillers), to underscore their belonging to a specific social or religious group. Just so, great importance has been given to the way that bodies have been represented in painting, sculpture, and more recently photography. From Emperor Augustus to King Louis XIV, and from todays presidential hopefuls to the Kardashians, the management of ones public image is indeed a matter of great scrutiny.

In this course, we will study portraiture and its conventions from its supposed origins in the Italian renaissance up to the present-day. How do traditional elements of the portrait, such as pose, dress, and gaze, contribute to the construction of identity and the confirmation of social status? What about portraits of the Other, such as portraits of servants, the Insane Series by Thodore Gricault, or portraits of foreign rulers, like Empress Dowager Cixi of China (d. 1908)? What social and ritual functions have portraits (and portrait galleries) had over time? Looking at a range of case studies, from Rembrandts Nightwatchto Tracy Emins installation Bed, we will explore how artists (and self-conscious patrons) have constantly stretched existing conventions in (self-)portraiture, broadening our understanding of what portraiture is - and can be.

fields.name: (Methods II:) Introduction to Visual Methodologies
fields.description: This course surveys a range of methodologies that have been developed to analyze visual culture. Beginning from the close formal analysis of images, it will address theoretical approaches including iconography, semiotics, psychoanalysis and discourse analysis. Students will explore how these approaches can be brought to bear on diverse visual objects, from painting, advertisements and film to built environments and digital photography. The course will attend closely to the critical dimensions of visual analysis, probing how forms of social difference are constructed and contested in images. The texts and topics discussed through the course will prove relevant to students interested in the arts, media and cultural theory.

fields.name: Performing Arts - Music
fields.description:
During this Performing Arts  Music course students will get acquainted with basic music theory and history as well as explore their own musicality.

Approximately a quarter of the courses time is dedicated to music history. Knowledge of the history of music, its forms and musical language, most important composers and pieces allows students to listen to concert music in an informed manner.

Another quarter of our time we will spend studying music theory such as rhythm, melody treatment, harmony and music notation. Studying these elements will enable students to understand musical language, learn music easier and write down their ideas to share it with others.

The remaining time of the course, students will explore their musicality and free their creativity in singing and improvisation exercises as well as games, study ensemble pieces and analyze a performance.

The course focuses on Western concert music, but students are welcome to bring in content from other traditions.

fields.name: Literature off the Page
fields.description:
This intensive course is meant to engage our students in the emerging field of the Public Humanities through an experiential approach to literature.  Through drawing on a range of models that explore literature in living contexts (e.g. van der Starr, 2020), this course will encourage students to participate in the literary cultural formation around them in its diverse range of languages, voices, and forms.  Students will be encouraged to experiment with the spoken word, the place and placement of literature in urban contexts, the shaping force of literature in digital worlds, and in its embodied forms: language that is inscribed visually on the body (tattoo art) or language that is invisibly ascribed to it.  

The course is motivated by an experimental framework, one that takes as its starting point the fact that literature is alive and moving in the world and present all around us.  It encourages in an experiential way (observation, making, reflecting, applying) an active engagement with literature as a means of understanding its shaping influence in public domains and cultural production and critique. As an introductory 100 level course, this course would benefit from the inclusion students from a range of majors, who might each bring with them a sense of how their disciplines contribute to this living cultural dynamic.

The emphasis on this intensive course is on experiencing literature in the public domain.  This experience consists of exploration and discovery (finding where a poem or piece of literature exists outside of the book), observation (attention to situated interactions with language and text), and reflection (drawing on critical and theoretical contexts to interrogate the relevance of literature in the public domain).  Central questions include: what does literature do and/or what purpose does it serve when painted on a building, printed on a shirt, printed on a mug, or projected in light?  What are the dynamics of observation regarding the way in which literature is read in spaces where we are unaccustomed to finding it? How might literature in built environments serve as a fixture of identity formation or resistance?  Through exploring these questions in an experiential way, students from all majors may be encouraged to participate in the broader discourse of the Public Humanities and participate directly in the future framing of the Humanities.

fields.name: Early to Modern History
fields.description: This course will focus on the history of Europe in a global context through a large part of the premodern era (ca. 1100-1800). This is a period of overall growth for Europe which, after having lagged behind the other continents (especially Asia and Africa) until then, slowly starts asserting its global economic and military hegemony.  The course will focus on the major political, religious, social, and cultural developments that intervened in this period, which is often credited with the birth of essential modern institutions such as the police, the state, capitalism and individualism. The theme of origins will be therefore a central one: students will be asked to evaluate to assess what constitutes 'modern' thought and practice, to what extent contemporary debates and institutions originate in the premodern period, and what the epistemological risks of this focus on the origins of modern phenomena are. At the same time, they will be encouraged to explore the ways in which the transformations that took place in the premodern era connect to the problems we experience in contemporary society, and to consider the value that studying these phenomena can have when discussing modern issues. They will engage with questions such as: what was society like before the existence of police corps, and what alternative ways were used to maintain the public order? How can we compare contemporary social media to premodern venues for publicly expressing opinions and dissent? Do we feel emotions the same way as people did in medieval and early modern times? A variety of approaches and sources will be used to engage in such discussions, among which: gendered perspectives, ethnography, historical sociology, the history of emotions, the history of books and other material objects. Students will develop tools to evaluate historiography on these and similar topics critically, and to assess how the ideas and practices that emerged in the premodern period are (ab)used until today.

fields.name: Periods and Genres: Modern
fields.description: This course is designed to provide an introduction to art with an emphasis on visual literacy in a historical context. The material spans the 14th century to the present and works of art and architecture are drawn from a range of world cultures. By the end of the semester students should be able to recognize and analyze the differences among the major periods, artists, genres, and theories of western art. The course will help students develop a familiarity with the art and broader cultural background of several non-western traditions. Students will develop the basic vocabulary for the formal analysis of art objects, and gain an understanding of the variety of social and historical contexts that have shaped artistic production in the periods discussed. Examples will include the visual arts of Africa and Asia, the Renaissance in Italy and the Dutch Republic, the Baroque period in France, the advent of modernity in the 19th century, the 20th-century avant-gardes, and postmodernism.

fields.name: Introduction to Film Studies
fields.description: This course introduces students to Film Studies. It focuses on providing them with a thorough, basic knowledge of film history and film analysis, and its associated terminology and methodology. The course surveys roughly the first half of the history of cinema (Pre-Cinema up until Italian Neorealism), using the different periods and movements to address key topics such as cinematography and editing (French Impressionism and Soviet Montage), mise-en-scne (German Expressionism), narration (Classical Hollywood), but also the more theoretical question of films relation to reality (for example, via Italian Neorealism). In the discussion of these topics, the course will also seek connections to more recent developments in cinema.

fields.name: Introduction to Cultural Analysis
fields.description:
This course introduces students to the study of material and artistic cultures from prehistory up to the Late Middle Ages. Students will learn the basics of formal, iconographical and contextual analysis, citing key examples of Near Eastern, Egyptian, Greek, Roman, Early Christian, Byzantine, Islamic and Late Medieval art. Special interest will be given to the understanding of these art works in their specific social, cultural and historical contexts. What can these objects tell us about the societies that produced them? And how do contemporary societies relate to these objects in terms of local, national and/ or world heritage? From a more theoretical point of view, students will learn to work with concepts such as periodization, stylistic development, the concepts of art vs craft, and the social position and status of artists over the centuries.  

The course is complemented by a second introductory course in art history, Periods and Genres Modern. Taught in the second semester, this second course covers the Early Renaissance up to 21st-century art. When taken together, the courses provide a comprehensive overview of the field of art history. Please note, however, that both courses are designed to function independently from one another, so it is well possible to take just one of them.
