fields.name: Methods in the Humanities I
fields.description:
The objective of the 100 level methods course is to equip students with the tools and vocabulary for doing Humanities while also making these approaches tangible, and encouraging an understanding of the relationships between methods, objects of study, and research questions. The course aims to provide an introduction to foundational methods in the major, through a combination of introduction to the method itself and in the practice of engaging the method to analyze an object. The objective is to provide plenty of opportunity to practice working with objects with different methods, thus developing skills to be applied in disciplinary courses and prompting reflections on how a method shapes and even produces our objects of analysis.

The design of the course revolves around objects of analysis, presenting a range of objects which students encounter from different methodological perspectives. By relating multiple methods to the same object, students discover how different methods shape the interpretation of an object in different ways, and how no one method can fully or completely explain an object. Pairing and combining methods in an unconventional manner outside of a chronological progression, emphasises the relevance of each method for contemporary scholarship and facilitates creative, perhaps unexpected, dialogue between various methodological trajectories within the Humanities. 

At the same time, it is important that the object-centered course design not be reduced to a module format. Maintaining a backbone throughout the course is crucial to the coherence and cohesion of the course. This throughline is comprised of the sustained attention to methods as such. Returning in each cycle of the course to a set of basic guiding questions that reflect on the methods in question and on the notion of method itself provides continuity between the modules of the course and encourages connections between these components. These questions also constitute a guideline for shaping the work forms for each class:

 Framing Questions for the Course (Discussed in week 1 and 16)
- What does it mean to do Humanities? What is a method? A methodology? How do these relate to research questions?
- What are the objects of the Humanities? What can we do with them?

 Questions for Encountering an object (first session of each cycle)
- What do you notice about this object? 
- What questions does the object prompt for you? 
- What is this object (how would you initially delineate it, categorize it, etc)

 Questions for Encountering a Method (second and third session of each cycle)
- What is the objective of this method? What does it look for and why?
- What is the starting point, or the grounding assumptions, from which this method proceeds? How do those questions direct a particular mode engaged of object analysis?
- What constitutes evidence(?) in this method? 
- (How) is it situated in and related to broader intellectual, social, cultural, political, economic contexts?
- What worldview does this method operate within, generate, promote? What new questions and perspectives does it generate?

 Questions for practicing with methods (sessions 4 and 5 of each cycle)
- How does this method define, categorize, shape, delineate, draw boundaries around the object? 
- What does this method usefully illuminate about the object? 
- What elements of the object does it pay attention to? How does the object exceed the framework offered by the method? (Or: what questions does or can the method not ask or address, about this or other objects?)
- What kinds of questions does this method generate beyond the scope of interpreting the object?
- Reflect  is this method (only) a method? What is a method?

fields.name: Big Questions in Artificial Intelligence and Data
fields.description:
This course seeks to understand and address the complex phenomena that underlie the impact of Datafication and Artificial Intelligence on human beings, societies and the planet. 

The term datafication is used to emphasise the exponential growth in the volume of data produced globally today. Datafication has led to great increases in transparency, anti-corruption work and improvements in data quality - even raising hopes of empowerment through being counted and given voice by new technologies.

But it has also raised alarming questions of data ownership, accountability and the implications of dependency, safety and control.

Big data sets feed into another trend of recent years, Artificial Intelligence (AI). Machine learning algorithms have garnered huge investments, and climbed policy and research agendas throughout the world. However, applications of AI appear to have vastly divergent effects on individuals and societies, which we do not fully oversee. What seems to be the work of intelligent machines depends on (obvious or hidden) work of humans but also goes beyond that. Moreover, automated decision-making, the processing of data in order to predict and decide, has quickly become a central - and often disruptive - mechanism in areas as divergent as human resources recruitment, political marketing, education, policing, food production, and banking.

There is, therefore, increasing consensus that we are witnessing a paradigm shift, a digital transition: data and digital technologies (including algorithmic technologies) now pervade every aspect of our work and lives. Emerging interdisciplinary research is increasingly demonstrating the risks of algorithmic systems further entrenching systemic social injustices while also making them less transparent against established models of scrutiny. In parallel, regulators struggle to fully understand and anticipate potential (unintended) implications of applying AI to spheres from social services to healthcare while most tech development takes place without any kind of democratic oversight or public debate. 

In this course we take an interdisciplinary approach in order to analyse and better understand the complex phenomena described above. Indeed we claim that an interdisciplinary approach is the only way. 

Finally, we use the metaphor of past, present and future as an organisational principle for ordering the contents of the course: we start with basic knowledge and background, dig into current issues and finish with an outlook for tomorrow.

fields.name: Big Questions in Bioethics
fields.description:
Ethics issues like the above are abundant in health care. In order to provide good care, both on an individual level and on a policy level, dealing with these issues is of key importance. Exploring these issues, supporting health care professionals in dealing with them, and making recommendations is the main focus of bioethics.

Bioethics is a thoroughly interdisciplinary domain, and includes a plurality of methodological, professional and theoretical approaches. Professionals with backgrounds in medicine, health sciences, law, ethics, neuroscience, social sciences, and philosophy closely collaborate in dealing with ethical issues such as those stated in the above.

That dealing well with ethical issues in health care requires an interdisciplinary approach will be a key assumption in the course, and determines how we approach the various subjects we will focus on.

fields.name: Big Questions in Consciousness
fields.description:
Arguably everything we perceive about ourselves or the world around us relates to consciousness. From individual health and resilience to wider societal and global issues such as inclusivity and sustainability, consciousness offers a fascinating conceptual lens from which to view ourselves and our world. Most academic subject areas and disciplines address issues of consciousness in some way: from biology and evolution to brain, mind and cognition, to perception and attention, emotion and affect, to history-making and remembering, to nationalism, spirituality, and political action. The study of consciousness in this interdisciplinary course offers opportunities to consider the relationships between consciousness and body, mind, self, culture and society from a number of disciplinary perspectives, including anthropology, biology, ecology, history, psychology, neuroscience, philosophy, literary studies, cultural studies, psychoanalysis and sociology.

The major questions addressed in this course include definitions of consciousness (What is consciousness? What does it mean to be conscious? What are the origins of consciousness?); how consciousness is situated in natural and social environments (Where is consciousness located? Do animals and plants exhibit consciousness? Can we enter anothers consciousness?); the effects of disruptions to consciousness (What happens if the connections between the brain, the sensory systems and self are disrupted or damaged?); how consciousness is culturally constructed (How does consciousness underpin the cultural, social, and political processes through which societies remember and reconstruct the past, present, and future?) and finally, the limits of consciousness (Can we alter or even transcend consciousness?)

The course is comprised of four units, each of which contains a Disciplinary Introduction (DI) through which students will become acquainted with substantive arguments and debates about consciousness from selected disciplinary perspectives, and an Interdisciplinary Space (IS) in which students are encouraged to collaborate, share knowledge, exchange ideas, and develop interdisciplinary skill sets.

fields.name: Big Questions in Language, Power & (dis)Empowerment
fields.description:
Our unique ability to learn and speak a language might not be something that we are always aware of. Yet language interacts with every aspect of our life in society; it makes it possible for us to exchange information, to share our ideas, opinions and emotions. Precisely because of its all-pervasive nature and because it is such a unique characteristic of human beings, language  its origin, structure, uses, applications and power  has caught the attention of many scholars. For instance, neuroscientists relate human language to the organization, structure, and the intricate workings of our brain. Biologists are interested in the development of language in the individual, its origins, and evolution. Sociologists and psychologists are interested in the use of language to express a national or local identity. Literary scholars examine an authors use of language to articulate their interpretation of a piece of literature. Cultural theorists explore the interaction between language and culture. This brief overview already reveals that language interacts with many of the disciplines that feature in AUCs curriculum  or society at large  and that it can only be fully understood if it is considered in relation to society. To come to a full, holistic understanding of language, its uses and its power, this Big Questions course will take an interdisciplinary approach to this phenomenon, by first comparing and contrasting how language is used and studied in different disciplinary contexts and then attempting to integrate and synthesize these different views.

In the first half of the course, we will provide a basic understanding of the language system, focusing on meaning-making and language use. In the second part, we will elaborate on how language intersects with power, distinguishing between the power behind language  recognising when language reveals power or reflects power  and the power of language  recognising when language maintains existing dominance. We will approach this from different disciplinary perspectives (e.g. language through the eyes of linguists, psychologists, sociologists, anthropologists, computer scientists, biologists, philosophers and cultural theorists) with the aim to build a multi-disciplinary framework. In this context, we will also link the concepts of language and power to immigration, and the arguably linguistically, politically and culturally vulnerable position of immigrants. In the third part of the course, we will then take this multi-disciplinary framework as a starting point for an interdisciplinary inquiry by working collaboratively in interdisciplinary groups to explore how different (disciplinary) approaches shed light on the interplay between language and power, and how combining different views may provide a deeper, more holistic understanding than would be obtained by adopting a mono-disciplinary perspective. Each group will undertake an interdisciplinary project related to the themes of the course, involving research and a creative product (e.g., a podcast, a short movie, a policy proposal, etc).

fields.name: Big Questions in the Anthropocene
fields.description:
The impact of humans on Earth measured and experienced in what is commonly referred to as the Anthropocene, brings us the questions: how and to what extent has human impact surpassed that of natural forces? How do we imagine and envision the Anthropocene? What are the problems relating to the Anthropocene and the experiential and felt elements of life within it? What is required to survive in a context in which multiple scales of violence affect humans and non-humans alike?

Itself a highly contested term, the Anthropocene has been used not only to designate a geological epoch, but also as a means of framing a number of significant environmental, social, and cultural challenges that this period has brought with it. These challenges will be examined from perspectives in the Social Sciences (e.g. international relations, economics, cognitive psychology, sociology, anthropology), Humanities (e.g. ethics, visual arts, film, history, communication, journalism, critical theory) and Sciences (e.g. earth system science, environmental science, ecology, engineering).

In this course, you will draw on a number of disciplinary perspectives to open up problems that attend the Anthropocene, both conceptually and as a marker for more complex and urgent material/ real-world impacts that humans continue to shape and encounter. The course is structured around three key themes: (1) resource management (food security, sustainability, energy); (2) cultural construction (rethinking and contextualizing human/nature relationships, Anthropocene as epoch); and (3) social action (the new economics of the Anthropocene, ethical dilemmas, politics).

In Big Questions in the Anthropocene, you will critically evaluate your relationship with the planet and study new ways and the cultures and practices that it sustains. Together, we will explore questions such as: how do our economies impact waste disposal and energy sources? In addition, we will examine technological innovations, debate ethical issues, and perform social analyses. As we interrogate the idea of the Anthropocene, we will also discuss and challenge related concepts and oppositions. These include the presumptive binary division between nature and humankind; the myth of human domination over nature; and naturalized conceptualizations of time and history.

To effectively address the problems of the Anthropocene, you will develop a set of interdisciplinary tools and a broad understanding of the context and situations in which to apply them, as well as the potential of these tools to facilitate discussion and effect change.

fields.name: Big Questions in the Senses
fields.description:
The senses transcend disciplinary, geographic and chronologic boundaries: they can be studied from the perspectives of anthropology, linguistics, biology, chemistry, psychology, philosophy, art and cultural history. Seeing, smelling, tasting, touching and hearing (in addition to the lesser known senses such as balance) can even be used as embodied methodological tools in the production of knowledge. Ideally the senses should be approached from all of these perspectives, since perception is both a cultural and physiological disposition. Yet the senses  especially those referred to as lower senses (smell, taste, touch)  are often overlooked as serious topics of study and as sources of knowledge. Besides our sense of sight, our other senses are not trained in an analytical sense, and we lack proper vocabularies to describe our sensory impressions. As a result, they are often undervalued or even excluded in modern societies, and in particular in academia.

In an increasingly digital and consequently audio-visual world, especially during the global coronavirus pandemic, it is more important than ever to both understand the senses from a multi-disciplinary perspective, to be able to analyze the visual input we are bombarded with, and to educate the senses we are neglecting.

Media theorist Walter Ong stated that we would gain a truer understanding of other societies if we were to allow that their conceptions of the world may very well not fit into our visualist paradigms. Analytically and consciously seeing, smelling, tasting, touching and hearing can lead to a better understanding of ourselves and other cultures and add to our wellbeing.

Senses exist at the intersection of the cultural, the social, the personal and the biological (or even the chemical) and lay at the core of human interaction with the world and each other. In this course, we want to investigate the senses from these different perspectives.

fields.name: Big Questions in Time
fields.description:
Time is a central concept in our thinking, but has profoundly different meanings in different disciplines. In this course we will explore how these perspectives are different, and focus on developing interdisciplinary skills to understand these differences and work on a number of case studies to apply this understanding to practical problems.

We will start by exploring the role of time in a number of disciplines and build an understanding of the meaning of time within different contexts. Topics will include measuring time, historical development of the Time concept, deep time, space-time, time and age, the reality of the present, past and future, time as cultural concept, and time as a social construct.

Students will first explore the role and nature of time in their own discipline and then compare and contrast these concepts to those of other disciplines.

Many of the problems society faces are in some way related to time. Sustainability, for example, is closely intertwined with different perspectives of time, and yields different solutions depending on the time scale used. Population increase, or depletion of resources for example, can be viewed at the human time scale, which already has a different reality for students and teachers.

Climate change compels us to think about notions of finiteness or even the end of time, on which cultures around the world have a different take. Rapid technological advancements, including innovations to counteract current environmental destruction, affect our material base and thus how we perceive time.

In the second part of the course students will work in interdisciplinary groups on practical projects. They can define their own projects, provided they are of an interdisciplinary nature, and can yield a practical application of their knowledge. The final products include an installation contrasting different perspectives of time that will be exhibited.

Creativity is a vital ingredient in the project, as students in interdisciplinary teams will build a tangible installation on time. The project requires in cooperation skills, interdisciplinary skills, maker skills in combination with artistic skills.

fields.name: Big Questions on the Environment: Science, Society & Culture
fields.description:
It is fair to say that the environment in general and climate change in particular are the quintessential interdisciplinary issues of our time. They can be studied within the scope of sciences (e.g., earth system science, climate science, environmental science, ecology), social sciences (e.g., environmental policy and law, international relations, economics, cognitive psychology, sociology, anthropology) and humanities (e.g., philosophy, religion, ethics, literature, visual arts, film, history, communication, media, journalism, and critical theory). The interdisciplinary connections between these approaches form the basis for this Big Questions course.

The course content will span different disciplines and explore how these may help in providing a full understanding of a broad array of aspects regarding contemporary environmental problems, in particular climate change. In the first half of the course selected topics will be studied from a more monodisciplinary angle (e.g., studying a work of art; a policy framework; physical observations) which together build a multi-disciplinary framework. This part is mostly based on (guest-)lectures, student-led teaching, and group discussions.

In the second half of the course we will move to truly interdisciplinary inquiry by having students work collaboratively in interdisciplinary teams to explore how different (disciplinary) approaches shed light on the same issue and together may provide a deeper, more holistic and more contextual understanding than would be obtained by taking only one approach. Each student team will undertake an interdisciplinary group project related to the theme of the course, involving research and a creative product (e.g., a work of art, a short movie, a play, a policy proposal, etc).

fields.name: Introduction to Biology
fields.description:
Life is hugely diverse, yet this diversity is captured by just five general theories: cellular biology, genetics, organismal biology, evolution and ecology. In this course, we will study selected topics in the first four theories (the fifth, ecology, has its own introductory course). Cellular biology and genetics highlight the universality of life: processes at the molecular and cellular level often are very similar in highly different organisms. Organismal biology aims to understand how organisms can survive in an environment that is continuously changing and how death of the individuals does not obliterate life. Finally, evolutionary theory aims to understand the diversity of life: despite all commonalities at the molecular and cellular levels, there is huge variation among organisms in morphology, physiology, life cycles etc. Based on a renowned text book we will explore the exciting aspects of biology that are associated with these theories.

Quality news papers/sites with a science section report regularly on important news facts in the field of Biology.  In addition, there are news facts that are clearly linked to Biology.  The students are invited to choose a news fact to their liking and to write a paper about it.  For a good grade the paper has to show a clear relationship with the course contents and the textbook.  An oral presentation of the paper is also part of the assessment.

fields.name: Introduction to Chemistry
fields.description: The course introduces the basic concepts of chemistry that are important for understanding the electronic structure of atoms, the periodic table and the trend in the chemical and physical properties of the elements. The nature of the chemical bond (ionic and covalent) will be explained in terms of accepted theories and related to the chemistry of common compound classes, inorganic and organic. The course also covers the properties of the different states of matter (gas, liquid and solid) together with an overview of intermolecular forces such as electrostatic interactions (ion-dipole, dipole-dipole and dispersion forces) and hydrogen bonding. The common classes of (bio)organic compounds will be introduced together with the fundamental reactions they undergo. The development of the basic concepts of chemistry will be described and illustrated with recent scientific results.

fields.name: Introduction to Geological Sciences
fields.description:
This course will introduce the foundations of Earth Sciences i.e. the vast dimensions of space and time in geological processes, the functioning of the major dynamic systems in the Earth as well as the role of Earth sciences in society and its relations to other disciplines.

Students will learn to understand the dimension of deep time in geologic processes, including the basic principles of absolute and relative age determination.

Rocks, the basic building blocks of the Earth, will be studied to observe the record of past processes.

fields.name: Introduction to Health and Wellbeing
fields.description:
Aim of the course is to introduce students to the medical sciences in the broadest sense. There will be much focus on the leading causes of death and disease globally, and the risk factors underlying these. Many of these risk factors come together in the clinical diagnosis Metabolic Syndrome. 

During the course, the student is introduced to key elements of the core courses of the biomedical track. It also provides a historical and philosophical introduction to this field of study. Further, because of its introductory nature this course is enjoyable for Humanities and Social Sciences students who do not shy away from Natural Sciences.

fields.name: Introduction to Literature
fields.description: This course provides an introduction to the study of poetry and narrative as well as detailed study of the relationship between these texts and their cultural and historical contexts. The course emphasizes the development of close reading and analytical skills and encourages students to acquire a working knowledge not only of a specialized vocabulary for textual analysis, but also of the cultural and political milieus in which the authors wrote. We address a diverse array of authors, both canonical and non-canonical, in order to consider current literary debates about the shaping nature of cultural, educational, and political values of literature on questions of canon.

fields.name: Introduction to Media Studies
fields.description:
This course was previously offered under the name 900153HUM Media & Communication. Students are NOT allowed to take the course with the new name if they received credits for the course with the old name.

This course is a broad survey of and introduction to the field of media and mass communication. Students consider the role of media messages and technologies in changing political, social and cultural dynamics on the local, regional, and global stage. The course introduces students to the analysis of media content, as well as to the evolving landscape of media technologies. The main aim of the course is to introduce students to the mutually constitutive properties of media and society, considering how media content and forms participate in the formation of individuals and identities, communities and cultures. Three primary elements cross cut the course:
1. Theories: How messages are produced, communicated and received in mass media; how media forms impact individuals and groups.
2. Medium: The history, structure, impact and control of individual media forms, including print, broadcast and new media.
3. Influence: The mutual engagement and interaction between media and society.

fields.name: Introduction to Philosophy I
fields.description: This course will introduce Philosophy in a broad sense, East (China, India, Middle-East) and West (America, Europe), North and South (including indigenous philosophies). It attempts to be world-philosophical in the true sense of the word, exploring and connecting different traditions, offering a cross-cultural approach, introducing schools and tools. This Autumn chapter of the course takes its departure in the so-called Axial Age (800-400 BCE) and then moves to Ancient Philosophy, Medieval Philosophy (with special attention for both mystical traditions and Arabic philosophy) to finally reach the Modern Era. Periodization itself will be a matter of conversation, since different traditions may work with different periods. Although this first intro will roughly cover the period from 800 BCE to CE 1800, lines will be drawn to contemporary philosophy.

fields.name: Introduction to Philosophy II
fields.description: This course will introduce Philosophy in a broad sense, East (China, India, Middle-East) and West (America, Europe), North and South (including indigenous philosophies). It attempts to be world-philosophical in the true sense of the word, exploring and connecting different traditions, offering a cross-cultural approach, introducing schools and tools. This Spring chapter of the course starts roughly in 1800, addresses several 19th century philosophers and schools from East and West (including thinkers, such as Arthur Schopenhauer who attempted to integrate Eastern thoughts in a more Western metaphysical framework), and then moves on to the 20th century, relating to, among other schools of thought, ordinary language philosophy, phenomenology, the Frankfurt School, postmodernism, the Kyoto school, 20th century Philosophy Africana (as especially highlighted through Peter Adamsons grand project History of Philosophy without any Gaps). Finally, it will sketch certain lines of thought in the 21st century, focusing on specific trends and thinkers. For this final part of the course philosophers from VU, UvA  and AUC will be invited to present what they see as important new developments. Although this second intro will cover the period 1800-now, lines will be drawn back to earlier periods.

fields.name: Introduction to Physics
fields.description:
Intro to Physics introduces the main concepts and the mathematical formalism of classical mechanics as well as a number of instructive applications.  Specifically, the course uses mathematics and the principles of classical mechanics  such as space, time, conservation laws, reference frames, and basic forces and gravity  to study  rigid-body dynamics, including rotation and oscillation.  Applications include everyday examples in architecture, transportation, and sports as well as physical phenomena such as hurricanes and planetary motion.  The necessary mathematical methods from vector calculus and differential equations will be developed along the way.  

Through the homework and related quiz and exam questions, students will encounter real-life applications and will be introduced to advanced topics studied in AUCs 200- and 300-level physical science courses.  Whiteboard exercise sessions will train students in the art of orally communicating physical concepts and ideas.  Students will further learn experientially via in-class demonstrations.  Additionally, they will explore an advanced topic or application of choice via a small team project.

fields.name: Introduction to Public Health
fields.description: Public health is the art and science of preventing disease, promoting health and prolonging life through the organised efforts of society. As opposed to clinical disciplines, public health does not study the health of individual patients, but instead focuses on the health of all people together. In public health, everyone counts. To improve population health, we should not only cure disease, but also prevent diseases that often occur in a population. Preventive efforts include actions to encourage healthy behaviour (e.g., promote physical activity and a healthy diet) or improve mental health (e.g., raise awareness and provide support), and environmental policies (e.g., hygiene, safer workplace and traffic). To inform public health practice, a great variety of topics can be addressed. To begin with, we need to know how our ways of living and living conditions influence our individual health. Next, it is important to describe the health of populations at large, and to understand how the health situation changes over time and differs between groups of people. Moreover, it is important to know which preventive actions are effective, not only in theory, but also in the real-world practice of the Netherlands or any other country around the world.

fields.name: Introduction to the Energy Transition
fields.description:
Part 1: Energy systems

We start with a brief overview of the planetary energy balance, and consider how energy flows have historically been redirected for human purposes. Following this, we will trace the driving forces that have led to and maintain the current energy system, Doing so, we will specifically address societal and technical forms of systemic lock-in that inhibit change. Next we will explore the recent history and possible future of several key low carbon and renewable alternative energy sources. What have been important forces for change? Where could these forces lead us? What could a zero carbon world look like? And what would be the economic, (geo)political and cultural ramifications?

Part 2: Energy science
The underlying chemical and physical principles are used to show how energy is collected and utilized and why such processes are inherently inefficient. We consider the working principle of the following energy conversion mechanisms: thermal energy (as the basis for different ways of harnessing energy), solar energy and wind energy. Further, the conundrum of providing continuous electricity with intermittent renewable resources is investigated.

fields.name: Academic Writing Skills
fields.description: Academic Writing Skills is an introduction to academic study and the foundation skills required for becoming a successful junior member of an interdisciplinary academic community. The syllabus reflects a progression of competence in the primary skills of academic reading, research, writing and presentation while fostering both cross-disciplinary and digital literacy. Activities will combine a range of digital and print media and will draw on the six AUC themes, emphasizing interdisciplinarity and diversity, demonstrating contemporary relevance and global perspectives, and reflecting students own interests. The course will accommodate different learning methods and styles, and each section of the syllabus will involve both a theoretical and a practical dimension, encouraging reflection and enabling students to learn by doing.

fields.name: A Golden Age? History and Heritage of the Dutch Republic
fields.description: The so called Golden Age, which corresponds roughly with the 17th century, was an extremely important period in Dutch history. The enormous increase in trading activity at that time not only increased social mobility but produced a wealthy merchant class. This merchant class was important for patronage of the arts, literature and science and the merchants were also in a position to influence urban planning and architecture of that time. Topics to be covered in the course include colonialism and trade; scientific discoveries; navigation; the Dutch East India Company and the Amsterdam Bank; tulip fever; the perceived tradition of religious tolerance in the Netherlands; still-life painting; the Dutch political scene and the Dutch Republic in the century Europe. Students will learn about historical developments in the Dutch Republic that made the 17th century such an important period for The Netherlands, the Golden Age, and will trace the significance of these developments to the present day.

fields.name: Adaptation Studies
fields.description:
Although the originality of a work of literature or art has often been privileged as the main criterion for evaluation, writers, playwrights, filmmakers and artists have always looked to previous works for inspiration. Adaptation, in other words, has always played a leading role within literature and culture as a primary mode of creative transfer and production. Arguably, globalization and advancing technologies have made (and are making) processes of adaptation increasingly complex, by increasing the scope and modes of reception and interaction across cultures and genres and platforms.

This class examines the theory and the practice of adaptation. We will consider adaptation as a cultural product (primarily using case studies from literature and film, but also including theatre, art, media, etc.) and as a cultural process, in which an existing work is adapted to another medium or form, or to another context or culture. We attempt to do so from an interdisciplinary and global perspective, drawing on the experience and interests of our group.

In the introductory part of the course, we will explore possible frameworks for analyzing adaptation. Students will be introduced to a) the main issues and debates involved in adaptation studies and b) some of the primary tools that have been proposed for the study of adaptations.

fields.name: Addiction
fields.description: The goal of this course is to gain insight into the etiology and the neurobiology of addictive behaviour. The course explores various topics in the study of drug addiction. The primary emphasis is on psychological and biological theories of drug addiction. Genetic and personality traits representing risk factors for the development of addiction will be identified. Other important topics are clinical diagnosis and treatment. Psychomotor stimulant (e.g. amphetamine, cocaine) and opiate (e.g. heroin, morphine) drugs, but also the more socially accepted drugs nicotine and alcohol, figure prominently in an examination of the pharmacological properties of addictive drugs. Much of the course relates the important mood-elevating effects of these drugs to their biological actions. However, non-drug related addictions, such as gambling and obsessive eating will also be discussed.

fields.name: Advanced Creative Writing
fields.description:
This course continues the diverse exploration of creative writing as a discipline and an art form. Students will immerse themselves in both the theory and practice of writing creatively.

Objectives
1) The student builds off her/his prior knowledge from Creative Writing.
2) The student illustrates knowledge of her/his individual voice and personal aesthetic through writing and discussions.
3) The student learns how to work on a larger creative project.
4) The student learns the role of research when it comes to working on a creative project.
5) The student is immersed in the practice of writing and will hopefully continue to write after the class ends.

fields.name: Advanced Geosciences
fields.description:
The history of the universe (Big Bang, Galaxy formation), nucleo-synthesis and formation of compounds. 

Planetary evolution in the solar system, the Earth-Moon system, internal differentiation. 

Earths heat and heat transport. 

Mantle mineralogy, discontinuities, and mantle convection. 

Geosynclinal theory to Plate Tectonics; details of Plate Tectonics (driving forces; magmatism, metamorphism and structures of plate margins). 

Sedimentary basins in plate tectonic context. 

Interactions between Earths layers, and the relevance of water for solid Earth processes and formation of natural resources. 

Early evolution of atmosphere and hydrosphere. 

Coevolution of planet and life.

fields.name: Advanced Macro-Economics
fields.description: The course comprises three parts. The first part explains how fiscal and monetary policies work in mainstream macroeconomic models. How to model the demand side and the supply side? How to bring in money and banking? This part builds a framework for a closed economy setting as well as an open economy  setting. Specific attention is paid to macroeconomic fluctuations (business cycle). The second part focuses on how macroeconomic policies respond to a crisis. Are fiscal and monetary instruments apt and effective to deal with a crisis, in particular, in the sense that they minimize income losses and that they maximize prospects for post-crisis recovery? This part starts with a couple of guest lectures and covers three recent crises. First, the global financial crisis that started with the bankruptcy of Lehman Brothers on September 15, 2008. Next, the European debt crisis with mounting and unsustainable sovereign debts in various Euro zone countries, especially Greece in 2010. And, lastly, the economic crisis caused by the COVID19 pandemic. The third and final part is being reserved for group work aimed at the preparation and participation in a debate and at the writing and presentation of a policy brief.

fields.name: Advanced Micro-Economics
fields.description: This course develops students understanding of the methods of microeconomics and covers fundamental topics such as utility, choice and demand; firm behaviour and imperfect markets, welfare analysis, and market failures. We follow closely the book by Snyder and Nicholson (2012), please make sure you have your copy before the course starts!

fields.name: Advanced Programming
fields.description: By the end of this course you will have an understanding of programming languages at the lowest levels to interact with the instruction set at the interface between the software and hardware of a computer, as well as at higher levels through building an interpreter for a simple programming language.

fields.name: Advanced Research Methods and Statistics
fields.description:
In this course we will cover a series of techniques that are more advanced than those covered in BRMS1, BRMS2, or Statistics for Sciences. We will work extensively with science and social science data and learn how to analyze and interpret data at an advanced level. The course covers the following topics:


- Review of multivariate linear regression and ANOVA
- Basic matrix algebra
- Model selection and diagnostics in multivariate linear regression
- Logistic regression
- (M)ANOVA and (M)ANCOVA
- Discriminant analysis and classification
- Principle component analysis
- Analysis of repeated measures
- Categorical data analysis and multi-way frequency tables                                                                                                                                                                                    - Additional topics as time permits

The central aim of the course will be that students acquire the skills to conduct and interpret quantitative analyses of various empirical studies. Students will also analyze science and social science data using the techniques learned in the course and complete data analysis assignments.

Please note that ARMS is not designed to be an advanced mathematics course.

fields.name: Advanced Research Writing
fields.description: Advanced Research Writing is a preparation course for the Capstone, providing the skills necessary for students to produce longer research projects and assignments as a mature member of the interdisciplinary academic community. The syllabus develops skills from Academic Writing Skills, while prompting students to develop new skills in a specific research field. It considers and problematizes the broader academic landscape, and also looks beyond academia, to the significance and societal relevance of research, so as to encourage social responsibility, collaboration, and cross-disciplinary cooperation. The course mirrors the Capstone process, from research proposal through to edited and revised document, and explores the research-writing process, helping students to anticipate hurdles and develop a writing style that is attentive to their research field.

fields.name: Ancient Philosophical Texts
fields.description: Does the art of rhetoric merely involve the clever use of words to persuade an audience? Or is the best rhetorician a person who has a philosophical disposition to inquire about the best possible options? What is the power of words in politics? Are words meaningful or mere constructions? Can rhetoric serve to create moral imaginaries? In this course, we will travel back in time to ancient Athens, a city-state that was obsessed with the power of rhetoric. Ancient Athens was a rowdy democracy where political gain crucially depended on the art of public speaking. Many teachers of rhetoric travelled to wealthy Athens in order to teach the ambitious elite the techniques and philosophies that would ensure success in politics and in life. This invited the great philosopher Plato (427-347 BCE) to ask important questions about the relationship between rhetoric, language, truth, meaning, and power. In this course, we will study several of Platos dialogues in order to reflect on questions such as: What is the art of rhetoric? Can rhetoric be separated from philosophy and morality? What is the power of words in politics? What is good rhetoric? The final week is dedicated to a specific kind of rhetoric, namely, the rhetoric of music, myths, and stories. We will ask questions such as is there a rhetoric of music? How do myths and stories relate to the emotions, and to the moral imagination? Throughout the course, we will read a selection of texts that help us think about the questions concerning rhetoric today, and listen to a number of speeches by politicians etc. in order to acquire a better sense of the different techniques of rhetoric. Finally, we will discuss the reception of Plato and the question of who owns the classical age.

fields.name: Anthropologies of Community
fields.description: This course promises a critical contemplation of Community as an idea(l), experience, and expression of social cohesion. We deconstruct and decolonize community as a concept, and seek to comprehend how communities are formed, and why they continue to be pervasive and powerful in/for the 21st Century. Students explore the diverging meanings and purposes ascribed to community by local and global actors across the world, and how these relate to wider societal contexts and structures governed by states and neoliberal/global capitalism. Through examining how community has been theorized within anthropology (etic) and how it is understood and experienced outside of academia (emic), we aim to develop a critical decolonialized conception of community able to comprehend and confront urgent contemporary matters-of-concern.

fields.name: Artificial Cognition: Pattern Recognition
fields.description:
Cognitive Sciences and Computer Sciences (specifically Artificial Intelligence) are symbiotic fields of research. Many popular models of Machine Learning are based on our knowledge within (cognitive) neuroscience, like neural networks and decision trees. Conversely, Machine Learning is an important tool used to analyze neuroimaging data, and help us test established cognitive theories about perception, emotion, and consciousness.

Humans sense, act, think, feel, communicate, learn and evolve. We see these capabilities increasingly also in machines. This course aims to develop a first understanding of how humans and machines make sense of the natural environment from all the physical signals pouring into them. Information processing is discussed as a system of interconnected nodes, where the brain, the social, and machines all play integral parts.

The concept of pattern recognition is central to the understanding of how information systems function, which will be discussed at multiple levels of abstraction (e.g. social interaction, the brain, artificial intelligence). The course is particularly relevant for students interested in crossing the divide between (physical, life, social) sciences to cooperatively i) step up progress in cognitive information processing in both man and machine, and ii) develop new applications and technologies serving society. Topics covered include, information structure, pattern recognition and machine learning, man-machine interaction, artificial intelligence, mediated communication, expression and emotion, bias in man and machine, brain structure, neuronal processing, visual consciousness, art and the brain, social cognition

fields.name: Artificial Intelligence, Technology and the Law
fields.description: This course will explore topics at the intersection of law, technology, and artificial intelligence (AI). Machine learning systems, algorithms, and other AI applications are transforming economic business models and society for the last decades, and laws and regulations often fail to keep up with the pace of technology. Everyday decisions around us, like when loans are approved by banks, which job candidates are reviewed, and whether criminal defendants are deprived of their liberty are now often made by machine learning systems in the background. The materials and discussions in this course will ask students to grapple with how AI is impacting our lives from a legal perspective. We focus particularly on the challenges to current laws posed by prominent near-future technologies. We will examine how these technologies will interact with, challenge, and shape laws and society going forward. The course will start with two general topics an introduction to AI and ethics, followed by 4 core case studies of challenges in law and technology: privacy and vulnerability; competition and the internet of things; the judicial process; and freedom of speech in the democratic debates.

fields.name: Astroparticle Physics
fields.description:
Astroparticle physics is a multidisciplinary field, which connects the study of the smallest scales (elementary particles) with the largest scales (the Universe). Important topics are the origin of cosmic rays, gravitational waves, the physics of the early Universe, and the nature of dark energy and dark matter. The latter forms an important theme of the present course.



The course starts with a description of the Standard Model of particle physics, including discussion on how quarks and leptons were discovered. We then consider how particles such as neutrinos and charged particles can be used as probes of the physics that occurs in the Universe. After an interlude on cosmic ray acceleration, we turn to cosmology: the evolution of the Universe, from the Big Bang to the Universe today, and the role of dark matter and dark energy in that evolution. This includes descriptions of the large scale structures, the early Universe, nucleosynthesis, inflation, and the cosmic microwave background. We will discuss the astrophysical evidence for dark matter and how we attempt to identify the particle responsible for it.

fields.name: Atmospheric Sciences
fields.description:
The focus of this interdisciplinary course is on the physics and chemistry of the Earths atmosphere. We will work towards understanding sources of atmospheric trace gases and aerosol particles (also known as particulate matter or PM), their chemical and physical transformations, their environmental and climatic effects, and their removal processes.

Emphasis will be put on applying these concepts to atmospheric problem sets, for which a basic understanding of physical chemistry and algebra is assumed. A brief primer on the necessary chemical concepts (e.g. kinetics and chemical equilibria) will be included. These problem sets revolve around understanding source-sink relationships and quantifying the combined effect of atmospheric mixing (e.g. boundary layer dynamics or troposphere-stratosphere exchange) and chemical transformation on the concentration of trace gases and aerosols. Meteorology and atmospheric dynamics will be briefly discussed, but they are not part of the core content of the course.

Topics of study include: tropospheric photochemistry and photochemical smog formation; acid rain; stratospheric ozone depletion; particulate matter (PM) formation; aerosol population dynamics; heterogeneous chemistry; cloud physics; radiative transfer.

fields.name: Author in Context
fields.description:
This course, the fourth installment of the Author in Context series will explore the work of the Modernist author James Joyce through his epic text, Ulysses.  Widely touted as one of the most significant works in English of the twentieth century, Ulysses charts the meandering course of Leopold Bloom as he moves through Dublin on the 16th of June, 1904.  It is a text that sprawls and stretches, extending its experimental body into the city, politics, and history, as it simultaneously navigates the numinous and the ordinary, the ephemeral and eternal, the mythic and the modern.  
 
In this course, we will do a deep dive into this text, situating it in the context of Joyces other work, Irish culture, and literary modernism as a foundation for exploring the diverse range of topics it engages.  In moving through the text, we will explore the way in which it resonates with Homers Odyssey, the most beautiful, all-embracing theme of the text in Joyces words, and examine its response to the Celtic Renaissance, Irish politics and the British colonial occupation of Ireland.  We will trace related patterns of imagery through the text as well as pay close attention to Joyces experiments in form, the publication history of the text, and its critical history.

fields.name: Cancer Biology and Treatment
fields.description: Cancer is a leading cause of death worldwide with an enormous personal as well as societal impact. Oncology is the branch of medical science dealing with the biology, diagnosis and treatment of cancer. Knowledge about cancer development and treatment is essential to perform fundamental and translational research on cancer and to prepare applied research protocols for the diagnosis and treatment of specific patient groups. This knowledge is also important for the best communication between medical practitioners and basic scientists, as well as between scientists and laymen. The Oncology course provides a thorough overview of the biology of cancer and the different treatment methods.Basic knowledge of all aspects of cancer covered by the course textbook will be taught in lectures by teachers who are experts in their field. Further insight from ongoing research will be provided in seminars by guest scientists. Besides interactive lectures and seminars, active learning integrated in the course includes writing and presentation assignments, a science journalism workshop and journal club.

fields.name: Capstone
fields.description: The Capstone is the culmination of skills, knowledge and attitudes students have acquired in their curriculum, and must be completed during their final semester at AUC. Within a specified timeframe, and under supervision of a (partner) faculty member, students are expected to carry out research: gather information and sources, formulate a thesis statement or research question, situate their research within the field, set objectives for the project, establish a methodology, and communicate their findings clearly and coherently in a polished piece of scholarly work.

fields.name: Cardiovascular Diseases
fields.description: Cardiovascular diseases including heart failure and stroke are among the main causes of death in the Western world. Their incidences are still rising due to the aging of the population, obesity and, paradoxically, the successful treatment of acute myocardial infarction and cardiac arrhythmia. The aim of the course is to give the students a thorough understanding of the pathomechanisms involved in cardiovascular diseases and to provide insight in the current state of affairs and future prospects of prevention, diagnosis and treatment of cardiovascular diseases. Starting from basic cellular processes, various aspects of cardiac and vascular function at the organ level in health and disease will be covered. The impact of lifestyle, diet, sports and genetics are discussed. Major health issues related to obesity, diabetes, chronic inflammation, sepsis and shock will be discussed. The course includes several practicals and a demonstration of cardiac imaging using ultrasound. The courses teachers are basic researchers and clinicians from the fields of cardiology, pulmonology, internal medicin and nephrology.

fields.name: Cases in Cultural Analysis
fields.description: This practice based course explores and animates the work of cultural analysis as a close attention to objects  be they elements of popular culture or everyday life; works of art; events; or cultural expressions of any kind. As founding definitions of the field emphasise, cultural anaysis involves theoretical reflection and reading in which the "object" from subject matter becomes subject, participating in the construction of theoretical views. (Bal 1999: 13). Put differently, rather than applying abstracted theories to cultural objects, cultural analysis establishes a dialogue between object, theory, and analyst.

fields.name: Cell Biology and Physiology Lab
fields.description: One of the rare opportunities offered by AUC to acquire laboratory skills. Students will be engaged in ongoing research. Within four weeks, students will be introduced to approximately 6-8 cell biological techniques. These techniques last up to two days per technique, supervised by an instructor. The to be used techniques give a realistic impression of techniques typically required for a cell biological research paper. In short, a cell biological experiment was conducted in the month preceding the lab course and students, together with an instructor, will analyze and interpret the samples. Students will elucidate how cells reacted towards the variables applied in the experiment in terms of gene expression, cell biological behavior, protein expression and cell morphology. In the final week, a report will be written, where students, usually divided over 3 groups, have to integrate the various results. The course takes place at Academic Centre for Dentistry Amsterdam (ACTA, department of Periodontology) and at Academic Medical Centre (AMC, microscopy facility).

fields.name: Challenges in Health and Society
fields.description:
In this course students will take an interdisciplinary approach to biomedicine and health. There will be an equal emphasis on interdisciplinary content and interdisciplinary skill development. With regard to content, in the first part of the course we will explore the broader health theme of immigrant health, as explained by AMC specialists. These themes will be deepened further in specialized guest lectures. With regard to skills, the first part of the course will focus on personal development, especially in relation to interdisciplinary collaboration, which we will discuss with the help of an educational novel written for this purpose called WIN WIN WIN.

In the second part of the course, students will form groups based on similar health-related interests, possibly also related to their future capstone topic. In these groups they will together explore the societal context of their topic and identify Societal Challenges that these areas face. Students will be asked to present their topic to the class, and they are free to use the outcome of this investigation to improve the contextualization part of their Capstones.

The last part of the course will consists of a concluding reflection concerning what students have learned about Health during their studies at AUC. Several classes will be given to help stimulate and structure this reflection.

fields.name: Classical and Modern Sociological Thought
Climate Sciences: Past and Present
fields.description:
The past Century has seen a rise in extreme weather alongside rising concentrations of gases in the atmosphere. These are generally attributed to our own grand geophysical experiment: the burning of fossil fuels. Predicting the course of events should Humanity adopt one of the many emission scenarios (e.g. Business as usual) is the job of Climatologists with the aid of climate models.  Scientists make predictions on the outcome of various scenarios by experimenting with various model boundary conditions. Yet the climate system is complex. Numerous feedbacks operate at different temporal and spatial scales. The Earth however, is a natural laboratory with over 4.5 billion years of history, ranging from hothouse to icehouse climate. A prime example is the ice sheets that entomb Antarctica, rest upon rocks deposited in Polar Forests stalked by diverse macrofauna, including Dinosaurs. Whilst the Present is the key to our understanding of the Past, the past equally offers us an understanding of our Future.Understanding these changes is the job of palaeoclimatologists and palaeoceanographers, whose role is to understand climate, feedbacks, and climate system interactions on timescales of thousands to millions of years.

The aim of this course is to give the student a theoretical and practical understanding of the Climate system. They will learn how to interpret and use palaeoclimate records to understand Past, Present, and Future Climate. The student will also understand how scientists critically evaluate proxy information. This course is split into three parts: (1) a theoretical understanding of the components of the climate system; (2) practical instruction in how Palaeoclimatologists reconstruct the climate of the past; and (3) how such reconstructions are used to understand the climate system. Fundamentals questions to be addressed are: (i) How do the various components of the climate system work? (ii) How do the components of the climate system interact? (iii) How do these change work over vast temporal and spatial scales? (iv) How do we reconstruct the climate of the past? And, (iv) how do we deal with uncertainty when we can no longer directly measure?

Conservation and Restoration Biology
Contextualizing Chinese: Language and Society 2
fields.description: Students are able to do (parts of) the HSK 1-2 Elementary (CEFR A1-A2): They can understand and use familiar everyday expressions and very basic phrases aimed at satisfying of basic needs of communication. They can introduce themselves and others and can ask and answer questions about personal details such as where they come from, where they live, people they know etc. They are able to interact in a simple way, provided the other person talks slowly and clearly and is prepared to help.

fields.name: Contextualizing Chinese: Language and Society 1
fields.description: Students are able to do (parts of) the HSK 1 Elementary (CEFR A1): They can understand and use familiar everyday expressions and very basic phrases aimed at satisfying of basic needs of communication. They can introduce themselves and others and can ask and answer questions about personal details such as where they come from, where they live, members of the family etc.

fields.name: Contextualizing Arabic: Language and Society 2
fields.description:
At the end of his course the student will have covered the main linguistic aspects equivalent to the linguistic aspects of the A2 level of the Common European Framework for Languages and will be familiar with the most relevant cultural aspects of Arab culture, exposed through the following: 

 

Linguistic:  

Understand spoken language (listening) sentences and frequently used expressions related to areas of most immediate relevance (e.g., personal and family information, shopping, local geography, employment); simple ordinary tasks requiring a direct exchange of information on familiar and routine matters; discourse related to his/her background, immediate environment.   
Understand written language (reading) in short texts and identify specific information in everyday texts such as advertisements, prospectuses, menus, instruction manuals and timetables, press reports film synopsis and personal messages. 
Write short, notes and messages in the form of emails, letters, short presentations, blogs, text messages or leaflets. 
Interact orally in order to express everyday transactions that require a direct exchange of information on familiar topics and activities; sustain short conversations on topics related to themselves (family and other people, living conditions, educational background, past, present or most recent job/studies) and their routines, travels and immediate needs, both in relation to present and past experiences.  Be familiar with social conventions and body language. 
Cultural: 

Demonstrate a familarity at a pre-intermediate level with cultural artifacts and activities that show the diversity of the Arab culture, specifically at this level regarding history, literature, work, celebrations, cultural events and rituals, food and ecology.  
Demonstrate an understanding of the cultural and linguistic diversity at a pre-intermediate level of the Arab world, by presenting a wide variety of materials such as: texts, podcasts, TV and radio news and current affairs programs from different realities and geographies of the Arab world.  
Develop intercultural competence through activities that make students  question their values and cultural references, make them aware of stereotypes, and enable them to establish meaningful connections with people, practices, and cultural objects from the Arab world. Have the ability to apply simple forms of language in different cultural contexts, namely: personal experiences, recalling historical past events or employment situations.

fields.name: Contextualizing Arabic: Language and Society 1
fields.description:
At the end of his course the student will have covered the main linguistic aspects equivalent to the linguistic aspects of the A1.1 level of the Common European Framework for Languages and will be familiar with the most relevant cultural aspects of Arab culture, exposed through the following: 

Linguistic:  

Understand spoken language (listening) from media and spontaneous conversations. Students will interact in a simple way provided the other person talks slowly and clearly and is prepared to help.  
Understand written language (reading) in basic, short texts of the general life (greetings, habits, needs, social conventions, etc.)  
Write general short texts about personal information, daily routines, family structures and relations etc. 
Interact orally in Egyptian Arabic in order to describe experiences and events in present. Students will be able to introduce themselves, talk about everyday life, food, life conditions, family relations and be familiar with social conventions and body language. 
Cultural: 

Demonstrate a basic familiarity with cultural artifacts and activities that show the diversity of the Arab culture, specifically at this level regarding cities in the Arab world, greetings, historical places and everyday life routines.  
Demonstrate a basic understanding of the cultural and linguistic diversity of the Arab world, by presenting a wide variety of materials such as: texts, podcasts, TV and radio news and current affairs programs from different realities and geographies of the Arab world.  
Develop intercultural competence through activities that make students  question their values and cultural references, make them aware of stereotypes, and enable them to establish meaningful connections with people, practices, and cultural objects from the Arab world. 
Have ability toapply basic, simple forms of language in different cultural contexts, namely: introductions, life routines, personal preferences, and descriptions.

fields.name: Dynamical Systems
fields.description:
Dynamical systems are mathematical models that appear in many areas of the natural sciences. They describe the evolution of chemical reactions, the motion of satellites around the earth and the outbreak of diseases. Their solutions determine the shapes and speeds of signals in optical fibres, the size of convective rolls in the atmosphere and the arrangement of atoms in a crystal.

The dynamical models that scientists use take many different forms. They range from simple low-dimensional iterated maps and ordinary differential equations to complex networks, partial differential equations, coupled map lattices, delay equations, stochastic differential equations, hybrid systems and many more.

In this course, students will develop a first understanding of the intriguing qualitative and quantitative properties of dynamical systems, both from a theoretical/mathematical and from a practical/applied point of view.

fields.name: Ecology - from Soil to Society
fields.description:
The theory of ecology aims to understand the spatial and temporal patterns of the distribution and abundance of organisms. Before we delve into this theory, we will first acquaint ourselves with the major groups playing a role in the ecological theater: bacteria, plants, animals and fungi. Throughout the course we will deepen the acquaintance by looking to specific plants and animals. We then briefly address the abiotic factors affecting the distribution and abundance of organisms. Finally we will address their reciprocal interactions and how these contribute to the regulation of population size and the flow of energy and nutrients within ecosystems. 

The interaction of ecology with humans will be covered in various ways. The human activities underlying economic and socio-cultural globalization lead to a third form of globalization that has multiple and increasing impacts on ecology: biological globalization. This is the process by which species spread across geographical distribution barriers, leading to so-called bio-invasions. We will use invasive species as a tool to study ecological processes. These species often disrupt local ecosystems, providing natural experiments to study ecological processes. At the same time, they may impact strongly on the economy if they completely overtake the local ecosystem. Invasive species thus provides a strong linkage to ecological theory and societal issues. Other links to relate to conservation and restoration ecology. The rational for society to aim for conservation and restoration is to be found in ecosystem services. These services allow the value of nature to be expressed in monetary units which is a prerequisite to integrate ecology and economy. 

Ecological theory is often underpinned by or even formulated in terms of mathematical models. During the course we will pay due attention to this approach and we will practice some

fields.name: Discrete Mathematics and Algebra
fields.description:
(1) Students will be able to use basic proof techniques for counting and solving combinatorial questions related to sets, permutations and graphs.
(2) Students will get familiar with basic graph concepts like graph coloring, graph planarity and Eulerian graphs.
(3) Students will get to know fundamental optimization problems on graphs and learn how to develop algorithms to solve them.
(4) Students will learn modular arithmetic and properties of prime numbers and how these can be employed to design cryptographic schemes.

fields.name: Digital Habits, Digitized Lives
fields.description:
At the conclusion of the course, students will be able to:

Demonstrate their grasp on key concepts and theories that engage with digital tools and their affordances.
Discern the moulding effects of digital technologies on contemporary societies from multiple theoretical and disciplinary perspectives, and show knowledge of key debates in the field.
Analyse the role of digital technologies in shaping everyday practices, habits and relationships.
Situate different methodologies within disciplinary contexts and elaborate on their relevance.
Apply a practice-based analysis on digital media and tools.
Identify relevant frameworks for the study of the interconnections between disciplines that focus on the technological, textual, anthropological, social, economic, political, and legal aspects of the digital world, and know how/where to access useful resources for further academic research.

fields.name: Data Structures and Algorithms
fields.description:
After taking this course, the student:

has basic knowledge of common data structures and algorithms, 
can choose an appropriate data structure for a computational problem,
can analyze the performance of algorithms in terms of time and memory requirements,
can read pseudocode and implement given algorithms,
is able to write simple programs in the programming language C,
 understands memory management and can program with pointers.

fields.name: Counterculture
fields.description: The student will master a group of signal primary and secondary texts exemplifying the global countercultures of the period 1953-1974, learning to identify, analyze, and question the major characteristics of the period in a variety of genres and disciplines.

fields.name: Cultural Memory Studies
fields.description:
Learning outcomes

On successfully completing the course, students will have (1) acquired a thorough working knowledge of the interdisciplinary field of cultural memory studies; (2) they will have obtained insight into the different disciplinary discourses and methodologies that inform and constitute the field; and (3) they will have acquired the ability to reflect both critically and analytically on specific instances and examples of cultural memory and its role in society and culture, from contexts that range from global to local/urban public spheres. In the process, students will also (4) have enhanced their interdisciplinary skills and (5) received conceptual and critical frameworks that help them bring academic knowledge to bear on problems and situations in non- academic (public sphere) environments.

fields.name: Electricity and Magnetism
fields.description:
The course is divided into three sections:

Electricity
Magnetism, electromagnetic induction and circuits
Special relativity and light
In the first two sections, students are introduced to the main electromagnetic laws and phenomena in vacuum and in matter, culminating in (an introduction to) Maxwells equations. The third section deals with the principles and consequences of special relativity, such as the constant speed of light, time dilation and length contraction. The aim of this course is to reach an understanding (at the level of the book used) that goes beyond knowing the equations, and that relates to daily experience, to current technological advances, and to the physics that governs the basic constituents of matter

fields.name: Empire and its Afterlives
fields.description: This course covers contemporary social and political struggles in the Middle East region from a historical and de-colonial perspective. Todays conflicts have a long historical arch that can be traced to a long 400 years of Ottoman empire rule and the European colonizing era. We study earlier struggles in the region, from the 19th century and through the colonial period, and their afterlife. The approach this course offers is a bottom up study of particular societies and their political cultures. Readings expose nuanced perspectives that pose an alternative to dominant paradigms of the regio

fields.name: Dutch
fields.description: This page refers to all Dutch language courses.

fields.name: Environmental Chemistry/Eco-Toxicology
fields.description:
This interdisciplinary course addresses the presence of chemical pollution in the environment and its effect on
biological processes ranging from the molecular to the population level. The course consists of four main pillars, each
addressing its own questions, i.e. 

1. Environmental chemistry: What are the main classes of environmental pollutants? What are their chemical
characteristics? How do they enter the environment? What is their fate in the environment?
2. Monitoring of pollutants: How can we measure exposure to chemicals in the environment? How can we discover new
contaminants? 
3. Environmental toxicology: How does a compound behave after uptake? What makes a chemical toxic? How can we test
the toxicity of a chemical? What is the mode of action of a toxicant? How do chemicals interact? 
4. Risk assessment: How can we determine a safe level of exposure for humans? And for the environment? 
Throughout the course, several classes of compounds will be discussed with special emphasis on these four pillars. Each pillar will be examined separately

fields.name: Environmental Economics
fields.description: Economics helps explain decisions made by individuals, firms, and governments. Many such decisions are inextricably related to the natural environment. This relationship goes both ways. For instance, individuals may deteriorate local air quality by purchasing a polluting diesel car while simultaneously this degraded air quality affects their own well-being. In this course, we study the relationship between natural resources, environmental quality, the economy, and environmental policy using a range of modern economic theories and methods. Students will develop a thorough understanding of relevant aspects of the economy and the environment, their inter-linkages, and their relevance to current environmental problems including e.g. climatic change, declining fish stocks, water shortages, and biodiversity conservation. The lectures will focus on linking theory to practical examples in order to set the stage for the application of methods, such as simple modelling and valuation techniques.

fields.name: Epidemiology
fields.description: This discipline brings together the biological (medicine) and social sciences. Students will study exposure/disease relationships. Topics include measuring disease occurrence and causal effects, epidemiological study designs, infectious disease epidemiology, dealing with biases, analyzing simple epidemiological data, statistical terminology, measuring interactions, public health surveillance, and writing a scientific mini article.

fields.name: Epigenetic Regulations
fields.description: Epi-genetics concerns, in its broadest sense, the information that is added to the primary base sequence of DNA. It studies the biochemical processes, biological consequences, and inheritance of this additional information. The nature of this information is the chemical modification of DNA and of the proteins that are bound to DNA. They control the expression of genes and activity of parasitic DNA sequences in our genome. In this course, we will dissect this epigenetic language, the sophisticated molecular processes involved, as well as the biological outcomes and traits in animals, human, plants, and 'lower eukaryotes.

fields.name: European Union Law
fields.description: European integration  by means of the European Union  has profoundly changed the way states and people interact on the European continent. Important drivers of integration have been the European Court of Justice and national courts in the Member States, who by actively interpreting and applying EU law have played a major role in removing obstacles to trade and mobility in the EUs internal market and continue to do so in an ever growing number of areas. This course offers an academic entry into the legal discipline as a way of engaging with the European Union. The first part of the course addresses the founding case law of the Court, the core principles of EU law, the internal market and European citizenship. The second part of the course addresses a selection of current challenges facing European integration and world society as a whole, such as free movement, equal treatment, privacy regulation, Brexit, migration and asylum, the euro and the rule of law.

fields.name: Human Rights Law and Politics
fields.description:
1. Knowledge of the philosophical basis and basic concepts of human rights



2. Knowledge of the European regional human rights system



3. Understanding of the process of progressive implementation of human rights principles in policy



4. Understanding of the steps involved in the response to human rights violations



5. Having skills regarding the basic processes of research
