fields.name: Evolution and Origin of Human Diseases
fields.description:
Nothing in biology makes sense except in the light of evolution. This quote from the evolutionary biologist Dobzhansky illustrates the central position of evolution in the biological sciences. This also applies to the medical sciences, which are fundamentally based in biology. Hence, an evolutionary approach to diseases is likely to teach us something valuable about the diseases about their origin, their evolutionary consequences or about approaches to combat the disease.

In the course, basic concepts of pathogen evolutionary dynamics will be introduced, including techniques for analysing mathematical models for disease dynamics. Concept include Quasispecies Dynamics, Red Queen Evolution, and Evolution of Virulence. In the second part of the course, students will give introductions in a number of topics in Evolution and Origin of Human Diseases. These topics include Antibiotic Resistance, Emerging Diseases, Evolution of Cancer, and Darwinian Medicine.  Using these topics, central concepts in Evolution and Origin of Human Diseases will be discussed, and these will form the basis of the final exam.

fields.name: Human Rights and Human Security
Human Evolution
Existentialism in Literature and Philosophy
fields.description:
This course will explore Existentialism as an interdisciplinary (philosophical and literary) movement that arose mid-19th century  in response to the modern individuals (increasingly urban) existence in a world no longer God-sanctioned , and that remains relevant until this day, in the face of the challenges of our contemporary, globalizing world.

The course will focus on the close reading of important existentialist authors, such as Kierkegaard, Dostoevsky, Ellison, Kafka, Sartre, Fanon, De Beauvoir, Baldwin and Camus; but the course will also explore contemporary authors, such as David Foster Wallace, Zadie Smith and Haruki Murakami.

The objective of the course is to provide students with a thorough grasp of Existentialism, entering into a critical dialogue with its canonical and contemporary representatives and texts, reflecting on the contemporary relevance of notions such as: anxiety, freedom, boredom, commitment, alienation and authenticity  not as ready-for-use theoretical concepts but as aspects of human reality that require detailed description, analysis and reformulation, as that reality is also subject to constant change.

fields.name: Human Body - Anatomy and Physiology II
fields.description:
After this course the student has a concept of the bio-complexity of the human body and how this complex system is formed, organized and (dys)regulated.





This concept forms the basis for writing a newspaper article, the design of a functional concept of a cancer stem cell niche in brain tumors, understanding of the principles of life science research, and participating in a debate.

fields.name: Field course in Environmental Earth Sciences
fields.description:
The Field course Earth and Environmental Sciences will explore in the building of the Pyrenees. The Spanish Pyrenees form a beautiful outdoor laboratory to study dynamic mountain building. In this course we will focus on practical outdoor observation of the Earth, combining landscape and geology. The location offers superb examples of the development of a small scale mountain chain.

The first two weeks are spent preparing for the field work. This includes studying the relevant geological history, preparing the logistics, and learning analytical skills; furthermore mapping, structural geology techniques as well as techniques to study sedimentary layers and landscape will be introduced.

In the last two weeks of the course we will stay in the region of Ainsa and Jaca (in the province of Aragon). Students will unravel the geological history of a small region through careful mapping and interpretation of the collected data. This results in a reconstruction of the geological history in space and geological time. In the second week we will cross the Pyrenees and explore the structure and building of the mountain chain that has formed as a result of the collision between the Iberian Plate and the European Plate. We will observe large scale compressional processes as well as details in the rock record that illustrate the formation of the Pyrenees. The landscape of the Pyrenees is dramatically influenced by glacial processes that shaped the current topography. Various features in todays landscape can be immediately linked to the most recent ice ages and their impact on the Pyrenees.

This course is open for all students with a basic knowledge in geological sciences, and counts as a lab course. The field period is a very intense period, with a high work load, with full days in the field and analyses of the data in the evenings.

fields.name: Hormones and Homeostasis
Film Lab
fields.description: In the form of a one-month intensive course, Film Lab will instruct students on the basics of the practice of filmmaking, including cinematography, lighting and editing. The programme does not just cover the techniques, but considers their importance as part of a medium of communication: for example, how editing can foster both continuity and impact, how lighting affects depth of image and of meaning, and how framing and camera movement can be used as forms of storytelling, et cetera. Having first-hand experience with exploring these aspects, and the failures and successes produced by these attempts, will give students a better understanding of how film works (more specifically, why some films might work so well in certain ways, and others dont seem to work at all). That is, the academic merit of this course lies (as with AUCs Creative Writing and Performing Arts courses) in the fact that learning about the basic mechanics of the medium in practice will improve students critical-reflective understanding of that medium and the scholarship on it.

fields.name: Film Philosophy
fields.description:
Film is an object of philosophical reflection, and one of the questions this reflection can be seen to produce is whether  and if so, how  films themselves might be said to do philosophy. Accordingly, this course takes a two-pronged approach to the study of film philosophy.

After an introduction to both practices  what is philosophy? what is film (studies)? , this course will first discuss 4 major authors (representing the major approaches) in philosophy of film: namely, Andr Bazin, Gilles Deleuze, Stanley Cavell, and Vivian Sobchack. In these discussions, we will uncover the ways in which all these authors, in their different approaches, confirm film as offering a (philosophical) exploration of reality (rather than an ideologically regressive flight into fantasy). The contemporary relevance of these approaches will be uncovered by relating them to recent films, such as Atlantics (Diop, 2019), Girlhood (Sciamma, 2014), In the Mood for Love (Wong, 2000), and Portrait de la jeune fille en feu (Sciamma, 2019).

We will see that these approaches  as theorizations of the reality of film  offer different methodologies via which to think the other, subsequent question of this course, namely whether and how films can be judged to be philosophical in themselves. So, in the latter part of the course, we focus our attention on discussing how films can be said to offer thoughts, reflections, arguments, or other philosophical contributions on their own. We will discuss this via in-class case studies of different films, including one or more selected by students themselves.

fields.name: French
fields.description:
Students develop a basic knowledge of French grammar, syntax and vocabulary and learn how to handle successfully a variety of basic social situations they may encounter in daily life in French-speaking countries.
Students practice listening, speaking, reading and writing skills at a complete beginners level.
Students are introduced to the many French speaking cultures of different countries through short texts, videos, clips from the internet, magazines and newspapers.

fields.name: Freshwater and Marine Biology
fields.description:
The planet we live on appears blue from space because 70% of its surface is covered by water. Water is essential to all life on Earth. However, human impacts, such as eutrophication, chemical pollution, exploitation of aquatic resources and climate change threaten the functioning, health, and services of freshwater and marine ecosystems, and ultimately human life as well.  In this course you will learn to understand the key concepts in freshwater and marine biology, analyze the effects of human impact on aquatic ecosystems, and reflect on conservation and restoration measures of aquatic ecosystems on an overpopulated and industrialized planet. You will learn the key concepts and theories  i.e. how do freshwater and marine ecosystems function - through lectures, flipped classrooms, prescribed scientific papers, and a textbook.  The relevant questions in the field  i.e. how do human activities threaten freshwater and marine ecosystems - are addressed in highlight lectures given by experts in the field, and may address topics such as: 

Plastic in the ocean 
Climate change and ocean acidification  
Fragile aquatic ecosystems (e.g. coral reefs, the deep sea) 
Aquatic ecosystem services  
Harmful blooms  
Biodiversity, restoration & conservation  as part of an excursion to iconic human-made archipelago the Markerwadden.

fields.name: Fundamentals of Macro-Economics
fields.description:
Macroeconomics studies the economy as a whole, that is, the performance of national economies such as the Netherlands, of groups of countries such the as European Union, or the global economy. The performance of the macroeconomy has major direct impacts on the well-being of everyone in the economy, including yourself.

In this course we take discussions of concrete macroeconomic issues in the news and in the public debate as our starting point. This includes the conduct of fiscal and monetary in the context of the economic recovery from the Covid 19 pandemic, and the future of work in advanced economies and its implications for inequality. For each issue, we examine the arguments and views about the functioning of the macroeconomy expressed in the discussions in the news and the public debate. We then examine to what extent the empirical and theoretical findings of academic macroeconomics can help us to better understand the issue as well as the arguments expressed in the public discussion, using sources at the introductory and intermediate level. In this way you develop knowledge of key facts concerning the performance of economies (including how this performance is measured), and of the main theoretical frameworks that economists have developed to think about how economies function. You will practice applying your knowledge through a final project that could become your own contribution to the public debate and/or serve as an educational resource for people interested in macroeconomic issues.

fields.name: International Political Economy
Fundamentals of Micro-Economics
fields.description:
This course offers main theoretical concepts and policy applications in economics. Applying economic tools of analysis help students gain an understanding of how economic decisions are being made at the micro level (firms, households, government). Microeconomics also offers a normative perspective that helps evaluating observed (equilibrium) outcomes and the consequences of policy choices.
In particular, we cover topics in individual consumer choice, aggregate demand, evolutionary game theory, theory of the firm, market structures (perfect competition, monopoly, duopoly, oligopoly, monopolistic competition), market failures, and general equilibrium theory. The role of policy will be discussed throughout.
The course is divided in three main parts: (I) consumer theory, (II) producer theory, (III) welfare theory. 
The course is at the intermediate level and will in general prepare for (applied) courses in the social sciences and in particular for advanced level courses in economics, like Advanced Microeconomics (900331SSC), The Promotion and Regulation of the Economy (900332SSC) and Market Failure, Institutions and Economic Policy (900334SSC).

fields.name: Intermediate Programming: Principles and Practice
fields.description:
At the end of the course the student should understand the basic characteristics of programming languages. In particular, the student should: 

Know the notion of type and basics about different type systems (typed vs untyped languages) 
Know basics of complex data types: Lists and Arrays 
Know basics of scoping rules & parameter passing 
Know basic programming techniques and when to apply them: Iterative vs Recursive 
Know the basics of object oriented programming: Classes, Attributes, Methods, and Objects  
Become fluent in a programming language  
Know how to approach the learning of a new programming language

fields.name: Gastronomy: the Applied Sciences of Cooking
fields.description:
Gastronomy: The Arts & Sciences of Cooking epitomizes the liberal arts and sciences philosophy, because it focuses on the applications of sciences  physics, chemistry & biology  in one of the most basic life skills, cooking, and puts it into a broader societal and cultural perspective by using insights and theories from the social sciences and humanities.

The last fifteen years, since the advent of Molecular Gastronomy in the restaurant business, the field that combines the practice and science of cooking has become a legitimate scientific sub discipline. This manifests itself in master degrees in Gastronomy that are accredited worldwide (e.g. Wageningen University and Research Centre) and lectures series on the science of cooking that are offered at prestigious institutes like Harvard. AUC will be the first to offer a course on gastronomy in a bachelor program in the Netherlands.

This course will not only be theoretical and discursive, but will also contain cooking exercises. For how can anyone discuss the diversity of universal culinary systems without experientially partaking of food, through experiment, for the purpose of sensorial evaluation? (Hegarty, 2005; p. 7).

fields.name: Information Lab
fields.description: Upon completion of the course the students will be proficient with the tools, techniques and methodologies for Machine Learning and Data Science and will have gained insight into the daily practice of a modern Fintech company. Students will become familiar with all phases of the data science pipeline from data wrangling, extraction, transformation and loading through data cleansing, imputation, exploration to feature engineering and model selection, validation and refinement, data visualization and deployment. Among the Machine Learning techniques will be: linear and logistic regression, support vector machines, decision trees and random forests, principal component analysis, k-means, deep neural networks & natural language processing. Among the  software tools and libraries will be: Python, numpy, pandas, matplotlib, seaborn, scikit-learn, pytorch, emacs, org-mode, git, bash, GNUmake.

fields.name: Gender and Sexuality
fields.description: The study of gender and sexuality has constituted a crucial strand of cultural studies from the inception of the discipline through to the present day. This course on gender and sexuality studies traces trajectories of the field as they have emerged over time  from feminist theory to queer theory to trans studies and beyond. The course is interdisciplinary in nature, integrating a combination of both theoretical readings/primary texts, and the analysis of relevant objects within their socio-political context. Special emphasis is placed on the discussion of the social construction of sex and gender; the politics of identity and inequality; and the intersection of gender and sexuality with other markers of difference including race, religion, nationality, and class.

fields.name: Infectious Diseases
fields.description:
The student can explain the role and importance of infectious diseases and the combat against them in our society in the present as well as in the recent past.
The student can classify microbes studied in the field of microbiology, e.g. parasites, bacteria, and viruses and can describe their epidemiology.
The student can explain current concepts in infectious diseases and can describe microbial genome structure, as well as microbial gene and protein expression.
The student can describe different methods to detect pathogens.
The student can describe disease symptoms induced by the pathogens after infection in the human host.
The student can explain the relationship between parasites and host (e.g. way of entry, mechanism of disease), the immune reactions that follow infection, and the mechanism of vaccination as a way to prevent disease.
The student can define, investigate and present current knowledge gaps and possible answers in the field of Infectious Diseases in a clear effective way, both oral and in writing in order to communicate knowledge to a public consisting of either specialists or laypersons.

fields.name: Genes, Bioinformatics and Disease
fields.description: Students will study concepts and techniques related to traditional and modern genetics. The course provides students with a comprehensive overview of conjugation and recombination, gene regulation, forward and reverse genetics, gene linkage, mutagenesis screens, population genetics, genomics and functional genomics. The course also explores the applications of bioinformatics in modern life sciences.

fields.name: Immunology
fields.description:
After the course the student is able to explain in the context of human well-being:

The principles of innate and adaptive immunity, including their cell types, recognition structures and effector molecules
The tissue-specific requirements of the immune response
The mechanisms of the failures of immune responses, including uncontrolled infection, and development of allergy, autoimmunity and cancer
The way medications, in particular immunotherpy, may repair immune failures

fields.name: German
Global Identity
fields.description: This is a four-week intensive. We will hear, discuss, read, and reflect on identity and diversity issues in different contexts and, in relation to others and ourselves. More specifically, you will acquire basic knowledge of the central concepts and theoretical debates, learn to critically reflect on and analyze popular discourses and representations of identity and culture, and learn how to analyze and present your research about the subject. This course will build on the students diversity and differences and provide them with tools in order to more poignantly identify, address, and manage issues of identification, mechanisms of inclusion and exclusion at multiple levels, stereotypes, preconceptions, aiding their quest in becoming responsible researchers and citizens and civically engaged future leaders.

fields.name: Global Modern and Contemporary Art
fields.description:
This 200-level course, Global Modern and Contemporary Art, expands geographically and temporally on the 100-level survey of art history, Periods and Genres: Modern. During the first half of the semester, we will address Modern art in Africa, Asia, and South America, building upon such concepts as positivism, individualism, and progress. Several sessions will be devoted to each continent, focusing on modern art as an international phenomenon, and comparing local expressions with canonical examples from Europe. A variety of media will be addressed, including investigation of the South African magazine, Drum, the Post-Impressionist Storm Society in China, and Braslia in Brazil.

The second half of the course will address international contemporary art, attending to case studies of artists who work globallyas opposed to focusing on particular localesas so many contemporary artists do not confine their careers to their native countries, but rather live and work abroad. Identity is fluid, if not elusive, for many of these contemporary artists, so we will consider the contexts in which they operate, as well as the relationship between works of art and their sites of execution. Amongst the artists we will examine are Chinese artist Ai Weiwei, Iranian artist Shirin Neshat, and Columbian artist Doris Salcedo.

Throughout the semester, we will confront issues of postcolonialism, multiculturalism, exoticism, identity, and the politics of the cross-cultural gaze. Global Modern and Contemporary Art contributes to AUCs institutional goal of offering a culturally inclusive and global curriculum. Moreover, this course draws upon recent scholarly research and reflects the worldwide trend away from Eurocentric historiography.

fields.name: Health Lab
fields.description:
During this practical course we will investigate the human exposure to toxic chemicals in plasticizers, flame retardants and surfactants. These chemicals are added to many plastic consumer products, and some of these toxic additives leach from the plastic during use, resulting in potential human and environmental hazard.

Assessing human exposure to plasticizers, flame retardants and fluorinated surfactants . Students will wear silicone wristbands for several days. These wristbands will act as personal samplers and absorb the chemicals that they are exposed to during the day. Both chemical identification with mass spectrometry techniques and in-vitro bioassays will be applied to investigate the human exposure.
Fast screening of plastic additives in electronic equipment. Small plastic pieces of electronic equipment will be collected by the students. By using fast screening high resolution mass spectrometry techniques, the samples will be screened for flame retardants.
Identification of plasticizers and flame retardants in house dust. The students will collect house dust in their own homes. The house dust will be analysed for flame retardants and the relation with the electronics in the house will be investigated. The toxicity will be investigated with in-vitro bioassays.
In-vitro biotransformation of organophosphate flame retardants (PFRs). By using a rat liver enzyme system, the biotransformation of the selected PFRs will be investigated using mass spectrometry techniques.
Measurement of PFRs metabolites in urine. The identified metabolites found in the in-vitro biotransformation study will also be investigated in the urine samples.
A literature assignment followed by a presentation of a research paper dealing with human exposure to toxic chemicals related to plastic products and the indoor environment will be done at the end of the course.

fields.name: Probability and Statistics
fields.description:
1. Learn formal reasoning in terms of probability and gain intuition for randomness.



2. Get acquainted with statistical modeling and analysis.



3. Learn simple stochastic simulation schemes and statistical analysis tools in R.

fields.name: Principles of Private Law
Physics Lab
fields.description:
In almost all science disciplines, laboratory experimentation is key to model building, model verification, scientific progress and advances in various fields of technology.

After this course the student will have gained experience in:

- Getting introduced to a subject through literature.

- Formulating a research question or hypothesis.

- Translating a theoretical formulation/problem into a lab experiment.

- Designing a method for experimenting and measuring.

- Setting up an experiment by choosing suitable equipment (taking safety issues into consideration).

- Dimensioning an experiment.

- Conducting an experiment.

- Keeping a log book (documenting the entire experiment).

- Analyzing and interpreting the experimental data.

- Presenting results in tables and graphs.

- Evaluating the experimental data (including statistical analysis and computational processing).

- Estimating/calculating errors and accuracy.

- Connecting results with theoretical models and comparing with theory.

- Reporting in writing on the entire experimental process.

- Reporting in an oral presentation on the entire experimental process.

fields.name: Photograph as a Socio-Political Document
fields.description:
Students should be able to formally analyze photographs and have the capability to critically address images in a variety of contexts.

Contents:

The photograph as proof of what has been (according to Roland Barthes) is inextricably tied to claims of truth. What some viewers might see as merely an art object has had the power to change labor laws (photographs of children in factories), label people and objects (anthropology and natural science), prompt the establishment of national parks (photographs from expeditions in the American west), garnered support for environmental activists (images of Earth taken from space), and provoked debates on abortion (image of fetus on the cover of Life magazine) to name a few examples. This course will examine the history of photographs as they have functioned in the scientist's laboratory, the courtroom, and mass media. We will question the assumed veracity of the photograph and discuss how the photograph has been used as a device in argumentation.

fields.name: Philosophy of Science
fields.description:
- The student has achieved a broad knowledge of central debates in contemporary philosophy of science.



- The student understands the key concepts and arguments employed in these debates.



- The student is able to analyze these



concepts and arguments and engage critically with them.



- The student is able to present his/her own well-argued views regarding the nature of scientific knowledge and its role in todays culture and society.



- The student is able to apply the general philosophical analyses to concrete cases, especially from his/her own field of study.



- The student is able to give clear oral and written presentations on philosophical topics.

fields.name: Pharmacology
fields.description:
The student is able to:

Describe how drugs act (general principles, molecular aspects, cellular aspects)
understand how to assess ligand-receptor binding interaction
explain the theory of receptor occupancy and affinity (saturation vs competition)
understand how to assess ligand efficacy and potency
explain the theory of conformational equilibrium and efficacy (intrinsic activity), potency
carry out pharmacological experiments under the supervision of a lab assistant.
Understand how to perform binding and functional assays
analyse and interpret pharmacological data
calculate pharmacological parameters,  
report on the results of the pharmacological experiments.
explain how chemical mediators act (cholinergic system, noradrenergic transmission, local mediators)
describe processes that affect proliferation and play a role in cancer
describe how drugs act on the CNS
describe how drugs act on the heart and respiratory system
demonstrate competence in data presentation, analysis and interpretation, information retrieval and written communication.

fields.name: Perspectives on Economic Thought
fields.description:
Students gain understanding of fundamental questions in economic thinking in relation to other (social) sciences

Students are able to situate economics as a discipline in social and historical context

Students can relate modern and historical economic theories to currently observed phenomena such as climate change and inequality

Students have developed a critical understanding of different perspectives on economic thinking in relation to assumptions made

fields.name: Statistics for Sciences
fields.description:
At the end of the course the student can:

Summarize data using summary statistics and statistical plots
Compute probabilities based on principles and using probability functions
Investigate estimates for population parameters and their sampling distributions
Construct confidence intervals for population parameters
Perform hypothesis tests for population parameters
Conduct linear regression and analysis of variance
Perform simulations using statistical software

fields.name: Statistical Methods for Social Sciences Research
fields.description:
At the end of Statistical Research Methods, the student can 

graphically represent data appropriate to the data type, and summarize data in a few descriptive characteristics, such as sample mean and standard deviation 
apply the general rules of probability to random phenomena to compute the probability of an event, and use various probability models to describe the distribution of a variable (e.g., normal, binomial), compute probabilities using those models, or determine quantiles associated with probabilities 
use sampling distributions and the central limit theorem to compute probabilities associated with sample statistics 
construct confidence intervals for population means, population proportions, population mean differences, and differences between two population means or proportions, and interpret a confidence interval correctly 
perform an appropriate statistical test to investigate a hypothesis formulated from a research question, and interpret the results, including the z-test for proportions and changes in proportions and differences between proportions, the t-test for means and mean differences and differences between means, the chi-square test for goodness of fit, the chi-square test for association, and the t-test for a correlation 
explain the concepts of test statistic, P-value, Type 1 error, Type 2 error, power, and statistical significance, within the context of significance tests, and explain the relationship between confidence intervals and significance tests 
use ordinary least-squares linear regression to model the association between a continuous dependent variable and one or more quantitative independent variables, use a fitted linear regression model to make predictions about a dependent variable and to investigate a proposed mediation model among 3 or more variables 
use one-way analysis of variance (ANOVA), or regression analysis using dummy variables, to make inference about differences in the mean of a continuous variable among 3 or more factor groups, and when appropriate use a multiple pairwise comparison of means with an appropriate correction to perform a post-hoc test in ANOVA 
use two-way ANOVA to make inference about differences in the mean of a continuous variable among combinations of groups of two factors, including the presence of an interaction, and to investigate a proposed moderation model 
use SPSS for the implementation of all statistical procedures

fields.name: Life, Earth and Universe
fields.description: This course runs through all the natural sciences and revolves around the central concept of evolution, starting from the earliest stages of the Big Bang to the evolution of complex life on planet Earth. The concept of evolution is approached from various disciplines, emphasizing their interconnections. The focus will be on the evolution of the Universe, the evolution of planet Earth, and the evolution of Life.

fields.name: Linear Algebra
fields.description:
Linear algebra is a branch of mathematics that turns up in an enormous variety of contexts. One reason is that many processes can be described with reasonable accuracy by a linear approximation (in which nonlinear interactions are neglected).

Another reason is that some mathematical objects have an intrinsically linear structure (e.g. group theory and geometry).

fields.name: Statistical Mechanics
fields.description:
The student understands the microscopic foundation of thermodynamic concepts
The student understands the micro-canonical, canonical, and grand canonical ensembles, knows when to use them, and is able to compute means and standard deviations
The student is able to apply statistical mechanics to novel problems and appreciates the broad applicability of its techniques across the natural
sciences

fields.name: Linguistics
fields.description: We live in a world of language, but what is language really? This course focuses on the analysis of language at different levels (syntax, morphology, etc.) and from perspectives (language acquisition, variation, change and processing). Thus, students will not only look at what sentences, words and sounds are made of, but also how these components behave in the wild: how do we learn language; how and why does language vary historically, geographically and sociologically; and how is language processed in the brain? The aim of this course is to provide students with a solid and broad foundation in language and linguistics as a science, by addressing fundamental concepts, questions, theories and data.

fields.name: Risk Management and Natural Hazards
fields.description:
The student will be able to:

Understand the disaster risk equation and which factors determine a societys ability to manage the risk
Have in-depth knowledge of the emergency management cycle and understand how different domains and technology support its different phases
Conduct basic spatial analyses with the help of GIS in exploring hazard, exposure and vulnerability
Assess the degree of risk posed by natural hazards using modern geospatial analysis and visualization tools
Understand the role of community and citizens in actively participating in risk analyses by means of voluntary geographic information.
Support emergency planning with spatial tools.

fields.name: Logic, Information, Argumentation
fields.description: This course provides an introduction to basic concepts and tools from logic and argumentation that lie at the heart of rigorous scientific reasoning and practice. The students are trained in analytic and abstract thinking through the study of the formal systems of propositional, predicate and modal/epistemic propositional logic, which have broad applications in areas such as linguistics, psychology, philosophy, communication, cognitive science, computation and many more.

fields.name: Machine Learning
fields.description:
Machine Learning aims at methods for using (large) amounts of observational data to discover general patterns. This course will introduce students to basic algorithms for supervised learning

(classification and regression) and unsupervised learning (e.g. clustering). Topics include Linear Regression, Logistic Regression, Decision-Tree learning, Bayesian Learning, Neural Networks and Clustering. Students will develop an understanding of the fundamental concepts of machine learning using statistics and acquire skills in applying methods to real world learning problems. Students will implement algorithms in Python and learn to use a Machine Learning toolkit.

fields.name: Queering Media Studies
fields.description:
After successfully completing the course, the student is able to:
1. Demonstrate their knowledge and critically reflect on the historical development and main theoretical frameworks that constitute the field.
2. Appraise, apply and critique the discussed methodologies in order to undertake research and theoretical exploration into queer approaches to media studies.
3. Evaluate, discuss and critically engage with case studies of contemporary examples of queer approaches to media studies using course literature.
4. Apply theoretical frameworks and methodologies from the field of media and cultural studies to reflect upon and critically engage with the ways media has affects on and is affected by, queer experiences (of gender, race, sexuality, etc) as well as critically reflect on the possible influences of queer and non binary, feminist, POC and non mainstream users in shaping, and occupying media.
5. Analyze the complexity of medias entanglements within mind and body through empirical research, academic writing, discussions and presentations.

fields.name: Maker Lab
fields.description: AUC's open-inquiry Maker Lab course requires students to define their own research goals and experimental methods.  The freedom and flexibility to do so is enabled by ubiquitous solid-state sensors controlled by microcontrollers (Arduinos), which are matched with open-source code for data collection and analysis.  With powerful detectors in their hands, the world offers itself as the students laboratory, yielding unlimited data and unfiltered feedback to steer their investigations.  Students' projects are supported by (and participate in) the Maker* movement's resources of open-source software and hardware.  The students freedom in designing their own experiments means this course will suit a multi-disciplinary cross-section of science students stretching from the information track, to physical and environmental sciences, to bio-sciences and the health track.  As a bonus, students acquire transferable 21st century skills for their later careers, as more sectors are transformed by data analytics, remote sensing, and Internet-of-Things devices.

fields.name: Mathematics of Physics
fields.description:
This course introduces the student to a number of central concepts and techniques in mathematical physics.
We start introducing the necessary background on sets, functions, and the notions of homomorphism and isomorphism. We practice mathematical proofs for these notions. Tensors are then introduced, and tensor calculus is developed. Groups and representations are defined, and we study in detail two groups that are of central importance in physics: the rotation group SO(3) and the spin group SU(2), their geometrical interpretation, and their representations, which we then apply to quantum mechanics.
In the second part of the course, after a review of Maxwells theory and its reformulation in terms of gauge potentials and tensors, we study in some detail the theory of special relativity, applied to classical electrodynamics. Finally, we study various symmetries of classical electrodynamics: its covariance, gauge invariance, and conservation laws.

fields.name: Medicinal Chemistry
fields.description: Medicinal Chemistry is an highly interdisciplinary discipline at the interface of chemistry and biology. In this course a general introduction will be given to the process of drug discovery, drug design and synthesis, drug development and drug safety assessment. Subsequently, potential drug targets, mechanisms of drug actions (including drug- receptor/enzyme interactions and dose- response relations), drug disposition (including pharmaco-/toxicokinetics) and drug toxicity will be discussed. Using various drug classes, relationships between chemical structures and biological activities will be derived and illustrated. Various modern developments and tools will be illustrated by recent applications in the field of medicinal chemistry. Finally, intellectual property as well as production aspects will be discussed.

fields.name: Quantum Physics
fields.description:
General goal: students understand the fundamental concepts of quantum mechanics and are able to apply its techniques in a variety of situations. Concretely, the learning outcomes are:


1. The student is able to discuss the basic experiments and ideas that lead to quantum mechanics and to explain why the classical mechanics fails in explaining quantum phenomena.

2. The student is able to explain the basic concepts and physical principles underlying quantum mechanics: particle-wave duality, Heisenbergs uncertainty principle, non-locality, complementarity, etc.

3. The student is able to apply the mathematical formalism of quantum mechanics in a variety of problems. Specifically:

4. The student is able to solve the Schrdinger equation for a number of given potential functions, including three-dimensional potentials, under specified initial conditions.

5. The student is able to analyse the spectrum of eigenvalues and eigenfunctions of the Hamiltonian (continuous, discrete, etc.) and to normalize the wave-functions under given physical conditions.

6. The student is able to use the Dirac notation and use it to compute physical observables.

7. The student is able to distinguish operators that correspond to observables from those that dont, and is able to characterize the main properties of operators (self-adjoint, unitary, etc.).

8. The student is able to solve basic problems involving special functions (Legendre, Laguerre) and to build up spherical harmonics using special functions.

9. The student is able to discuss and interpret the physical meaning of observables and predict the possible outcomes of (series of) measurements with their respective probabilities.

10. The student is able to relate and compare the Schrdinger and matrix formalisms.

11. The student is able to solve the Schrdinger equation for systems with spin  or 1, and to combine low spin states to high-spin states.

12. The student is able to apply ladder operators and the angular momentum algebra to systems with angular momentum or spin.

13. The student is able to explain the basic building-up of the periodic table from the principles of quantum mechanics.

14. The student is able to relate operators and states in quantum mechanics to classical quantities and also to differentiate them.

15. The student is able to analyse and discuss a conceptual problem about quantum mechanics without doing calculations.

fields.name: Metabolic Biochemistry
fields.description: The aim of the course is to give the students a thorough understanding of how human metabolism is organized and regulated at the molecular, cellular, organ and organism level. Starting from basic cellular chemical processes in obtaining energy from food (part 1), we will study metabolic organization at the multi-organ level (part 2). This will be studied both in healthy and diseased states, including inherited diseases, based on the principles of homeostasis. Finally, the impact of lifestyle, diet, sports and alcohol abuse are discussed (part 3). Major health issues related to deranged metabolism, especially obesity, diabetes, chronic inflammation and cardiovascular diseases are discussed, as are molecular modes of action of several of the best known major drug classes, like statins and aspirin.

fields.name: Quantum Information and Quantum Communication
fields.description:
After successfully completing the course, the student is able to:

1. Use techniques from quantum information theory to solve problems about quantum communication and quantum computation.

2. Describe in mathematical detail some of the main protocols for quantum key distribution (such as BB84) and assess their limitations.

3. Describe in mathematical detail some of the main algorithms for quantum computing (such as Grovers search algorithm).

4. Discuss the main technologies used for quantum information processing, and understand their challenges and limitations.

5. Discuss the societal impact of quantum technologies and ethical and legal aspects thereof.

fields.name: Migration, Integration and Diversity
fields.description:
By the end of this course, students should be able to:

Appreciate the complexity of the processes of migration from different perspectives
Develop and present persuasive oral and written arguments related to migration and displacement
Critically analyse, from an interdisciplinary perspective, the challenges of diversity through migration histories and trajectories
Engage in contemporary debates on integration responses from an interdisciplinary perspective, drawing on insights from historical experiences and current cases
Think critically about policies related to refugees and forced migration and the resolution of displacement crises

fields.name: Modelling Real World Problems
fields.description: This course will focus on modelling real world phenomena, ranging from physical to sociological processes. After an introduction to modelling and simulation as the third paradigm of science, we cover two methods for modelling real world systems: Cellular Automata and Complex Networks. The course provides basic understanding of both methods and introduces well-known examples for each approach. Practical experience is obtained with lab sessions in which students will familiarise themselves with basic tools and techniques in Cellular Automata modelling and Complex Network Analysis.

fields.name: Molecular Cell Biology
fields.description: This course focuses on the functioning of cells and the techniques used to study them. In this course, the different parts of cells are introduced, and how these different constituents function in relation to each other is discussed. The course also explores how cells interact with cells in their direct vicinity as well as cells at a distance. Next, the interactions of cells with the extracellular environment and their role as part of a multicellular organism are covered using interactive lectures and recent scientific papers. The following topics will be discussed and presented: Organelles of the cell; Molecular constituents such as DNA, RNA and proteins; Regulation of gene expression; Cell-cell interactions; Cell cycle; Signal transduction ; Energy generation; Cell-extracellular matrix interactions; Cell migration; Cell death; Different cell types in different tissues.

fields.name: Qualitative Research Methods
fields.description:
In terms of knowledge, the student will be able





 To understand and be able to define the key concepts, principles, and methods used in Qualitative Research and understand the kind of knowledge that these methods generate



 To understand the key debates in Qualitative Research Methods



 To discern which qualitative research methods to use and when and how to employ them



 To conduct a qualitative research in an ethical way (obtaining informed consent, safeguarding the interviewees anonymity)



 To plan, design, and conduct qualitative research in the form of a small study (on a subculture of their choice)



 To work with, analyse, and interpret qualitative data



 To write a research report based on the qualitative data that they have collected on their own In terms of skills, the students will improve:


 Their skill to effectively present  verbally and in writing  her/his acquired knowledge on qualitative research methods (and subcultures)

 Their skills to identify and effectively read, analyze, and assess (the quality of) ethnographies and other scholarly work involving qualitative research methodology

 Their debating skills

 Their observation skills

 Their qualitative interviewing skills

 Their sensory perception

 Their analytical and critical thinking skills

 Their reflexivity, i.,e., their ability to critically reflect on their own position in the research field and its impact on the study, the impact as well as the benefits and limitations of the methods and theory used




 The development of adequate, concise, and constructive research questions



 The writing of a research proposal



 The writing of a research report

fields.name: Molecular Sustainability
fields.description: The current climate crisis is intimately connected to excess of carbon dioxide (CO2) due to burning fossil fuels. In Nature CO2 is part of the already for three billion years existing closed loop of the photosynthesis driven carbon cycle. What are sustainable molecular alternatives for fossil fuels? Can we also use CO2 as feedstock for fuels and materials? Can we design zero emission energy carriers?  How to store wind and solar energy into chemical bonds? Also there is a great need for closed loop cycles for depleting elements such a phosphorus but also metals. But also to find solutions for a sustainable production and more circular use of bound nitrogen. In other words, what are the problems that have to be solved on the molecular level to arrive at a sustainable society with respect to our energy, fertilizer and materials needs.

fields.name: Psychology
fields.description: After completing the course, students will be able to describe the theories and concepts covered with regards to: the basic scientific methodology used in psychology; the genetic and evolutionary basis of behaviour; the structure and functioning of the brain, learning, motivation and emotion, visual perception, memory, consciousness, intelligence and reasoning, cognitive and social development, social perception and attitudes, social influence, and personality.

fields.name: Molecular Techniques Lab
fields.description:
The course is divided in two parts, where students will first expand their background knowledge on molecular techniques, before performing research themselves in the second part.  

In the first two weeks, guest lecturers will provide interactive sessions on state of the art molecular techniques and how they are used in everyday research. The content is organised around the central dogma in molecular biology: from gene to protein. Students will prepare for the lab by putting the scientific method into practise via a COVID-19 assignment and lab introduction. Finally, also the ethical aspects of research are discussed, specifically concerning gene editing and the principles of open science.  

In the second part of the course, students develop practical skills in recombinant DNA technology and Biochemistry. The Molecular techniques used are the core of the Molecular Biology and Biochemistry fields and are often applied in biomedical- and cell biology research. The student will also be introduced to several bioinformatics tools and computer programs that are often used in these fields. The techniques in the course include: BLAST, (in silico) cloning, (colony)PCR, gel-electrophoresis, DNA digestion, ligation, transformation, sequencing, protein purification, enzymatic activity determination protein identification through mass spectrometry. The course is set up as a short internship where you start from the current literature to develop a hypothesis, which can then be tested in the lab in the practical part of the course.

fields.name: Moot Court Lab
fields.description:
This course lets student take an intensive approach to preparing for developing and
delivering an international legal argument before the International Court of Justice. Students
will receive training and work on drafting a Memorial for their respective sides in a legal
dispute, setting out a convincing argument on the basis of international legal sources.
Participating students will also undergo intensive training to practice pleading before a
panel of judges. At the end of the course, students will plead their case before a panel of
judges that will consist of experts on international law.

fields.name: Programming Your World
fields.description:
Algorithmic thinking: the ability to analyse a computing problem, articulate it clearly, design a solution and implement that solution in a working computer program.
Ability to communicate with computing professionals, express information processing needs and have an understanding of what can be realised technically.
We view programming as an empowering and organisational tool and aim to develop an awareness of how the computer can be controlled by writing clear, correct and efficient programs which can be applied in any area of study.

Having successfully completed the course the student will have a practical understanding of the fundamentals of computer programming, will be able to design programs from scratch, understand programming interfaces and apply them to his/her needs and to communicate with computing professionals.

fields.name: Nanoscience
fields.description: This course will focus on the properties of materials  from bulk to nanoscale.  We will first dive into the microscopic structure of materials to understand how atoms bond and how the symmetry of the lattice changes the behavior of the material in bulk.  We will explore the deep origins of the electronic and optical differences between metals, semiconductors and insulators.  We will then further explore how scaling down to the quantized and/or quantum regimes further modifies and fine-tunes these properties, giving rise to the modern field of nanoscience.  We will study some special properties of nano-materials which underlie advanced technologies in energy, electronics, and medicine.

fields.name: Numerical Mathematics
fields.description: Numerical mathematics is used frequently in all areas of science (e.g. fluid dynamics, meteorology and financial risk management). In many applications one encounters mathematical problems that cannot be solved through manipulations of formulas and, in such cases, numerical methods are used. These algorithms, implemented in computer programs, are at the core of scientific computing. In this course, students will learn the mathematical principles behind these numerical techniques and will apply them to non-trivial problems in applications outside of mathematics. The course focuses on the main numerical methods from modern day analysis and scientific computing. The theory is implemented in hands-on practical assignments. The list of subjects includes: error analysis, systems of linear equations, eigenvalue problems, interpolation, least square methods, fast Fourier transform, non-linear equations and ordinary (and partial) differential equations. Applications include Google page rank, data analysis and planetary orbits. A number of Matlab assignments will also form an integral part of the course.

fields.name: Nutrition and Health
fields.description:
Almost every person is an expert on nutrition and has ideas on the relationship between nutrition and health, either scientifically or not-scientifically proven. A well-known saying is therefore: More is known about nutrition than is true.

But how do you interpret messages in the media on nutrition? Is milk either healthy or unhealthy? Do you develop extra muscle from eating lots of protein? Do fibers protect you from developing colon cancer? Is it necessary to take vitamin supplements in order to stay healthy?

To be able to answer these complex questions, in-depth understanding in nutrition is required. Which nutrients form the basis of our daily meals and what is their specific role in the human body? Moreover, it is important to be able to interpret results on nutrition research correctly. How do you measure nutritional intake in groups or individuals, and what are the pros and cons? And how do you measure body composition and how should you interpret the results?

In the first half of the course the focus will be on (physiology of) macro- and micronutrients. The second half of the course will focus on nutrition research (methods) and nutrition worldwide.

fields.name: Organic Chemistry
fields.description: On the molecular level, life is based on Organic Chemistry. Crude oil is a remnant of ancient life and products derived thereof are also made via organic chemical processes. For these reasons Organic Chemistry plays a central role in molecular sciences. This course provides an introduction to Organic Chemistry and focusses on the properties of organic molecules and their reactivities. This will be tought in a conceptual way focussing on reaction mechanisms using curly arrows showing the course of the flowing electrons. The influence of inductive and conjugative electronic effects in combination with sterics on the outcome of reactions will be the thread in the course. To give an impression of the work of an organic chemist in the lab three practical days are scheduled. Also you have to dig in the literature to find out how an important organic molecule is made and present this to your peers. The ten two hour lectures are followed by a two hour tutorial session. The goal of the course is to gain insight into the properties, reactivity and synthesis of organic molecules.

fields.name: Partial Differential Equations
fields.description:
The majority of physical phenomena can be described by partial differential equations (Maxwell equation for electromagnetism, Schrdinger equation in quantum mechanics, Einstein equation in general relativity, diffusion equation in thermodynamics, wave equation in optics). Partial differential equations are also fundamental in the life sciences (reaction-diffusion equations) and economics (e.g. Black-Scholes equation).

This module discusses these equations and the methods for their solution. For example, for the heat and wave equation we discuss the method of separation of variables. This ties in with the remarkable result of Fourier that almost any periodic function can be represented as a sum of sines and cosines, called its Fourier series. An analogous representation for non-periodic functions is provided by the Fourier transform (and the closely related Laplace transform). We shall also discuss the the role of eigenvalue problems and some basic spectral theory, as well as fundamental solutions and associated Green  s formulas.

fields.name: Peace Lab
fields.description: This course provides field training and experience in hands-on qualitative research, as well as experience with methodologies in the peace-building, peace-making and peace-keeping fields. It is a unique opportunity for students to compare and contrast theory and practice.

fields.name: Topics in Global History
fields.description: Students will learn to critically assess claims made in todays public debates, examine them in a historical perspective, understand key positions taken by historians and social scientists, learn to apply key analytical methods, develop an interdisciplinary perspective, and stake out well-argued positions of their own in writing and speaking.

fields.name: Thermodynamics
fields.description:
The student is able to understand and apply the basic principles of thermodynamics and statistical physics: the First, Second and Third Laws, heat and work, entropy, interacting systems, thermal equilibrium, phase transitions, free energy and chemical equilibrium.
The student is able to apply the methods of thermodynamics to a variety of problems ranging from physics to biology to engineering.
The student is able to perform independently (without recourse to any material) thermodynamic symbolic and numerical calculations on the level of the examples and problems of the textbook.
The student is able to evaluate modern topics in thermodynamics (e.g. as discussed in the research literature) and discuss about these in writing and in presentations.

fields.name: Urban Environment Lab
fields.description:
This course focuses on the science and social science of urban environment planning. The lab takes an evidence-based approach to the problem of climate change and spatial planning. More specifically, we will explore the urban heat island effect in Amsterdam using a range of spatial analysis tools and methods.

Students will measure this effect in small groups, statistically link obtained local temperature measurements to environmental characteristics and assess potential future changes in urban temperatures in Amsterdam based on socio-economic and climate scenarios. Following this assessment solution strategies will be proposed to limit local temperature increases. Finally, an attempt is made to evaluate the effectiveness of these strategies

fields.name: The Promotion and Regulation of the Economy
fields.description:
Understanding of the notion of market failure, the role of regulation and the role of antitrust.
Use of economic models to gain insight into the effects of market failure on social outcomes.
Market diagnosis: Identification of situations where competitive forces are weak.
Prescription of public policy measures intended to deal with diagnosed problems.
Discussion of real-world experiences of abuse of dominant position, cartel agreements and merger cases.
Application of game theory and microeconomic tools to analyze such market phenomena as collusion, abuse of dominance, merger decisions, pricing and regulation of natural monopoly.
Understanding of the trade-offs and limitations to policy choices when policy makers are ill-informed, captured, or when markets are highly dynamic (innovation and platforms).
Statistical analysis and interpretation of empirical economic data drawn from relevant case studies and markets.

fields.name: Vector Calculus
fields.description:
This course deals with the extension of single-variable calculus into
three dimensions, including line and surface integration and the
classical theorems by Green, Gauss and Stokes:
1. Vectors and coordinate geometry in 3-space
2. Vector functions and curves
3. Functions of two and more variables, partial derivatives
4. Gradient and directional derivatives
5. Optimization
6. Implicit function theorem
7. Multiple integration and iterated integration
8. Polar and spherical coordinates
9. Line integrals and vector fields
10. Surfaces and surface integrals
11. Divergence and rotation
12. Theorems of Green, Gauss and Stokes
13. Applications

fields.name: Violence and Conflict
fields.description: This course will provide an introduction into the field of conflict studies, investigating the escalation of non-violent conflict into mass-violence and exploring international responses to violent conflict. We will first look at the dynamics of inter-group conflict, focusing specifically on conflict between ethnic groups, including genocide. We will then move to the analysis of militarized conflicts, focusing mainly on intra-state (civil) wars. What motivates groups to pick up arms against a government? How do rebel groups organise and arm themselves? Why do some rebel groups manage to overthrow a government, while others collapse? How can we explain diverging patterns of violence in civil wars? Drawing on this analysis, international responses to violent conflict will be investigated, including humanitarian relief and peacekeeping. A recurring theme throughout the course will be the connections between processes of state-formation and violence, both in Western and non-Western settings.

fields.name: The Human Body - Anatomy and Physiology
fields.description:
The student is able to:

define and use correctly a range of anatomical terms
describe the histological structure and relate it to the function of the fundamental human tissue types
describe the structure and function of the nervous system and explain transmission and the action of drugs on the nervous system 
describe the structure of the respiratory system and physiological systems involved in transport of oxygen around the body and the removal of waste products
explain the principles of homeostasis and describe the roles of the neural system in its maintenance
describe the structure of the respiratory system and physiological systems involved in transport of oxygen around the body and the removal of waste products
describe the development, role, structure and function of skeletal muscle fibres and the organisation and function of the muscular system
describe the composition and function of blood and overview the structure and regulation of the cardio-vascular system including the heart, the vascular system
describe how the renal system works
explain the regulation of fluids and electrolytes
demonstrate competence to interactively discuss physiological processes in the body analyse and interpret data during practical courses

fields.name: Visual Culture
fields.description:
This course explores the field of visual culture, which emerges at the intersection of art history, media studies, anthropology and cultural studies. Visual culture investigates both the prominence of the visual  the saturation of everyday life with images and visual artefacts - and visuality  the constructed ways of looking that shape how we see. We will explore scholarship proposing that the act of looking is a socially constructed process which varies across time and place.

We begin by tracing visuality in history, considering discourses surrounding optics, vision, sight and seeing over time. Can we associate a particular way of seeing with modernity, or postmodernity? What technologies and techniques have shaped ways of seeing from history into the present? And what visual artefacts have these ways of seeing produced?

fields.name: Text Mining
fields.description:
The student develops an understanding of the basic concepts and techniques used to mathematically represent and model language, including their underpinnings in linguistics.
The student develops programming skills for automatically extracting and processing textual data from different sources (such as textual corpora and social media).
The student is familiar with the main approaches to distributional semantics, including modern deep learning techniques, and is able to automatically extract distributional information from corpora.
The student is able to automatically characterise the semantic content of a document.
The student develops programming skills necessary for building his/her own text mining application (e.g., a search engine or a recommender system) by exploiting statistical learning approaches.

fields.name: System Earth
fields.description:
After successful completion of this course the student is able to:
 characterize the major characteristics and processes of the Earth's spheres 
 Understand how the different earth sciences (atmospheric science, oceanography, geology, glaciology, hydrology, biogeochemistry, etc) are related to each other and to the more disciplinary natural sciences such as physics, chemistry and biology
 understand the Earth as a complex system, which includes interactions and feedbacks between the different spheres and how these can lead to both stability and change over different timescales
 Analyze and understand source-sink relationships, stock and flow problems, and simple chemical kinetics in biogeochemical cycles
 apply a systems approach to studying earth science, combining analytical and integrating skills
 critically evaluate the role of human activity in influencing (the interactions between) the earths spheres, climate, and biogeochemical cycles
 assess a sub-field within earth system science based on a literature review and present their assessment to others

fields.name: Neuroscience
fields.description:
In the Neuroscience course we aim to provide students with a fundamental understanding of how the brain works and how neuroscientists learn about the central nervous system. Besides quenching a thirst for fundamental knowledge, we address a very important issue in modern preclinical and clinical Neuroscience, viz. how do malfunctions of the central nervous system lead to neurologic and psychiatric disease? Emphasis will lie on studying the normal function of the brain, but we will also explore ways to translate fundamental experimental knowledge to clinical practice.

The course has a strongly neurobiological character. We will study the organization and function of the nervous system by looking at the molecular and cellular components that constitute the nervous system and the way neural cells are organized in neural circuits which, in turn, make up neural systems that process similar kinds of information, i.e. the sensory, motor and associational systems. It will become clear how we can study the brain???s physiology and pathophysiology using structural, functional and behavioral analyses.

It will be impossible to cover all topics in the multidisciplinary field of Neuroscience and we will, therefore, study and discuss selected textbook chapters supplemented by original research papers. To emphasize and realize the experimental basis of our knowledge, we will spend a fair amount of time discussing experiments described in the research papers that form the basis of or are related to the book chapters.

fields.name: International law
fields.description: This course provides an introduction to public international law. Students are introduced to the basic principles and foundations of international law; to some of its central topics; and by means of several ???close ups??? they are asked to engage with topical issues of international law. The fundamental idea underlying this course is that international law has over the last decades been witness to radical changes as regards the relevant actors and the kinds of issues and developments covered by international law. This means that a singular focus on the state ??? the primary actor in international law ??? no longer ???does the job??? if the aim is to understand the international legal system. Therefore, the course emphasizes not just the role of the state, but also the rise of other actors and developments, and what these new participants and influences do to existing legal rules.

I liked the project and the readings (when I did them) were interesting but classtime was insufferable as this teacher couldn't sustain an interesting conversation among students as he went to deep into the readings that nobody did. for anyone who likes philosophy or is just interested in the subject, this is a great course which i highly recommend. the lecturer is very profound and understanding, but there are a lot of readings. besides that, there isn't a lot of workload

Such a boring course and awful representation of the other environmental courses at AUC. Teachers did not seem to coordinate with each other, course is mostly focussed on agriculture, tutorials were a waste of time.

Casper...... What more is there to say? 

Also the grading sucks ass. Like seriously how can a teacher be this good and then have bad grading. His teaching is literally transcendental. I'm convinced he's at the very least some kind of minor divinity, but he could just be god idk

Easy course and very interesting. Would recommend to anyone slightly interested in either economics or environment. Just don't expect to go into that much depth on either. He really puts in effort to make sure everyone understands the material and is very funny
This is a nice course, but can be really difficult without a background in biology. The course starts with philosophy and then different medical fields.

This is not a course. This is an exercise in your ability to handle mind numbing, tedious work for hours every week, while also not losing your mind (this part is optional though and I didn't do it). Agree with previous reviews, Cas is an actual god and also my father (I've decided so). Was a really fun and fairly easy course. Exams are open book and assignment are take home and fairly doable. Angelika loves to look people directly in the face if she thinks you look like someone that'd speak that language eventhough you don't. Angelika is still mainly unproblematic and very passionate. This really helps with the course. If you don't like going on tangents in the middle of class on some obscure linguistic thing then don't take the course.
Great intro to the field! Especially when it gets past the theories in the first part of the course. Would recommend to most people honestly

For me this course was really fun. The exams are hard and barely any of it is covered in class. I'm sure Sara will make some changes for next spring. The theory isn't difficult and if you just do the readings and exercises along the way the exams aren't hard. Music history is a lot but doable. I took this course during the second semester of my first year (2021), so things may have changed. But there was virtually no organization or support from both professors. such an interesting class!! you learn a lot of new information, which is nice because you aren't just repeating high school biology. the exams are kind of tough just because it's a large syllabus taught at a fast pace, but they're easy to score in if you do the readings regularly.

relatively easy (especially if you've done high school biology). the part I found annoying was the philosophy bits, but it's still interesting. be prepared for a lot of reading in the first few weeks!
Really bad class overall

Not a good course. The teacher (Brendan) reads off of his slides in the dryest manner. He does not teach, he is not a teacher. I have taken this course and have learnt absolutely nothing. I don't believe that all the course material is relevant for someone in the Humanities, which is my case. Fallacies were cool, but other than that I did not find anything useful. Course might be better if you have someone better in engaging and explaining, but should be reworked to be more comprehensible and relevant to all

If you want to take an easy but VERY interesting and engaging science course, this is the one! It is very surface-knowledge, well-structured in terms of workload, and very doable. Luis is beyond helpful, both in class and during office hours (for example if you missed a class or have something unclear). Every problem, topic, and exercise is demonstrated in class, which makes the classes engaging and definitely not boring. The exams are just like the mock exams in terms of difficulty. Overall, one of the best courses I've taken at AUC, so I recommend it!

This course is extremely white washed. Youll only discuss North America and Europe. It is purely theoretical and none of the lectures actually ****yze case studies of real events. Youll start by learning some abstract concept related to liberal democracy, then in the second half of the semester youll go over one alternate political model per lecture (fascism, nationalism, oligarchy etc). The class discussions are poorly led by the professor and never go into any depth or nuance. It is currently week 12 of the semester and the professor has not put a single grade into Canvas. This course is uninteresting and poorly constructed.

More so a history of political thought than anything else. It does not synthesize how this leads us to the modern era of politics and is not critically engaging. This might be due to the teacher at the time being Alison Wilson, rather than Melvin Schut who is new to AUC and lecturing at large.

Very interesting course on Affect theory and a broader interpretation of emotion. You read a lot of relevant and interesting authors and the teacher, Alexandra Brown, knows how to engage the class very well. It is high-level philosophy that is made understandable very well. The assignments are good and feasible. A lot of reading though, but that is 300-level philosophy.

Take this course. Allard is an amazing teacher and the course materials are extremely interesting. You can tell Allard knows immense amounts about it, but knows how to engage the classroom very well as well. There are a lot of readings, sometimes complicated, but this is 300 level philosophy. This course is so chaotic, the teachers dont really know what theyre talking about half the time, and the course material is all over the place. The Excel assignments are hard to navigate.

Professor is absolutely lovely, but is almost too good of a presenter: hard to follow his lecture notes after class if you missed the class because he explains everything verbally. Also one of the courses where there is a mock exam so you can get a good feel about what the exam questions are like (and between you and me, the mock exam questions are usually rattther similar to the actual exam ones- iirc grades were high 70% as an average).

Super fun course with a lovely professor, absolutely fascinating content. A must-take if you're interested in psychology. The first assignment is a Reflective Essay which was also (personally) incredibly fun to write (and a fresh breath of air from the high school 'reflective essays'). There's quite a bit of readings, and you will fall behind if you don't do them. Study tip for students planning on taking this: in the textbook there are little green boxes with "Focuses" that ask questions, the exam questions are usually a bit broader but very similar to these.
Is rly useful for (health) science majors (more so than linear algebra imo). However there isnt a lot of application to real data
Its kinda fun and really chill cause u only have to do a few assignments but not rly anything outside of class!

The course can get a little boring and one of the assignments is graded externally (by not-so-nice ppl) so its kind of unnecessary. Especially since you do the topics in other health-related courses, there isnt much added value

the class is lowkey repetitive for anyone who puts some effort. Also, the exams are just memorization of slides so whoever wants to understand stuff should consider learning stupid sidefacts instead :/
For science majors the neural part is kinda dull but otherwise it is a fun and interesting course. You have to do a lot of readings but they are interesting so i think its totally fine
The course is taught so well with interesting guest lectures and challenging questions that focus on understanding instead of memorization!
While the course is quite interesting, some of the topics are not explained so well. Overall good tho
It has been helpful to learn how to structure an essay and cite properly. Mr. Falahati is generally nice and helpful. However, a lot of the classes and assignments are tedious.

The content is interesting but the classes bore me to death. The teacher spends the whole class talking in a monotonous manner. The curriculum is almost exclusively white men. The course consists of reading texts, ****ysing them in class and in essays. The texts and class can be a bit dry at times but overall a nice introductory class. The economists in the curriculum are very diverse which I think makes the course more interesting. The teacher is nice. Takes a long time to grade things though.

this course provides a good introduction into the field of cultural ****ysis and cultural studies.
