Assignments are guided but still challenging, also offering you the opportunity to write about your own chosen object, giving you some creative freedom. The course also highlights some common methods and schools of thought used in humanities.

I guess I see the point of trying to get students to understand how to construct logical arguments, but overall I wouldn't say the course has many practical applications. Unless you really like math or puzzles. The teacher did not help that much but the preparatory materials were good. If you're interested in linguistics you can have some interesting conversations with Emile, he has a sense of humor and is very chill.

I recommend the class if you can handle a high workload and are very passionate in the philosophies that founded economics today.

I do want to highlight that the professor is passionate about the subject. It is clear that she understand the subjects very well and, when she teaches a concept, it is easy to comprehend. However, this does not become clear due to the class' structure. She is also, as I will emphasise later, receptive to feedback, so don't be discouraged by my review!

Because each class has the same structure everyday, it makes it a little boring: A discussion about the author you learnt before class, and then a presentation from a student. On top of that, the first half of the course is mostly philosophical, and only the second half are you taught only the most basic parts of economics, which is not clear on the description of the course.

The workload is, also, way too extreme. You have to write a one page summary on a certain concept for a new author before every class. And this is not for participation, but the entire thing is graded. On top of that you also have to do a final project in which you have to interview professionals in the field and have to write a whole research paper about (or any project you would like, it just has to be long). And then you also have in-class tests, which can be impossible to understand what to improve on since feedback is very specific.

But do not feel discouraged! I think this is only the first year she has taught it, and I feel like it will change a lot after this semester. Contrary to what I have said, I would recommend taking it! But please talk to the professor through out the class and let you standards in the class be known. She is receptive to feedback and if you read the syllabus and assignments, and think that it will be (or is) too overwhelming, let her know as soon as possible.

Text Mining is a programming course fully thought in Python. I only did programming your world and had no prior programming experience and managed to complete the course with a good grade. However, since it is a 300 level course I do recommend to be comfortable with programming in python. If PYW was hard for you I do not recommend jumping straight to text mining but the course is doable without doing the course AI or data structures. 
The lectures of the course are completely unnecessary to follow. The lectures talk about paradigms within the field, statistical models behind the programming etc. but not about the programming itself. There are some jupyter notebooks provided with examples of actual programming. So all assignments and projects are done by looking at the examples and copy paste that code and modifying were needed. The only plus side of this is that you actually do some programming, I heard (do not know from experience) courses like modelling real world problems dont have much actual programming involved. 

In first half of the course, weekly (or every other week, cant remember) assignments were given. These were very big and time consuming so be prepared for that. 

Since the lectures were unnecessary I am tempted to say I think the lecturer was not the best. However, I do need to say he was an understanding and thoughtful lecturer. Responds to emails within 30 mins and always gave deadline extensions when asked for. Also for the whole class. I was not the fast with grading tho.   

In conclusion, not the best course in general but from what I heard about the other level 300 programming courses, this course involved most actual programming which makes it the best level 300 pick for information track students in my opinion.

The teacher is absolutely amazing. If you show up to class you will learn everything that is required and only have to review for exams. The class is engaging and the content interesting. The course includes at least 3 excursions as well. I overall enjoyed the course, and its not too stressfull.

The success of the course for you fully depends on your teacher. While I find the content super fun and interesting, my teacher explained concepts with lots of difficulty. While it is clear he understands what he is teaching, it does mean you have to teach yourself everything, which is a bummer. Because of these circumstances, even the easiest tests were hard. If you want to learn the basic historical narratives that most other classes criticize, this is the class to take. This course should not exist or be mandatory for Social science or humanities majors.

The easiest class I've ever taken. I would recommend it for anyone who needs their Humanities requirement. You can get an easy 8/10 without paying any attention, and you get a lot of freedom with the final project. Prof is kind of boring tho.

The content was indeed interdisciplinary, and the excursions were fun but the course was held in December so they are unpleasant. Would recommend if you need/want an easy BQ, but not if you want something interesting or challenging.

Anne is just the sweetest being, always emphasizing the importance of taking care of ourselves when dealing with such harsh topics. Hated this course. It made me rething going into biomed. It was pure memorization and the teachers seemed bored as well. I wish it was more interactive and was not just tests. Melanie deserves a solid 5.0 for being an amazing, caring, and friendly teacher. She goes the extra mile, simplifying complex topics and adding visuals to slides. Her dedication is commendable. However, the course itself falls short with excessive focus on theoretical aspects like qualitative and quantitative concepts. While understanding these is crucial, delving into intricate details seems unnecessary, limiting time for the more practical aspects like basic social statistics and quantitative methods. A better balance, with practical elements taking precedence, would enhance the course.

The teacher is amazing and enhances the course with organized excursions, but improvements could be made, such as avoiding situations where only 2.5 days are given for presentation preparation, causing undue stress. Exercise caution before enrolling in this course unless you possess enough prior knowledge of European history in the Middle Ages, Christianity, and the Netherlands. The content may be less accessible for individuals unfamiliar with Europe, particularly non-western students due to distinct cultural backgrounds. Consider incorporating additional background information, including basic introductions to Dutch geography and the distinction between regions, as the term "Holland" is commonly used in various languages. It is advisable to skip this course if lacking sufficient background or enthusiasm for the specific history and literature of the Netherlands.

Learning happened more effectively through interaction with a senior student and reading their work. Very easy for a 300 but the topic is interesting

I would only recommend this course if you really want to take the cognition track. I think this is a really good course. Breandann is an excellent computer scientist and mathematician but its so sad we as AUC bachelors students cant keep up with him very well. I wish he went a bit slower. Fantastic course tho, both teacher Breandann and Luis are helpful.
Malvin is the most helpful teacher who goes out of his way for you. The course is structured in a very interesting way as well. I would say its essential if youre taking the information track here.

A course thats full of life. Taken on a whim and it made me turn to the geology track instead of physics. Who knew lectures about rocks could be the most interesting course of the semester
